<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Independence Party takes over third place in enrollment  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The Ross Perot-inspired Independence Party
of New York, on the strength of a 17 percent increase in voter
enrollment over the past year, has become the third-largest
political party in the state, surpassing the Conservative Party.
</P>
<P>
   ''The feat was accomplished in just six years,'' an Independence
Party statement noted Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   March enrollment figures from the state Board of Elections show
the Independence Party -- the New York wing of the national Reform
Party -- had 172,471 members, up from 147,545 members a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Conservative Party had 171,496 members, up from 169,900 a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party continued to lead the way in New York with
4.96 million members with the Republican Party in second spot with
3.09 million members.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing further back in the latest figures were the Liberal
Party (92,074 members), the anti-abortion Right to Life Party
(51,392), the labor-union backed Working Families Party (4,611) and
the environmentally-oriented Green Party (3,611). There are 2.15
million voters not enrolled in any political party, so-called
independents.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Long, chairman of the state Conservative Party, said he
wasn't concerned about the growth of the Independence Party and
being shoved into fourth place.
</P>
<P>
   Long said many of those enrolling in the Independence Party
believe they are registering as independents, not joining a
political party.
</P>
<P>
   ''Is the Independence Party competition? Yes,'' Long said. ''Do
I feel we have a solid base? Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   ''If they last another four or five years, I guess they would
start developing a solid base,'' Long added. ''They also have to
get lucky enough to have another Tom Golisano run again -- someone
with a $12 million checkbook.''
</P>
<P>
   B. Thomas Golisano, a millionaire Rochester businessman close to
Perot, put the Independence Party on the map in 1994 when he
bankrolled his own run for governor and collected more than 217,000
votes, well over the 50,000 votes needed to win the party an
automatic ballot spot for the next four years in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Golisano collected more than 364,000 votes in the
governor's race to retain the Independence Party's automatic ballot
status and move it ahead of the Conservative Party on the ballot.
Ballot placement for parties in New York is based on votes
delivered for candidates running for governor. The Conservative
Party produced 348,727 votes for Republican Gov. George Pataki in
1998, or about 16,000 less than Golisano received.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki also collected more than 2.2 million votes on the GOP
ballot line to win re-election in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
