<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Last Love Canal-era building being demolished  </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NIAGARA FALLS, N.Y. (AP) -- For 20 years, the 93rd Street School
stood vacant at Love Canal, a concrete reminder of the crisis that
turned the neighborhood it served into a national symbol of
environmental disaster.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, a backhoe was reducing the brick walls to rubble,
making way for park space for the new wave of residents who have
moved into the cleaned-up and revitalized neighborhood over the
last several years.
</P>
<P>
   The school was on the outermost cusp of a danger zone created by
seeping toxic waste from a canal-turned-chemical dumpsite. The
school closed in 1980 as panicked parents moved the children it
served out of the area.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were in the third ring, this was the end of it, right
here,'' said 93rd Street resident Andrew Tomascik, referring to the
way the area was divided and evacuated after the state declared
Love Canal a threat to human health in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Whole streets of homes and a school nearest the dump site, in
the first ring, were demolished. That area remains uninhabitable.
Other areas, however, including near the school, were declared
habitable again in 1988 and homes that sat vacant for years were
refurbished and sold.
</P>
<P>
   The school is the last Love Canal-era building that will come
down.
</P>
<P>
   Tomascik, unconvinced of any danger, never left 93rd Street, a
quiet dead-end lined with maple trees and bordered by a creek. He
was not sorry to see the decaying, graffiti-marked school across
from his house, or the seven-foot fence that has surrounded it, go.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fence had three strands of barbed wire,'' he said. ''That
bothered me more than the school being empty. It looked like a
prison.''
</P>
<P>
   The school was one of several constructed in the area to
accommodate the predicted increase in enrollment due to the
post-World War II baby boom. The two-story 93rd Street School was
considered the jewel, featuring more than 53,000 square feet of
space, modern classrooms and gymnasium and a swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   As the revitalization of Love Canal, now called Black Creek
Village, began, there was talk of refurbishing the school and using
it for offices or housing, but the asbestos-laden building remained
vacant.
</P>
<P>
   Demolition is expected to be completed in the next several
weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
