<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP boss says no support for Lazio run; Congressman disagrees  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The head of New York's Republican Party says
he has talked to GOP leaders from across the state and found no
support for a possible run for the Senate by U.S. Rep. Rick Lazio
as an alternative to Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've taken the pulse of the party and there is nothing there
for Rick Lazio,'' state GOP Chairman William Powers said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would urge him to support Mayor Giuliani,'' Powers said.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Lazio said that ''a handful'' of local county
chairmen ''have called and pledged their support.'' But the Long
Island congressman said he would not identify the county chairmen
who are supporting him without checking with them first.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the Republican congressman from Long Island said the
party might be ''blowing'' the Senate race against Hillary Rodham
Clinton by lining up behind Giuliani. Lazio said he was ready to
run, if the party wanted him to.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's slight lead in the polls over Clinton has evaporated
in recent days amid criticism of his handling of the shooting last
month of the unarmed Patrick Dorismond by New York City police. In
defending the police, Giuliani made public Dorismond's criminal
record, including juvenile records that had been sealed by a court.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not trying to force this issue,'' Lazio said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the end, if it is the will of the governor and state
chairman and the majority of the county chairmen and the (state)
Senate majority leader, Joe Bruno, that they feel like their man
is, come hell or high water, Rudy Giuliani, then I will accept
that,'' Lazio said.
</P>
<P>
   The congressman said that should he not get enough support at
the state GOP's convention at the end of May to have a primary
against Giuliani, he would not try to force the issue by
circulating petitions statewide to force a September primary. But
Lazio said he felt the issue would be decided even before the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said he was concerned that he was being portrayed by some
as a disloyal Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's frustrating to be held to a higher standard than Rudy
Giuliani. There are some people supportive of Rudy Giuliani who are
critical of me raising the issue of whether or not we have the
right candidate,'' Lazio said.
</P>
<P>
   ''But somehow, they seem to have forgotten that Rudy Giuliani
was the fellow who put a knife in the back of George Pataki and not
just endorsed but stumped for (Democrat) Mario Cuomo'' in the 1994
governor's race won by Pataki, the congressman said. ''That is the
moral equivalent of me going out and endorsing and stumping for
Hillary Clinton in the last few weeks of this campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio put his Senate campaign on hold in August at the request
of Pataki. At the time, the governor called for Republicans to
support the mayor as the strongest GOP candidate.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Lazio's comments Sunday, the governor through
aides reaffirmed his support for the mayor's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Giuliani was campaigning across Long Island with
Sen. John McCain. McCain said that while he didn't know Lazio very
well, ''I do know that Mayor Giuliani has the support of the entire
Republican establishment.''
</P>
<P>
   ''If he wants to run, he should run and we'll have a primary,''
Giuliani said. ''But it's up to him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
