<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High court says state properly rescinded NYC commuter tax  </HEADLINE>
By L. ANNE NEWELL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- A court ruling that effectively killed New
York City's commuter tax could mean the 300,000 out-of-state
residents who travel to work there will be eligible to receive
around $105 million in tax refunds.
</P>
<P>
   The state Court of Appeals' ruling will also cost the city an
estimated $360 million a year in taxes it wanted to collect -- $210
million from in-state residents and $150 million from out-of-state
residents. About 500,000 New Yorkers commute to jobs in the city.
</P>
<P>
   The state's highest court ruled unanimously Tuesday that the
commuter tax, rescinded by the state for New York residents last
year, cannot be imposed on residents of other states, either.
</P>
<P>
   The court also ruled that the state Legislature and governor
properly rescinded the tax on in-state commuters in May 1999,
despite arguments to the contrary by New York City officials.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling means the tax is most likely permanently gone, since
when lawmakers approved it, they included a ''poison pill''
provision that said that if part of the law was found
unconstitutional, the entire tax would be repealed.
</P>
<P>
   An appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court is possible because the
Court of Appeals made an interpretation of rights under the U.S.
Constitution in its ruling, but lawyers for the city and state said
that would be unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   The state stopped collecting the commuter tax from in-state
residents when the rescinder went into effect July 1, 1999, said
Marc Carey, a spokesman for the state Department of Taxation and
Finance, which collects and distributes the tax for New York City.
But the state continued to tax out-of-state residents throughout
the appeals process.
</P>
<P>
   Those commuters can get their money back, but the state won't be
hunting them down. The $105 million -- about $75 million collected
from July 1 to Dec. 31 and about $30 million collected during the
first three months this year -- will be available to residents who
claim the refund on their tax forms, Carey said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There will be a concerted effort to inform people (of the
changes),'' Carey said. But, he said, it will mostly be up to
commuters to make sure they correctly fill out their tax forms if
they want to receive refunds.
</P>
<P>
   Most officials, including New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani,
said the decision did not shock them.
</P>
<P>
   ''We expected that we would lose the case so it doesn't come as
a surprise to me,'' he said during a Senate campaign appearance
Tuesday with John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Lorna Goodman, a spokeswoman for New York City's corporation
counsel, said city officials were ''extremely disappointed'' by the
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think the Legislature acted in a very punitive way toward
New York City,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the city argued that the state Legislature and
governor illegally rescinded the tax without the New York City
Council asking Albany to do so in a ''home rule'' message, but the
Court of Appeals said no such message was necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The court also agreed with lawyers for Connecticut and New
Jersey residents, as well as the state of Connecticut, that the tax
was discriminatory.
</P>
<P>
   ''The language of the statute plainly and frankly discriminates
against nonresidents,'' Wesley wrote. ''There is little doubt but
that the discrimination is so great that both its purpose and
effect are exclusionary.''
</P>
<P>
   The court ruled on the various challenges concurrently.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am absolutely delighted that this tax now is finally dead,''
Connecticut Attorney General Richard Blumenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is an absolutely historic ringing endorsement of basic
fairness and constitutional principle that forbids unfair,
discriminatory taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   New York City also argued the rescinder was improper because its
passage was designed to win votes in a hotly-contested special
election for a state Senate seat in New York's northern suburbs.
The election was won by Thomas Morahan, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   The Court of Appeals said it would be put on a ''slippery and
dangerous slope'' by making judgments about the legality of laws
based on the political motivation of Legislatures and governors.
</P>
<P>
   Carey lauded the timing of the decision and emphasized that even
if the court takes several days to file its decision, taxpayers
still have time to file their amended taxes or ask for an extension
before this year's tax deadline.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
