<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More special education students taking Regents curriculum  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- A higher percentage of special education
students failed the high school Regents exams in 1998-99 than in
the previous year, but top education officials expect performance
to improve as students adjust to the tougher standards.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most of these children had never had the opportunity to be in
this curriculum and take these tests,'' Deputy Education
Commissioner Larry Gloeckler said Tuesday. ''In the past, the only
ones taking the exams were probably the ones capable of passing
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Gloeckler said special education students -- previously not
required to take Regents tests or classes -- have a ''safety net''
in the form of the easier competency tests, which they can take if
they fail the Regents. And when competency test results are
factored in, Gloeckler said ''a vast majority'' of students are
showing improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Education Commissioner Richard Mills said during a news
conference that tougher education standards are also enabling more
special education students to seek higher education. The latest
data showed 41 percent of students who completed high school
pursued postsecondary education.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a dramatic breakthrough not only in the level of
achievement but also in the level of aspiration,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to data released by the Regents, the number of special
education students taking the English Regents exams increased from
5,731 in the 1997-98 school year to 12,516 in 1998-99. Special
education students taking the Math exams went up 52 percent, from
8,265 to 12,543.
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of those students passing the English exams fell
from 74 percent to 60 percent while only 52 percent passed the math
exams last year, compared to 60 percent the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Regents' figures released Tuesday also showed that special
education students' achievement was not high in middle and
elementary school levels.
</P>
<P>
   Among fourth graders, only 1 in 5 students who took the fourth
grade English language arts test met or exceeded performance
standards. Students did somewhat better on math tests, with 36
percent passing.
</P>
<P>
   Eighth graders fared worse, with only about 1 in 10 students
meeting or exceeding standards on the English test and nearly 66
percent placing at Level 1 -- the lowest a student can score.
</P>
<P>
   Mills said the department is working to strengthen curricula and
improve training for both regular and special education teachers to
address the problem.
</P>
<P>
   The Regents data also showed that the rate at which students are
classified in the special education category is slowing and more
special education students are now in regular classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 45 percent of students with disabilities spent 80 percent
or more of a school day in a regular classroom setting in 1998-99.
During the 1997-98 school year, it was 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Mills said when the New York data is compared with the national
data -- 45.7 percent of special education students nationwide are
now integrated -- the state is ''showing progress.''
</P>
<P>
   One issue that remains unchanged is what education officials
called an ''overrepresentation'' of black and Hispanic students in
special education. The Regents data showed that in 1998, 25 percent
of students with disabilities were black and 19 percent were
Hispanic. That's greater than their representation in the general
student population, which is 19 percent black and 17 percent
Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   Gloekler said the Education Department will be sending out
letters to schools with overrepresentation and examine their
practices before recommending corrective measures.
</P>
<P>
   There are 420,000 special education students, ages 3 to 21, in
New York. Students have to meet one of 11 disability categories --
which include both physical and mental disabilities -- set by the
Education Department to be classified in special education.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-05-00 0008 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000405.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deal reached in Albany on parameters of new state budget  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- State legislators will meet today in
conference committees to begin discussing spending not agreed to in
a ''framework'' budget agreement reached by legislative leaders and
Gov. George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers will decide specifics about a $1.2 billion, five-year
tax cut plan, how to spend $1.4 billion the Legislature will add to
Pataki's proposed budget for 2000-01 and several other loose ends.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think there are a lot of important things to put out on the
table,'' state Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver said.
</P>
<P>
   But the parameters of an agreement were reached Tuesday by
Pataki, Silver and state Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno after
weeks of private discussions, mostly by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   The three men agreed that the new state budget would total about
$78.3 billion; that $900 million of the $1.4 billion in additional
spending would be on recurring programs and $500 million on
one-time expenses; that a record $3.8 billion transportation bond
act will be placed before voters in November and that reserve funds
in the budget will be maintained at more than $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000-01 state fiscal year began on April 1 and this is the
16th straight year that a state budget will be adopted late in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno said he hoped that the Legislature could discuss, draft
and pass a new budget by Passover, the Jewish holiday that begins
this year at sunset April 19.
</P>
<P>
   Silver said the deal struck Tuesday by the state leaders bodes
well for a reasonably timely budget.
</P>
<P>
   ''At this stage of the budget, we are probably four months ahead
of where we were last year in making this agreement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there was no agreement in 1999 on how much more money
to spend over Pataki's proposal until July 16, and it took the
Legislature until Aug. 4 to finish adopting a budget. That missed
breaking by a matter of hours the record for latest budget passage
in New York, set in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has agreed to monitor the work of the conference
committees and to warn legislators when they are discussing
spending that risks being vetoed, Bruno and Silver said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The governor indicated that if we stay within these (spending)
parameters ... he'd be comfortable with that,'' Bruno said.
</P>
<P>
   Silver insisted on Pataki's participation so he could avoid a
repeat of 1998, when the Legislature developed a budget without the
governor's input and he vetoed hundreds of millions of spending
adds.
</P>
<P>
   The state spent about $73.3 billion in the just-concluded
1999-2000 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno defended the expected spending increase of more than 6
percent by saying the state has extraordinary needs to meet and had
a $1.5 billion budget surplus from the past fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   But the anti-tax group Change-New York said the increase would
be more like 7.5 percent, or a ''fiscally irresponsible'' three
times the rate of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ''Governor Pataki started out as a fiscal conservative, and now
risks becoming a bigger spender and bigger borrower than Mario
Cuomo,'' Change-New York president Tom Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   If approved by voters, the $3.8 billion bond act will help fund
a five-year, $34.2 billion capital plan for transportation with
half the money going to mass transit and the other half for road-
and bridge-building or repairs. Basically, that means New York City
and the rest of the state will be treated equally given that the
vast bulk of the mass transit money goes to the Metropolitan
Transportation Authority that runs the subways, buses and commuter
rail service in the New York City region.
</P>
<P>
   Such a division of transportation money had been demanded by
Bruno, who comes from upstate Rensselaer County.
</P>
<P>
   The individual projects to be funded by the $3.8 billion bond
act will be worked out later by legislative leaders and Pataki.
Silver and Bruno both pledged to make funding for the conversion of
Route 17 into Interstate 86 in eastern New York and across the
Southern Tier one of the bond act's highest priorities.
</P>
<P>
   The bond act would be the largest in New York state history. The
previous high was a $3.5 billion mass transit bond proposal which
was voted down in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in the Senate wanted the proposed bond act.
Democrats who rule the state Assembly said the budget will also
include a commitment to extend the Second Avenue subway along the
East Side of Manhattan, a project championed by Silver, a Manhattan
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   While conference committees will work out the details of the tax
cuts, legislative sources said reductions will probably be made in
the state's gross receipts tax and that the state's Earned Income
Tax Credit that helps the working poor will be increased.
</P>
<P>
   Silver and Bruno did agree that Pataki's proposal to have New
York participate in the multistate Powerball lottery game was not
likely to be included in the budget.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-05-00 0009 </TRAILER>
