<DOCNO> APW20000405.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Financial, legal troubles leave children's TV show in the dark  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- Once upon a time,''Pappyland'' was a
cheerful place where children learned to draw.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there's trouble in Pappyland.
</P>
<P>
   Once one of public television's most promising children's shows
when it was broadcast on The Learning Channel and more than 140
public television stations, ''Pappyland'' has faded from the
screen, mired in a tangle of disputes, failed deals and legal
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, even the show's flagship station, WCNY in
Syracuse, stopped airing it -- although station officials said it
was because children were tiring of the repeat broadcasts. However,
on Wednesday, lawyers for WCNY will be in state Supreme Court for a
hearing on their lawsuit that the show's producers owe the station
$118,000 in royalties.
</P>
<P>
   A shortage of revenue is at the root of the problems, say the
show's creators. It created a trail of bad debts, legal troubles
and accusations of poor management that have strained ties between
production partners.
</P>
<P>
   ''The reality is, if we had knowledge of what the industry's
standards are as far as dollars, we probably wouldn't have tried
it,'' said Executive Producer Eric J. Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   ''Pappyland'' grew out of a character created in 1985 by
free-lance artist Michael Cariglio called Pappy Drewitt, who taught
children ages 3-8 how to draw. In 1993, Craftsman &AMP; Scribe's
Creative Workshop, a Liverpool company, produced the first 26
episodes. The half-hour show used colorful characters and songs
with its drawing lessons.
</P>
<P>
   The program became an instant hit with children and began
national distribution after one year. At the peak of its
popularity, producers said they were receiving 2,000 drawings from
children each week.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, ''Pappyland'' was picked up by The Learning Channel and
named one of the top 10 new children's shows by TV Guide.
</P>
<P>
   Like many companies that produce children's shows, Craftsman &AMP;
Scribe's gave away its programming to public television in hopes
that kids would fall in love with the show and demand Pappy
products.
</P>
<P>
   Good ratings and critical acclaim drew interest from several
companies about ''Pappyland'' art supplies, books, dolls and other
products.
</P>
<P>
   The company raised $8 million from private investors but it
wasn't enough to convince manufacturers that the company had the
financial muscle to properly promote ''Pappyland'' merchandise.
Most of that money was spent for production costs and other
expenses to get the show off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   So six years after its premier, ''Pappyland'' has yet to make a
profit, which company executives blame on the inability of
Craftsman &AMP; Scribe's to sign a single merchandise deal, except for
home videos.
</P>
<P>
   And even that deal has gone sour. Hallmark Entertainment, which
bought the home-video rights for 15 years, says it has no immediate
plans to put ''Pappyland'' tapes in stores, despite paying the
company a $1 million advance two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have other products in the pipeline we have to get out
first,'' said Marty DeGrazia, senior vice president for
distribution for Hallmark Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Only three stations -- WLIW in New York City, WMTP in San
Francisco and WLVT in Allentown, Pa. -- continue to show
''Pappyland.'' No new shows have been made since 1997 and Cariglio
has vowed not to tape any more shows under current management.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Craftsman &AMP; Scribe's thought it had a buyer but the
deal collapsed. Then, the company had to pay out $200,000 to
co-creator Jon Nappa, who threatened to auction off his copyrights
and trademarks to the show unless he received his promised share of
the royalties.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the problems, Roberts said there are those at Craftsman
&AMP; Scribe's who remain optimistic that they can turn things around.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to produce fresh episodes of ''Pappyland,'' as
well as a spinoff series, ''Pappy's Pad,'' that would teach drawing
to older children. It is pursuing investors, Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   To help steer Craftsman &AMP; Scribe's down the right path, the
company in late 1998 hired Nyhl Henson, the first general manager
of the Nickelodeon children's television network. Henson has spent
the past year cutting costs and restructuring the company in
preparation for raising additional money through a public stock
sale or attracting a major investor.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's a story that ultimately will have a happy
ending,'' Roberts said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-05-00 0009 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
