<DOCNO> APW20000405.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 00:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Klink Wins Pa. Senate Primary  </HEADLINE>
By CLAUDE R. MARX, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Rep. Ron Klink won a six-way race Tuesday
for the Democratic nomination to challenge freshman Republican Sen.
Rick Santorum.
</P>
<P>
   With 84 percent of the precincts reporting, Klink had 42
percent, or 264,243 votes, while state Sen. Allyson Y. Schwartz had
26 percent, or 160,628 votes, and former state Labor Secretary
Thomas P. Foley had 24 percent, or 149,432 votes. Three
lesser-known candidates split the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Klink, 48, is well known in the western part of the state
because of his four terms in Congress and his years as a news
anchor on a Pittsburgh TV station.
</P>
<P>
   Santorum had no competition for the Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Klink, Foley and Schwartz largely refrained from attacking each
other, choosing instead to take shots at Santorum, a key player on
welfare reform and the effort to ban what abortion foes call
''partial birth abortions.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the final week of the primary campaign, the candidates
went after each another more sharply, with Schwartz criticizing
Klink's opposition to abortion and gun control.
</P>
<P>
   Santorum has moderated his views since arriving in the Senate in
1995 as a conservative rebel after beating Democratic Sen. Harris
Wofford, who won a special election to succeed the late Republican
Sen. John Heinz.
</P>
<P>
   The last Democrat elected to a full term in the Senate was
Joseph Clark in 1962.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-05-00 0030 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000405.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 00:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diamondbacks 6, Phillies 4  </HEADLINE>
By BOB BAUM, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- Randy Johnson is back at it.
</P>
<P>
   The Cy Young winner struck out 10 in 8 2-3 innings Tuesday night
and the Arizona Diamondbacks opened defense of their NL West title
with a 6-4 win over the Philadelphia Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson (1-0) gave up four hits, including home runs by Scott
Rolen and Desi Relaford.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who led the majors in complete games last season with
12, was pulled after 133 pitches with a 6-2 lead. But with closer
Matt Mantei on the disabled list because of a sore shoulder, the
Arizona bullpen struggled to get the last out.
</P>
<P>
   Russ Springer relieved with a runner on first and gave up a walk
and an RBI single to Relaford. Dan Plesac took over and allowed an
RBI single to pinch-hitter Bobby Abreu.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Holmes then relieved and retired Doug Glanville on a line
drive for a save.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Finley, Luis Gonzalez and Damian Miller hit home runs off
Andy Ashby (0-1).
</P>
<P>
   Miller's three-run homer gave Arizona the lead in the second
against Ashby, acquired in the offseason from San Diego. Miller
later doubled.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez hit a two-run, 426-foot blast in the sixth. One out
later, Finley hit a solo homer high off the left-field foul pole to
make it 6-1. Finley finished 4-for-4.
</P>
<P>
   Ashby, Philadelphia's opening-night pitcher because Curt
Schilling is still rehabilitating from shoulder surgery, allowed
six runs and eight hits in six innings.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 3-0 in eight opening-day starts, didn't allow a hit
until Mike Lieberthal's one-out double in the fourth. Philadelphia
cut the lead to 3-1 on Rolen's home run in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who walked two, benefited from some slick fielding.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth, second baseman Jay Bell made a diving stop to his
right and threw out Rico Brogna from his knees. Kevin Sefcik
followed with a liner off Johnson's glove and Bell grabbed it on a
short hop, then threw to first in time for the out.
Notes: Abreu did not start because of a sore right elbow. Manager
Terry Francona said Abreu would have been out of the lineup against
Johnson anyway. ... Arizona left-handed reliever Greg Swindell will
leave Wednesday to attend the funeral of his father, who lost a
long battle with cancer. ... After going through a 2-for-44 slump
last season and losing his job at first base, the Diamondbacks'
Travis Lee started in right field and had an opposite-field single
in his first at-bat. ... Arizona had six left-handed batters in the
starting lineup. ... Paid attendance was 44,298 and total
attendance was 46,438, some 2,500 short of capacity, in part
because the Lakers were playing the Suns a block away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-05-00 0037 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000405.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 00:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 12:45 EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, April 5, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mori Elected Japan's Prime Minister
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's Parliament elected Yoshiro Mori as the new prime
minister Wednesday, ending a political crisis created by the sudden collapse of
Keizo Obuchi, who was on life support after suffering a stroke. Mori, a former
trade minister, was elected in the lower house vote following his installment
earlier in the day as president of Japan's ruling Liberal Democratic Party.
Obuchi held both posts, but has been in a coma since his collapse on Sunday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nasdaq, Dow Bruised but Recover
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Nasdaq composite index and Dow Jones industrials on
Tuesday each dropped more than 500 points before recovering in what was Wall
Street's most volatile day. Analysts said they couldn't point to any one factor
in today's massive selling, but most said the purge was long overdue. The Nasdaq
was down 574.57 points at midday, then clawed back to finish down 74.79 at
4,148.89. The Dow rose 196.31 points this morning before diving to a loss of
504.15 early Tuesday afternoon. It finished down 57.09 at 11,164.84.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mori Elected Japan Ruling Party Head
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Yoshiro Mori was elected president of Japan's ruling party
Wednesday, replacing Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi, who was on life support after
suffering a massive stroke. The full Parliament was to meet later Wednesday to
approve Mori as prime minister. Obuchi held both posts, but has been in a coma
since his sudden collapse on Sunday. The entire Cabinet resigned Tuesday, paving
the way for the quick selection of a new prime minister. Mori is expected to be
named to that spot later Wednesday and a Cabinet could be installed shortly
after that.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japan, N. Korea Start Normalization Talks
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PYONGYANG, North Korea (AP) -- North Korean and Japanese negotiators on
Wednesday began their first talks in eight years on establishing diplomatic
relations. Both sides said they would try to bridge their many differences,
including Tokyo's concerns over a North Korean ballistic missile that was fired
over Japan in 1998. The two countries have never had diplomatic relations.
Similar normalization talks between Japan and North Korea broke down in 1992,
and swift progress now is not expected. Pyongyang needs help from richer
countries to feed its impoverished people and modernize its decaying
infrastructure.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Anti-Castro Demonstrators Get Rough
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Anti-Castro demonstrators surged through a police barricade and
formed a human chain around Cuban refugee Elian Gonzalez's house on Tuesday as
rumors swept the crowd that the U.S. government was coming to take the boy away.
Miami police stood by and watched. The protesters broke through after Elian's
father was issued a U.S. visa to come to the United States and be reunited with
his son. They vowed to resist any attempt by the U.S. government to take the
6-year-old boy away from Miami relatives.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Genetic Approach To Cancer Promising
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- For the first time, scientists have reported success
against cancer using an intriguing technique called antisense technology, which
zeros in on a cancer gene to halt malignancy at its roots. Researchers have been
experimenting with this approach for more than a decade, but on Tuesday they
described the first cases in which the technique actually seemed to slow a
deadly malignancy. Testing is still early, and doctors do not know whether the
treatment will pan out. But a large international study is starting to settle
this.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Down at Midday
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell Wednesday amid increasing worries about wild
swings on Wall Street and political uncertainty at home. The Nikkei Stock
Average shed 213.36 points to 20,381.57 at the end of the morning session.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Diana Ross, New Supremes to Tour
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Thirty years after Diana Ross left the Supremes, the sexy
diva of '60s pop is back with her girls. In pink leather and lipstick to match,
Ross strutted into a news conference on Tuesday at Grand Central Terminal where
she and two new backup singers announced plans for a U.S. tour featuring the
group's timeless Motown hits. They're all Supremes -- Ross, Lynda Laurence and
Scherrie Payne -- but it's far from a reunion. The trio has never performed on
stage together.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Magic Zap Spurs 107-97
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- John Amaechi scored 24 points and Darrell Armstrong had
23 Tuesday night as the Orlando Magic beat the San Antonio Spurs 107-97 for
their season-high seventh straight victory. Chucky Atkins, who had 16 points,
led a fourth-quarter surge by reserves who helped Orlando pull away for good.
The rookie had five points and three assists in the 13-4 run that put the Magic
up 93-78 with just under six minutes to go. The Spurs, who got 30 points from
David Robinson, cut their deficit to 97-91 with 1:44 left. But Amaechi made a
one-hand runner on the baseline and Atkins followed with a clutch jumper to put
the Magic back in control.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by ANDREW DAMPF
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-05-00 0047 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
