<HEADLINE> Grizzlies 102, Rockets 100  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- Mike Bibby made a layup at
the buzzer and scored 15 of his 27 points in the fourth quarter as
the Vancouver Grizzlies erased an 18-point second-half deficit to
beat the Houston Rockets 102-100 Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Shareef Abdur-Rahim added 21 for Vancouver, which won only its
second game since Feb. 26 -- a span of 18 contests.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Steve Francis scored 30 for Houston, including a driving
layup with 5.9 seconds left to tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   The only excitement in the first three quarters for the 12,474
fans came in the form of booing Francis, whose second game in
Vancouver since forcing the Grizzlies into making a three-team,
10-player trade last summer was no less hospitable than his first
outing Nov. 29.
</P>
<P>
   The Grizzlies were forced to go to a smaller lineup earlier than
usual when forward Othella Harrington was ejected by referee Bob
Delaney at 7:45 of the first period. Harrington was given a delay
of game warning for failing to leave the court quickly during a
substitution, which was followed by the quick ejection.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets were constantly left open in the post, making 10 of
13 shots to end the second period. Houston had an 8-0 run to open
the third, followed later by a dunk by Francis over Vancouver
7-footer Bryant Reeves, to open a 71-53 lead midway through the
period.
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver responded with an 12-4 spurt to start the fourth and
eventually took the lead at 89-87 with 5:43 left.
</P>
<P>
   Bibby shot 5-of-8 in the final period to key the Vancouver
comeback. The Vancouver point guard also had 10 assists, his fourth
straight game in double digits, a franchise record.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Harrington's ejection resulted in the first minutes since
Mar. 21 for Cherokee Parks of Vancouver. ...Francis started play
leading the Rockets in scoring, assists and steals. If he finishes
the season in the same position, he will become only the fourth
Houston player in franchise history to do so, following Calvin
Murphy (1975), Allen Leavell (1983) and Clyde Drexler (1998). ...
The Grizzlies wrap up a franchise-high nine-game homestand Thursday
with the start of a home-and-home series with Portland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
