<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Another day, another uphill battle to ban soft money  </HEADLINE>
By CAREN BENJAMIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate's leading opponent of campaign
finance reform has finally met a bill on the subject he is willing
to consider -- if not necessarily vote for.
</P>
<P>
   And that makes Rep. Marty Meehan nervous.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the bill Senate Rules and Administration
Committee Chairman Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., is holding hearings on
doesn't address the real issue, according to Meehan, D-Mass., who
is set to testify before McConnell's committee today.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't think of anything that would make the American people
more cynical about Congress and politicians than if we were to pass
a so-called reform bill that actually did little or nothing to
reduce the role of money in politics.''
</P>
<P>
   There's good news too, said Rep. Christopher Shays, a Republican
who with Meehan is the lead sponsors of a bill banning ''soft
money'' -- unlimited donations by corporations and unions to
political parties.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only reason Mitch McConnell is having this hearing is he
knows the American people want the system to be reformed. It's an
affirmation of what he basically has denied. He has always said the
public doesn't care,'' Shays said.
</P>
<P>
   The Shays-Meehan bill mirrors a measure introduced by Sens.
Russell Feingold, D-Wisc., and John McCain, R-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell has engineered filibusters to keep that bill from
getting a hearing on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell contends banning soft money contributions would
violate constitutional free speech protections and give Democrats
and unfair advantage.
</P>
<P>
   But he has suggested he may be slightly flexible if a measure
crosses his path that would also raise individual campaign
contribution limits.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Chuck Hagel, a Nebraska Republican, is pushing a bill that
would limit to $60,000 per contributor soft money donations to
national political. The measure would also raise from $1,000 to
$3,000 the current ceiling on donations by individuals to
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   In late March McConnell launched a series of hearings on
campaign finance reform which he promises to end with a May 17 vote
on the Hagel bill -- though a Hagel spokesperson said McConnell
won't vote for it in its current form.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem with Hagel's bill is that it doesn't cap
soft money donations to state political parties, Shays and Meehan
said. Combined with the increase in allowable individual donates,
it would end up adding money to the political process, not taking
it away, Meehan complained.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hard money is the most accountable way to contribute to
campaigns,'' said Hagel spokesman Deb Fiddelke, who also pointed
out that the $1,000 figure was set in 1974 and the $3,000 is less
than consumer price increases between then and now.
</P>
<P>
   As for concerns about the state party loophole, ''we really just
wanted to get the ball rolling, to get discussion going on the
Senate floor,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
