<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Changes Shake Funeral Industry  </HEADLINE>
By JEFF DONN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   AGAWAM, Mass. (AP) -- The ad looks like plenty of others: a list
of products, prices and a promise to nip off an extra 5 percent if
you find a better deal anywhere in town. Major credit cards
accepted, of course.
</P>
<P>
   But this ad isn't selling televisions or love seats. It's a
funeral home peddling caskets and services.
</P>
<P>
   Though the sales pitch rattled some competitors, it reflects
deep changes reshaping the funeral home trade, which was long
handed down largely from father to son as a business and way of
life.
</P>
<P>
   Large corporate ownership, more aggressive sales and marketing,
new lines of business, and consumer demands for more choice are
finally chipping away at the accepted dictates of social taste and
religious orthodoxy that ruled the industry for generations.
</P>
<P>
   ''Years ago, people would purchase a funeral like it was their
last gift to the deceased. Today, people purchase funerals for the
benefit they receive,'' said Frank Forestiere, president of both
the Massachusetts Funeral Directors Association and Forestiere
Family Funeral Homes.
</P>
<P>
   A few decades ago, family funeral homes nearly all relied on
familiarity and word-of-mouth for business in more stable towns and
city neighborhoods. But the growth of suburbs, a faster and more
mobile way of life, and a more culturally diverse and secular
society all combined to shake the roots of the staid industry.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the past, funeral directors didn't have to advertise,''
said Kelly Smith, a spokesman for the National Funeral Directors
Association.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Forestiere decided to take a new approach. He placed
a full-page newspaper ad that took the unusual step of including a
list of prices and a discount offer for a funeral home in
Northampton. He claimed the ''lowest priced funeral and cremation
services'' in town, ranging from $1,095 to $1,995. The ad showed
six caskets and cremation boxes ranging from $60 to $1,395.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a crass ad,'' sniffed Robert Czelusniak, the president of
a Northampton competitor, Czelusniak Funeral Home.
</P>
<P>
   Industry sources say such aggressive advertising has made
inroads in places like Florida and California with large
populations and many senior citizens. But in the more genteel
climate of western Massachusetts, such a discount offer was
virtually unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Byron Blanchard, an activist who helps protect the funeral
buyer's interests at the Boston-based Memorial Society, praised the
ad for including prices.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most people haven't the slightest idea what is a fair price,
so they are in no position to bargain or walk,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After Forestiere ran his ad, Czelusniak fired off letters to
dozens of independent funeral homes, hoping to seize on the ad to
spur opposition to big corporate ownership.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the Wall Street firms control too much, then I see service
disappearing too much and greed and money being the crux,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The concern over corporate control of the industry comes as
consoldiation creeps into an industry that not too long ago was
almost exclusively family-run, with the business handed down from
generation to generation.
</P>
<P>
   Forestiere's grandfather opened the family's first funeral home
in 1905 as an independent business and the Forestieres expanded to
six homes. The company, however, has merged with Carriage Services,
which owns about 180 sites.
</P>
<P>
   Four big, publicly held companies now control 13 percent of the
country's roughly 22,000 funeral homes -- an $11 billion annual
business, according to the National Funeral Directors Association.
Though most other companies are small and often family-owned, many
own multiple sites.
</P>
<P>
   Some predict more consolidation because group owners can buy
more cheaply, give more benefits to workers and better handle the
heavier regulatory burden now imposed by government.
</P>
<P>
   Other changes have refashioned the funeral ceremony itself.
</P>
<P>
   Strains of Elton John and Celine Dion have taken a place beside
Bach in the repertory of funeral music. One trucker's family found
comfort in seeing his rig and dog stationed in the parking lot at a
Forestiere funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Many funerals are planned and even paid for long before the
death, making arrangements easier for families often separated by
thousands of miles.
</P>
<P>
   To adapt, Forestiere is building a Web site where customers will
be able to order flowers and sign condolence books. He hopes
eventually to join in the industry's latest technological
innovation: virtual funerals Web cast for far-flung relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ''I remember when we were married 31 years ago,'' said
Forestiere's wife, Lila. ''Every funeral was the same; only the
name was different. Now, no two funerals are the same.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-05-00 0123 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000405.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coke: Fewer Job Cuts Are Expected  </HEADLINE>
By SKIP WOLLENBERG, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Coca-Cola Co.'s restructuring program will
result in 800 fewer job cuts than initially forecast but officials
expect it will still help the soft drink giant achieve long-term
annual growth of 15 percent in earnings per share.
</P>
<P>
   The company also reaffirmed Tuesday it expects to sell 7 percent
to 8 percent more cases of soft drinks and other beverages globally
each year over the long term despite slower growth this year.
</P>
<P>
   The volume and earnings projections surprised some analysts who
had expected Coca-Cola would revise expectations slightly lower
growth because of competition at home from bottled tea, water and
fruit juices and overseas economic uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think these are ambitious growth goals for the company and
challenging ones to meet,'' said Marc Cohen, beverage analyst for
Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., who attended a nearly five-hour presentation
by Coke officials at a New York hotel.
</P>
<P>
   But chairman and chief executive Douglas Daft told the analysts
''we couldn't in all honesty'' project lower volume growth given
the confidence he has in recent changes in the company's approach
and its ambitious marketing plans.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking over as chairman and CEO in February, Daft has
decentralized control of the company's soft drink operations,
giving local executives more authority to develop products and
packages and marketing programs that fit their markets. He said
that should spur growth.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola had estimated in January that its restructuring
program would result in the elimination of 6,000 of the company's
29,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Chief financial officer Gary Fayard said the program should be
completed by the end of April and that it is now expected only
5,200 jobs will be eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the company still expects cost savings of $150
million to $200 million from the restructuring this year and $300
million in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings per share growth of 15 percent is at the lower end of
the company's recent long-range targets while the 7 percent to 8
percent volume increase forecast is in line with what the company
had been forecasting.
</P>
<P>
   During the meeting, executives of Coke operations around the
world described what they are doing to appeal to local tastes and
boost growth.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, for example, Coca-Cola sells more than 60 different
varieties of its canned Georgia Coffee beverage, which is a top
seller, while fruit-flavored drinks have been developed that are
popular in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Coke's long-term volume targets were announced,
president Jack Stahl conceded that growth will only be 3 percent in
the first quarter and 5 percent to 6 percent this year, partly as
the result of recent price increases.
</P>
<P>
   But Fayard said sales momentum has been increasing each month so
far this year and that he is confident sales volume will accelerate
enough in the last three quarters to provide 5 percent to 6 percent
growth for the full year.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead, Stahl said will continue to back its flagship
Coca-Cola and other core carbonated brands with aggressive
marketing programs.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said Coke will look for incremental growth by
backing more non-carbonated drinks such as bottled water, tea and
fruit drinks in various markets. And he said the company also plans
an Internet marketing program aimed at teens but declined to give
more details.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
