<HEADLINE> Butler Coach Ready for Nebraska  </HEADLINE>
By JEFF TUCKER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Butler coach Barry Collier is set to become
the new coach at Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   Collier met with his players late Tuesday after returning from
Lincoln, Neb., and it appears the official announcement will come
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Players leaving the 90-minute meeting at Hinkle Fieldhouse would
not say what Collier told them, but junior guard LaVall Jordan
said, ''We can't dwell on the fact. We're not mad at him for
leaving, but we have to move on as a team,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Butler athletic director John Parry would not confirm Collier's
departure, but said, ''I think Barry did a great job and we're
poised to keep on going. It's really a Nebraska announcement. It's
really their announcement.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cornhuskers fired Danny Nee last month after an 11-19
season, but athletic director Bill Byrne would say only: ''I'm not
talking about the coach. ''You guys know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Parry said he knows it's difficult for Butler, an Indianapolis
school with an enrollment of 3,800, to compete with larger schools
to keep quality coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's all about judging if it's the right job,'' Parry said.
</P>
<P>
   Collier guided Butler to 20 wins in each of the last four
seasons. This past season the Bulldogs went 23-8 and advanced to
the NCAA tournament for the third time in four years, only to lose
in the first round to Florida on a last-second shot in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The Gators went on to the championship game, losing to Michigan
State on Monday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
