<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan, North Korea Begin Talks  </HEADLINE>
By JOJI SAKURAI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PYONGYANG, North Korea (AP) -- As North Korea and Japan began
talks Wednesday aimed at establishing diplomatic relations, the
North demanded compensation for Japan's previous colonial rule over
the Korean Peninsula, an official said.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides had expressed optimism early Wednesday before the
start of their first such talks in eight years.
</P>
<P>
   But during the opening two-hour session, the North repeated its
long-standing demand regarding the widespread suffering caused by
Japan during its brutal 1910-1945 colonial rule over Korea, the
Japanese official told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The official, who asked not to be named, said Japan's chief
negotiator, Kojiro Takano, responded by repeating Japan's 1995
apology, but again rejected any compensation.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea's top negotiator, Jong Thae-kwa, did not appear to
be angered by the response, and the talks continued in a serious,
businesslike manner, the Japanese official said.
</P>
<P>
   Many other obstacles also remain, including Tokyo's concerns
over a North Korean ballistic missile that was fired over Japan in
1998, creating an outcry across the Asia-Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   The two countries have never had diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
   Similar normalization talks between Japan and North Korea broke
down in 1992, and swift progress now is not expected.
</P>
<P>
   A second round of negotiations is to be held in Tokyo and a
third in Beijing or another country.
</P>
<P>
   In reviving the talks, Tokyo hopes that engaging the North will
help draw the Stalinist state out of its isolation and boost
stability in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Pyongyang needs help to feed its impoverished people and
modernize its decaying infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Tokyo has promised to resume food aid frozen since the North
stunned the region by launching a ballistic missile that flew over
Japan in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Although Pyongyang denies kidnapping Japanese, it has promised
to investigate whether there are any ''missing'' Japanese citizens
within its borders.
</P>
<P>
   Japan says it intends to raise the question of kidnapped
citizens in this round of talks. It is reportedly refusing further
food aid to the North unless progress is made on the issue. Tokyo
also plans to pressure Pyongyang to halt its missile program.
</P>
<P>
   By some estimates, North Korea's economy shrank by one-half or
more during the 1990s, after the collapse of trading partners in
the Soviet Union and eastern Europe. A deadly famine also has
forced it to appeal for outside food aid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-05-00 0129 </TRAILER>
