<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Old Umbrella Shop Closing  </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Since it opened 134 years ago, a tiny shop
facing Carnegie Hall has kept many people from getting all wet --
from U.S. presidents to Charlie Chaplin.
</P>
<P>
   Uncle Sam Umbrellas and Canes, believed to be New York's last
umbrella speciality shop, was slowly folding on this humid,
overcast Manhattan Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''You don't want to be the last village blacksmith,'' said Henry
Schwartz as he helped his wife sell the remaining inventory.
</P>
<P>
   He was forced to lock the door as shoppers swept into the long,
tiny shop on West 57th Street, unfurling umbrellas that have made
America's heads turn from coast to coast.
</P>
<P>
   At $10 to $350 -- with up to 60 percent off in these last days
before the store closes April 11 -- there seemed to be an umbrella
for every type of cloud: Polka dots. Stripes. Paisley. Speckled.
Floral. Some sporting world maps and others cartoon characters. And
plain old black -- New York's favorite color.
</P>
<P>
   Sam has sold bright red umbrellas built for two, ones that
looked like pointy-topped pagodas and the GustBuster -- vented to
keep it from turning inside out.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was so sad to hear Uncle Sam was closing,'' said Irene
Kelvasa, a regular since 1965.
</P>
<P>
   She came for the service no other New York store offered: a man
who made and repaired umbrellas.
</P>
<P>
   ''Your umbrella is ready!'' repairman Gilbert Center announced
as he appeared from the workshop with her beige Isotoner.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's like a doctor. He takes one look and knows what's
wrong,'' said Kelvasa, a nurse. ''Mine wouldn't stay open. And when
it comes to umbrellas -- that's very important.''
</P>
<P>
   Her tastes run simple: only solid beige or green above her head
when it rains.
</P>
<P>
   Other customers reached for a $350 English model, with a
cigarette lighter concealed in its polished malacca wood handle. It
was made by Brigg, the official umbrella maker to the royal family.
</P>
<P>
   The shop harbored as many stories as there were rainfalls during
its 13 decades of existence. Franklin D. Roosevelt used a cane
bought here, after his mother haggled over its price. John
Steinbeck would stop by just to chat, and in recent years, Harrison
Ford was a regular.
</P>
<P>
   Uncle Sam was started in 1866 by a German immigrant, Adolph
Simon, who named it after his son Sam, the grandfather of the
current owner, Sandra Schwartz.
</P>
<P>
   The shop is closing because the building that houses it has
changed hands, and she can't afford to move.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, ''people don't seem to care about umbrellas anymore,''
Schwartz said.
</P>
<P>
   But on this Tuesday in the spring of 2000, they dug into the
stockpiles of umbrellas strewn everywhere as if mining gold. This
was the last of a more genteel era.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, Uncle Sam put soul into its parasols, and theater
into umbrellas used on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   And on a workbench in the back was a machine used to carve
canes.
</P>
<P>
   Uncle Sam canes have propped up some fancy walkers, including
Sammy Davis Jr., and presidents Theodore Roosevelt, Harry Truman
and John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Chaplin bought his bamboo ones here.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy purchased the fine wooden sticks he used
behind-the-scenes to prop up his ailing back. ''But he never let
himself be photographed with it,'' said Henry Schwartz.
</P>
<P>
   Leland Black, a market researcher, walked his walk with a German
ebony stick, then a pure silver-handled one.
</P>
<P>
   ''The silver one is for the evening. We'll go to the opera with
it,'' said his wife, Paula Black, as the Brooklyn couple headed for
the cashier.
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't much left on the nicked beige shelves that lined
the shop except memories.
</P>
<P>
   And there was an especially delicious one.
</P>
<P>
   ''Jack Benny had a tiny cane made that he kept in his mouth -- to
keep himself from smoking,'' said Schwartz. ''He sucked on it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-05-00 0138 </TRAILER>
