<DOCNO> APW20000405.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investors Confused by Markets  </HEADLINE>
By BRUCE MEYERSON, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- At the most sickening moments of this week's
stock plunge, the Nasdaq composite index was down nearly 30 percent
from the record levels reached just three weeks ago -- and still
showing a gain of 65 percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   These are confusing times for investors, even the ones who've
been around awhile.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years, they've grappled with real concerns like
a global financial crisis, potential computer disruptions from the
Year 2000 date change, and the persistent threat of domestic
inflation and rising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   But now, with economists forecasting continued prosperity at
home and continued recovery abroad, investors are facing a new
challenge in trying to assign specific values to a technological
revolution with few obvious limitations.
</P>
<P>
   Most market observers agreed that Tuesday's slide of more than
500 points by both the Nasdaq and the Dow Jones industrial average
was a textbook case of panic selling, the type of market spasm that
usually prompts a sharp rebound, much like the one that repaired
most of Tuesday's damage by the close of trading.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a fairly classic capitulation day,'' said Richard A.
Dickson, a market analyst at Scott &AMP; Stringfellow Inc. in Richmond,
Va., noting how investors even began abandoning cherished names
such as Intel or Cisco Systems, blue-chip companies with real
profits and real growth prospects in the Internet revolution. ''The
psychology was, 'Let me out at any price. It's never going up
again, let me out before I lose all my money.'''
</P>
<P>
   Based on past market behavior, Dickson and other analysts expect
the rebound to continue over the near-term as investors scope out
the sudden discounts on both the blue chips and the more
speculative names that have led the Nasdaq moonshot of the past
year.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, however, they find few historic comparisons to
predict what will come next as investors try to determine an
appropriate value for the technology companies that are forging a
new Internet-based economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''A serious investor looking at this environment would say that
this blowoff is a chance to buy quality stocks,'' said Joe
Battipaglia, chief investment strategist at Gruntal &AMP; Co., arguing
that the underlying fundamentals of the new economy and the old are
far superior to the backdrop behind steep market declines of the
past.
</P>
<P>
   ''This particular correction has the same feel as the one in the
summer and fall of 1998, which was the bottom of the Asian
financial crisis,'' said Battipaglia. ''But that was more
potentially dangerous than this today, because at that time the
world economic model was under great strain.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, he said, while this week's decline was ''not much
different from the big one in 1987 -- sharp, steep, quick,''
interest rates are not soaring like they were before the infamous
market crash that year. ''Nowadays, the economy's growing, company
profits are soaring and inflation is invisible.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, even if the economic backdrop is more sound these days,
this week's sudden decline may make some investors hesitant about
plowing back into the market, especially those who've been wooed
into the market by its stunning gains.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a lot of people who have been in the market for a year
or two years who have never experienced this kind of wrenching
loss,'' said Dickson. ''People who saw their portfolio values melt
away much faster than they ever seriously considered are going to
be a little more reluctant to chase these stocks higher.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
