<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 01:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain returns to campaign -- for 'soul mate' Giuliani  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE KELLMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHPORT, N.Y. (AP) -- Mayor Rudolph Giuliani didn't support him
for his party's presidential nomination, but, nevertheless, Sen.
John McCain visited the politically crucial New York City suburbs
to give the mayor a boost in his tight U.S. Senate race with
Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need more mild-mannered, even-tempered individuals like
Rudy and myself who will never rock the boat or say anything that's
controversial in nature,'' the Arizona senator cracked during a
town hall meeting in Northport, Long Island, on Tuesday. ''I look
forward to having a soul mate in the United States Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   In shirt sleeves, Giuliani took a page from McCain's book when
he was told by an audience member that Clinton alleges that the
Republican mayor lacks the proper temperament to do his job in the
scholarly Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ''Did she say that? Shut up! Sit down!'' Giuliani roared at his
questioner, a twinkle in his eye.
</P>
<P>
   When the laughter died down, he acknowledged being ''very
forceful in my advocacy.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Maybe Washington needs a little of that,'' he added, calling
McCain his hero.
</P>
<P>
   As for McCain, he predicted Giuliani would be an ''instant star
in many respects'' if elected.
</P>
<P>
   Basking in McCain's glow, Giuliani used Tuesday's event to
criticize Clinton for spending unregulated, or soft, contributions
on her campaign against him -- even though the mayor is raising soft
money as well.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he can support campaign finance reform and at the same
time raise unregulated campaign funds, Giuliani replied: ''I have
to be competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Giuliani has raised $19 million while Clinton has
collected about $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   Though McCain, a soft-money opponent, said last month that he
planned to raise objections to Giuliani's use of soft money, he
blessed Giuliani's stance on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think you can give up a financial disadvantage to the
tune of millions and millions of dollars, plus the independent
campaigns that are coming on,'' McCain said. ''We know already that
the trial lawyers are going to spend millions of dollars in, quote,
'independent campaigns.' So I can't expect Rudy Giuliani to give up
this enormous disadvantage, but I know he's committed to campaign
finance reform and I don't see that kind of commitment in a number
of my colleagues who presently serve in the United States Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, however, questioned whether Giuliani truly supports
reform, pointing out that the mayor vetoed the city's campaign
finance law in 1998 and raised illegal contributions during his
1997 re-election campaign, for which he was fined $240,000 by the
city's Campaign Finance Board.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once again New Yorkers are getting double talk instead of
straight talk from Rudy Giuliani,'' Clinton campaign spokesman
Howard Wolfson said in a statement. ''Does John McCain know that
the mayor broke campaign finance laws and vetoed campaign finance
reform?''
</P>
<P>
   The city's law, which capped spending by mayoral candidates to
$10 million and increased the amount of public matching funds for
candidates, was enacted only after the City Council overrode
Giuliani's veto.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, however, has a substantial campaign finance law of his
own on the books: In 1998, voters approved a Giuliani-sponsored
campaign finance referendum that banned corporate contributions
from city elections.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is scheduled to make similar campaign appearances for
candidates including Mark Nielsen, who is challenging Rep. Jim
Maloney in Connecticut, in an effort to entice the moderate,
independent-minded voters who formed the core of McCain's support
during his presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   ''McCain can get women to vote for him, which a lot of
Republicans can't,'' said event organizer Ray Maloney, a veteran
who voted for Texas Gov. George W. Bush only because he thought
McCain couldn't win the primary. ''That means a lot to this
party.''
</P>
<P>
   But not on McCain's schedule is a similar show of support for
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor's name came up only in passing during the
hour-long town hall meeting -- and then, only in response to
questions.
</P>
<P>
   When one man asked how the GOP could hope to win the White House
''without supporting Governor Bush,'' McCain replied: ''I support
the nominee of my party; I've had conversations with Governor
Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani mentioned Bush's campaign in answer to a question about
whether Republicans can hope to win New York state in the
presidential contest. The mayor said he tells the Bush campaign
that Ronald Reagan won the state in 1980 and 1984 and Bush can,
too, if he can attract moderate Republicans and Democrats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
