<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kosovo Town Want Guerrilla Back  </HEADLINE>
By DANICA KIRKA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   VITINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Huddled beneath a mural of Kosovo's
war heroes, Xhavit Hasani's friends talked about nothing else
besides getting him home.
</P>
<P>
   Hasani is a war hero himself in this little town tucked into the
southeast corner of Kosovo, known for smuggling weapons and medical
supplies to the Kosovo Liberation Army during its war against
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's forces.
</P>
<P>
   So people in the area were furious when Hasani was deported to
face felony charges in his native Macedonia late last month without
so much as a chance to defend himself -- a move that has also been
criticized by human rights organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Skenderbe Hebibi, a former KLA guerrilla who describes himself
as Hasani's best friend, stared through the smoke in the Drenica
cafe, the gathering spot that Hasani owns. He promised there would
be consequences for the U.N. action -- and it seems he was right.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, militants kidnapped four Macedonian soldiers,
offering to release them in exchange for Hasani. Officials close to
the Macedonian government told The Associated Press the soldiers
were released after Hasani was allowed out of prison on $100,000
bail.
</P>
<P>
   Hebibi had predicted the move days before the soldiers were
detained.
</P>
<P>
   ''What would the Americans have done if we arrested an American
soldier and then released him to a hostile country?'' he asked.
''We will do the same for the release of our soldier.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasani's detention and deportation might have been just another
event in the odd world that is justice in Kosovo, except for one
thing: The top U.N. representative in the province, Bernard
Kouchner, personally intervened in the case, signing the order that
sent Hasani to Macedonia to face charges of shooting at 11 people,
including two policemen.
</P>
<P>
   Hasani was deported because he posed a threat to public safety,
Kouchner said in the order.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats described the action as legally questionable --
signing Hasani away without giving him any legal forum to argue
against it. Kouchner's office declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty International accused the United Nations of taking an
action that many of its members -- including the United States --
would not be permitted to do under international law.
</P>
<P>
   ''How can the representative of the secretary-general not act in
conformity with U.N. human rights standards?'' said Shelley Inglis,
a researcher for Amnesty International in Pristina, Kosovo's
capital. ''This is clearly what is happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Though even U.N. administrators use the word ''disaster'' to
describe the overwhelmed local court system, Inglis suggested that
Kouchner could have -- at the very least -- rustled up the one
international judge working in Kosovo to hold a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have the responsibility to protect human rights,'' Inglis
said. ''They can't come into a place where the government has
violated human rights and continue to violate human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Kouchner would have much to gain by cutting a deal with
Macedonia, the country that borders Kosovo. A shaky Western ally
with a restive ethnic Albanian minority, Macedonia's government has
been under pressure to show it is tough on maintaining public order
after recent killings of policemen in ethnic Albanian enclaves
inflamed ethnic tensions.
</P>
<P>
   What Kouchner apparently didn't count on was that ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo would object, protesting at three spots along
the road to Macedonia after the deportation.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanian leaders, too, were furious that a former
guerrilla would be spirited away by U.N. helicopter to an uncertain
fate across the border. Western officials said Hashim Thaci, the
former KLA leader, threatened unspecified consequences unless
Kouchner acted immediately to bring Hasani back to Vitina.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials and NATO peacekeepers, meanwhile, closed ranks,
attempting to say as little about the case as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, it is unclear on what legal grounds U.S. soldiers
detained Hasani, given that he was wanted in Macedonia, not Kosovo.
He was held for three months at the U.S. Army's Camp Bondsteel.
</P>
<P>
   The order itself also has raised questions. Though Kouchner is
given wide latitude under the U.N. Security Council resolution
governing Kosovo, it is the NATO-led peacekeeping force -- and not
the United Nations -- that is responsible for security in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In his order, Kouchner noted that Hasani was a wanted man in
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   ''I consider in view of the above that Mr. Hasani poses a
significant danger to public order and safety and have decided that
he be deported from Kosovo,'' the order said.
</P>
<P>
   Hasani received a joyous welcome by ethnic Albanians in Vitina
late Monday after he was released from detention in Macedonia, the
Kosova Press news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of cars draped in red and black Albanian flags drove
through the town, 40 miles southeast of Pristina, to celebrate his
return.
</P>
<P>
   Hasani's friends were always confident he would come back.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right is on our side,'' Hebibi said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
