<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mendoza Named Investigative Reporter  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Martha Mendoza, San Jose correspondent
for The Associated Press, has been named a national investigative
reporter for the news service.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment was announced Tuesday by Managing Editor Jon
Wolman. She succeeds John Hendren, who resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza, who will be based in San Jose, will develop hard-edge
spot news and enterprise stories on subjects including the
environment, criminal justice, government and business.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza, who has been San Jose correspondent since 1998,
previously worked in New York on the AP's Special Assignment Team.
As a member of that team, she helped report the story of an alleged
massacre of civilians by U.S. troops at No Gun Ri in the early days
of the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza, 33, joined the AP as a newswoman in Albuquerque, N.M.,
in 1995. Before that, she worked for the Santa Cruz Sentinel and
for Bay City News service in San Francisco and San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   She is a native of Los Angeles and a graduate of the University
of California at Santa Cruz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
