<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Financial adviser to the stars informs court he now wants to be anagent  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A financial adviser charged with ripping off his
clients has been freed on $1 million bail to begin what his lawyer
said was a new career as an entertainment agent.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney David Lewis said the government strongly
opposed Dana Giacchetto's new career choice. He said it was an
''alarming proposition'' that Giacchetto could make his living by
charging substantial fees, after he allegedly swindled millions of
dollars from a world of celebrities which included Leonardo
DiCaprio, Ben Stiller and Courtney Cox Arquette.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Levander, Giacchetto's lawyer, said his client was trying
''to put his life back together'' by using his contacts in the
entertainment business to help actors and actresses get movie deals
or other business.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors told U.S. Magistrate Judge Andrew J. Peck that
Giacchetto should be limited to local travel and discouraged from
his new profession. Lewis said it was likely Giacchetto would
continue to steal from clients as an agent.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Giacchetto's assets have been frozen, the judge was
reluctant to interfere, saying: ''Assuming Mr. Giacchetto can get
on a Greyhound bus, stay in a Motel 6 with the last suit he owns on
his back, go schmooze with someone in California in the business,
why should we all care?''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the judge even suggested that nobody ''in their
right mind will make a deal with him with the current charges.''
</P>
<P>
   The government alleges Giacchetto, 37, stole as much as $5
million from the band Phish and its members and a million dollars
more from others while misappropriating as much as $20 million
entrusted to him.
</P>
<P>
   He also was accused of issuing fake portfolio statements and
other false documents to clients who wanted proof of their
purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Giacchetto is charged with securities fraud and with making
false statements to the Securities and Exchange Commission. If
convicted, he could face a decade in prison and $12 million in
fines.
</P>
<P>
   He allegedly committed the crimes while serving celebrities
including Matt Damon, Cameron Diaz and singer Alanis Morrisette
with an investment business, The Cassandra Group, run from a SoHo
loft.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the money allegedly went to support a lavish lifestyle
that Lewis said demonstrated ''a pattern of extraordinary
brazenness by Mr. Giacchetto with other people's money.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge agreed to let Giacchetto travel around the country if
he first obtains permission from the government, observing that ''a
lot of the business is based on the schmooze factor.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The schmooze factor is that business,'' agreed Levander, who
said it was critical that Giacchetto be permitted to go to dinners
where he could broker deals.
</P>
<P>
   Peck set bail at $1 million for Giacchetto, who surrendered to
the FBI Tuesday morning in Manhattan, just hours after returning
from a trip abroad. His passport was taken away.
</P>
<P>
   In court, Giacchetto nodded his head frequently as his lawyer
spoke and his parents watched from the gallery, agreeing to put up
a Medford, Mass., home valued at $500,000 to secure bail.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Giacchetto refused to comment to reporters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-05-00 0157 </TRAILER>
