<HEADLINE> Vargas Llosa Novel Causes Stir  </HEADLINE>
By RAMON ALMANZAR, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) -- A new novel by Mario
Vargas Llosa is stirring controversy with its portrayal of the
personal and political excesses of a slain Dominican dictator.
</P>
<P>
   ''La Fiesta del Chivo'' (''The Goat's Party'') tells of
Dominican parents offering their daughters to the feared dictator
Rafael Trujillo in return for promotions and choice jobs. It also
portrays Trujillo's son Ramfis seducing a high school student and
sharing her with his friends.
</P>
<P>
   The book's local publisher, Editora Taller, has defended the
novel, published last month in Spain, as a work of historical
fiction. But many historians say it twists too many facts.
</P>
<P>
   ''It makes personal references to situations that have yet to be
proved,'' Dominican historian Ramon Font Bernad said in a
television interview this week. He said Vargas Llosa, a Peruvian
writer who is one of Latin America's most respected authors, had
''offended'' the Dominican people.
</P>
<P>
   Trujillo remains a controversial figure in the Dominican
Republic long after the 1961 assassination that ended his 31-year
rule. Ramfis Trujillo held power for a few months after his
father's death before being forced into exile with the rest of the
Trujillo family.
</P>
<P>
   In Vargas Llosa's book, Urania Cabral, the daughter of a
Dominican senator, relives events of Trujillo's rule during a visit
to Santo Domingo in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas Llosa has admitted the book is mostly fictional, saying
his aim was ''to tell well-founded lies.''
</P>
<P>
   ''What appealed to me was not the phenomenon of the dictatorship
itself, but some of its characteristics,'' the Spanish news agency
EFE reported him as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Euclides Gutierrez Felix, the son of one of Trujillo's closest
allies, Capt. Euclides Gutierrez Abreu, has said there is no truth
to the stories of sexual favors.
</P>
<P>
   Among Vargas Llosa's defenders is Dominican writer Andres Mateo,
who said elements of the novel should be seen as symbolic, not
factual.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is an extremely severe portrait of a very difficult time,''
Mateo said. ''There was no cranny of social existence where the
oppressive symbols of (Trujillo's) power were not present, and the
novel reflects that with much rawness.''
</P>
<P>
   Editora Taller said Vargas Llosa -- who spent months in Santo
Domingo researching the work -- will visit the Dominican Republic on
April 26 to promote the book.
</P>
<P>
   A former journalist with Peruvian and French newspapers and
television, Vargas Llosa is best known for his novels ''The Green
House,'' ''The War of the End of the World'' and ''Conversation in
the Cathedral.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-05-00 0208 </TRAILER>
