<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Keeps Democrats Off-Balance  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- On the two most emotional foreign policy
issues now before Congress, the China trade deal and the fate of
6-year-old Cuban refugee Elian Gonzalez, Democrats are torn.
</P>
<P>
   And in both cases, the party's presumptive standard bearer, Vice
President Al Gore, isn't making life any easier for them.
</P>
<P>
   On Elian, Gore broke with the Clinton administration -- and
congressional Democratic leaders -- in voicing support for a bill to
block the boy's deportation by granting him permanent U.S.
residency status.
</P>
<P>
   On China, Gore gave off mixed signals until he and the
administration insisted they were both on the same page behind
legislation to grant China permanent normal trading privileges.
</P>
<P>
   The China trade bill is being strongly opposed by organized
labor, a key Democratic constituency.
</P>
<P>
   And even though Gore has pledged to work alongside President
Clinton for the package, what many see as his lukewarm support --
based on meetings earlier this year with labor leaders -- has given
a degree of political cover to fence-sitting Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., plans to schedule a House
vote on the China trade deal the week of May 22-27, sponsors of the
legislation said late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   That heartened backers of the bill, who fear that delaying the
vote into the summer could make it harder to win passage, with
election campaigns heating up.
</P>
<P>
   In both the China trade and Elian Gonzalez matter, vote counting
has been difficult, sponsors of both bills suggest.
</P>
<P>
   On highly charged measures on which it isn't even clear there'll
be a vote, ''It is always difficult to get your colleagues to tell
you where they stand,'' said Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla., a major
sponsor of both citizenship and residency bills for the Gonzalez
boy. He suggested Gore's support would help -- but it was difficult
to assess how much.
</P>
<P>
   By anyone's tally, there are a lot of undecided House Democrats
on China trade.
</P>
<P>
   Their ranks include Minority Leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri
and Rep. Charles Rangel of New York, the senior Democrat on the
House Ways and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a whole slew of undecideds. A lot of them still don't
think there's really going to be a vote -- so why commit?'' said
Rep. Robert T. Matsui, D-Calif., a leading advocate for more trade
with China.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore later reaffirmed his support for action this year
on the accord the administration negotiated with China, some labor
leaders suggested he had hinted he could negotiate a better
agreement as president with stronger worker and environmental
protections.
</P>
<P>
   That was enough to throw some uncertainty into the House
equation. Opponents welcomed Gore's apparent ambivalence.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would extend to China the same low-tariff trading
privileges now granted to other major U.S. trade partners. The
''permanent normal trade relations'' would end annual votes on
China's trade status.
</P>
<P>
   It was part of a package the Clinton administration negotiated
in November to help ease Beijing's entry into the World Trade
Organization, the Geneva-based organization that settles global
trade disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Congress will not vote directly on China's WTO membership. In
fact, trade-bill supporters argue that its rejection could lead to
a situation in which American firms are shut out of Chinese
markets.
</P>
<P>
   The China trade package has ''become a lightning rod for
everybody's dissatisfaction with everything,'' Clinton suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Bonior, D-Mich., the second ranking House Democrat
and a leading opponent of the China trade package, predicts that as
many as 150 of the House's 211 Democrats will vote against the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   That includes 98 who voted ''no'' last year to granting China
annual trade benefits. However, Bonior has only been able to
identify 19 Democrats who voted for annual renewal before who say
they'll vote ''no'' to permanent benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not going to suggest we're 100 percent going to beat this
thing,'' Bonior said.
</P>
<P>
   The vote is a difficult one for many Democrats -- in a year in
which Democrats hope to retain the White House and recapture the
House.
</P>
<P>
   If Gore is going to swing any votes in favor of the China trade
bill, he may have to work harder than he has on the Elian Gonzalez
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., said last Friday it
was too early to say what impact Gore's support might have. But
asked on Tuesday if Gore's stance had changed any Democratic votes,
Daschle responded, ''Not that I know of.''
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Tom Raum covers national and international
affairs for The Associated Press.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
