<HEADLINE> ABC Remains Ratings Leader  </HEADLINE>
By LYNN ELBER, AP Television Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- ABC is looking like a million bucks in the
ratings.
</P>
<P>
   The network has been the most-watched for 14 consecutive weeks --
its longest winning streak in 21 years -- and ''Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' is fueling the performance.
</P>
<P>
   The three editions of Regis Philbin's quiz show ranked No. 1,
No. 2 and No. 3 last week and helped draw viewers to other ABC
series, including the new ''Wonderland.''
</P>
<P>
   The psychiatric hospital drama, which followed Thursday night's
installment of ''Millionaire,'' drew an average 13.2 million
viewers to rank 25th among programs for the week of March 27 to
April 2.
</P>
<P>
   That's less than half the number of viewers that watched
''Millionaire'' that night -- about 29 million -- but ''Wonderland''
still managed to boost ABC's showing in the time period by 17
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The network also fared well with ''The Audrey Hepburn Story,''
starring Jennifer Love Hewitt as the actress. The TV movie ranked
12th among programs and won Monday night for ABC, according to
Nielsen Media Research figures released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The North Carolina State-Florida NCAA game gave CBS its
highest-rated Saturday since the Final Four game of a year ago.
This year's contest was watched by more than 15 million viewers and
ranked 14th among all programs.
</P>
<P>
   But the men's basketball tournament, which saw a number of
powerhouse teams quickly eliminated, ended lamely. There were
record low ratings for Monday night's concluding contest in which
Michigan State defeated Florida.
</P>
<P>
   NBC enjoyed success with the second outing of the Thursday night
sitcom ''Daddio,'' which ranked ninth for the week, drew 15.2
million viewers and retained most of its lead-in audience from
''Friends.''
</P>
<P>
   For the week, ABC had an average rating of 9.3 and a 16 share,
followed by CBS with an 8.3 rating and 14 share. NBC's 7.5 rating
and 13 share put it third, with Fox posting a 5.6 rating, 9 share.
</P>
<P>
   Among the newer networks, UPN had a 2.6 rating, 4 share, WB
earned a 2.1 rating, 3 share, and Pax had a 0.8 rating and 1 share.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's ''Nightly News'' had a slight lead in viewers, drawing
10.1 million compared to 9.95 million for ABC's ''World News
Tonight,'' while the two broadcasts had a matching 7.4 rating and
16 share. The ''CBS Evening News'' had 8.4 million viewers, with a
6.3 rating and 13 share.
</P>
<P>
   A rating point represents 1,008,000 households, or 1 percent of
the nation's estimated 100.8 million TV homes. The share is the
percentage of in-use televisions tuned to a given show.
</P>
<P>
   The top 10 shows, their networks and ratings for the week were:
''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' (Tuesday), ABC, 19.4; ''Who Wants
to Be a Millionaire'' (Thursday), ABC, 18.8; ''Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' (Sunday), ABC, 16.6; ''The Practice,'' ABC, 13.9;
''60 Minutes,'' CBS, 12.8; ''Touched by an Angel,'' CBS, 11.9;
''Friends,'' NBC, 11.3; ''Law &AMP; Order,'' NBC, 10.7; ''Daddio,''
NBC, 10.6; ''Dharma &AMP; Greg,'' ABC, 10.5.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen: http://www.nielsenmedia.com
</P>
</TEXT>
