<HEADLINE> Post Office Halts Holiday Stamps  </HEADLINE>
By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID, 
V0201-----
r w *1155AP-Postal-Thrift     04-05 0319
*1155 AP-Postal-Thrift,0318   
Post Office Halts Holiday Stamps   
By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- If this year's Christmas stamps seem a lot
like those from last year, don't blame your memory -- the post
office has decided to use up its leftovers.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with stocks of more than 100 million 20-stamp holiday
booklets, the Postal Service announced Tuesday that it has decided
to postpone the new Christmas stamps planned for this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rather than printing new holiday designs for 2000, we believe
it is a good business decision to exhaust our current inventories
of 1999 holiday stamps and supplement them with a small reprint of
one design,'' said James Tolbert, executive director of stamp
services.
</P>
<P>
   A scheduled Thanksgiving stamp is also being delayed. With a
1-cent rate increase likely next year, the agency decided it was
better to postpone the Thanksgiving stamp rather than have it
become outdated in a new months. Thanksgiving is to be part of a
series of holiday stamps that also includes the previously issued
Kwanzaa and Hanukkah stamps.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas stamps being postponed are traditional design
depicting Jan Gossaert's painting ''Madonna and Child,'' and the
contemporary version featuring four images of Santa.
</P>
<P>
   There are still supplies of Christmas stamps left from last
year, he said, including a design featuring Bartolomeo Vivarini's
''Madonna and Child.'' The contemporary design with a stylized
antique-gold deer set against one of four different colored
backgrounds will be reprinted, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Postal spokesman Don Smeraldi said the agency has 53 million
20-stamp booklets of each design leftover. Because the deer stamps
were popular last year and are expected to again do well, he said
another 75 million booklets of that issue will be printed for use
this holiday season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
