<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 02:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> President Johnson Pressured Israel  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID, AP Diplomatic Correspondent
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Johnson administration opposed Israeli
reprisals against Syria-backed terrorist attacks in the mid-1960s,
advising Israel to take its complaints to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Golda Meir complained, newly declassified U.S.
documents say, and was told Israel could not be considered an
injured party if it were to retaliate. Meir responded she was not
interested in Israel being considered an injured party; she did not
want Israel to be injured at all.
</P>
<P>
   This account appeared in a summary of the documents released
Monday by the office of the State Department historian.
</P>
<P>
   According to the account, terrorism on Israel's borders with
Lebanon and Jordan was the work of independent Palestinian
terrorist groups, chiefly Yasser Arafat's Fatah, which had Syria's
support.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1966, Israel retaliated with a large-scale raid into
Jordan, angering U.S. policy-makers, who said Israel knew Jordan
had tried to prevent such attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The United States voted for a U.N. Security Council resolution
that censured Israel, and President Johnson authorized a warning to
Israel that U.S. military shipments would be suspended if Israel
carried out another raid.
</P>
<P>
   During that period, Johnson and Secretary of State Dean Rusk,
worried about a threat of nuclear proliferation in the Middle East,
pressured Israel to promise not to develop nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy failed. A White House emissary sent to Tel Aviv
reported back to Washington that Israel was a tougher bargainer
even then the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Israel refused to make a commitment it considered dangerous to
its national security, the declassified documents said.
</P>
<P>
   At stake was a drive by Israel to acquire U.S. weapons. It had
received surface-to-air Hawk missiles from the Kennedy
administration in 1962 in a sale that was a departure from U.S.
policy.
</P>
<P>
   The United States was worried about ''the likely Arab reaction
and the impact of a sale on U.S. interests in the Near East and
influence in the Arab world,'' according to a summary of the
documents.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and his advisers had agreed to sell U.S. tanks to Jordan
while advising Israel that it should buy tanks it wanted from
Germany or Britain. The United States, Israel was told, would not
even consider a weapons sale unless Israel accepted four
conditions:
</P>
<P>
   --Tell its supporters in the United States that it accepted sale
of tanks to Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   --Promise not to develop nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   --Agree to Atomic Energy Agency inspection of its facilities.
</P>
<P>
   --Agree not to take pre-emptive action against Arab projects to
divert Jordan River water.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1965, Rusk cabled the chief U.S. emissary,
Undersecretary of State W. Averill Harriman, that Rusk and Johnson
thought it was time for Israel to make hard decisions, the newly
published documents said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are limits beyond which we cannot go in support of
Israel,'' Rusk told Harriman, while informing him the cable
reflected Johnson's feelings.
</P>
<P>
   When Israel would not budge, despite what Harriman described as
a Rusk presentation that was ''to the point of rudeness,'' Johnson
decided to sell Israel military equipment comparable to what the
United States was providing Jordan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-05-00 0242 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000405.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 02:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Partial Birth' Abortions Considered  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID ESPO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Courting a third presidential veto on the
subject, the Republican-controlled House is ready to pass
politically-charged legislation banning ''partial birth''
abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ''We keep hoping the president will see the light on this,''
Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla., said Tuesday, on the eve of a vote on
the measure, expected to gain more than the two-thirds majority
needed to overturn a promised veto.
</P>
<P>
   ''To have this debate is pure politics,'' countered Rep. Nita
Lowey, a New York Democrat and supporter of abortion rights. The
Republican leadership, she added, is ''just taking a political
action.''
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors say the measure, similar to a bill passed last fall in
the Senate, is designed to abolish a certain type of late-term
procedure in which a fetus is partially delivered, then aborted.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents counter that, as written, the bill would apply far
more broadly, thus undermining a 1973 Supreme Court ruling that
granted women the right to abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is voting on the measure at the same time the Supreme
Court is prepared to hear arguments on the constitutionality of a
''partial birth'' ban enacted in Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   While there is no direct connection between the court case and
the pending legislation, sponsors say the measure before the House
was crafted to meet objections of federal appeals court judges who
said the Nebraska statute failed to meet constitutional standards.
</P>
<P>
   As drafted, the House bill seeks to ban abortions in which a
doctor ''vaginally delivers some portion of an intact living fetus
until the fetus is partially outside the body of the mother'' and
''kills the fetus while the intact living fetus is partially
outside the body of the mother.''
</P>
<P>
   The only exceptions would be in cases in which the life of the
mother was threatened, and Democrats were discussing Tuesday night
whether to seek to a broader exceptions to include women whose
physical health were jeopardized.
</P>
<P>
   Since gaining their majority in the House and Senate in 1994,
Republicans have twice pushed ''partial birth'' measures to Clinton
desk, causing political anguish in the process for many Democrats
who favor abortion rights but found the bills impossible to oppose.
</P>
<P>
   House Democratic leader Dick Gephardt has voted for similar
bills in the past, for example, and will do so again.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has vetoed two ''partial birth'' bills in the past and
has served notice he will do so again, calling on Congress to
provide for exceptions in the case of potential harm to a woman's
health.
</P>
<P>
   Both previous vetoes were overridden in the House before being
narrowly sustained in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome this time, Canady offered one prediction:
''I can't say that we're going to hear any new arguments.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-05-00 0248 </TRAILER>
