<HEADLINE> Broncos-Rams Opens Monday Night FB  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The NFL is again opening the season with the
last two Super Bowl winners playing on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver Broncos and St. Louis Rams will cap the opening week
of the 2000 season in St. Louis on Monday night Sept. 4.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams will start the defense of their title, while the
Broncos will try to rebound from an injury-plagued 6-10 season.
</P>
<P>
   That game and a Sunday night meeting in Buffalo between the
Bills and the Tennessee Titans highlight the first weekend of the
NFL season.
</P>
<P>
   The Bills-Titans game is a reprise of the ''Music City Miracle''
in the first round of last season's playoffs, won by the Titans on
a last play lateral on a kickoff return. Tennessee later beat
Indianapolis and Jacksonville and went on to the Super Bowl, where
they lost to the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams' opening game will be their first Monday night
appearance since 1991, the beginning of a decade of futility that
ended when they turned a 4-12 record in 1998 into an NFL title last
season. It will be the third straight season Denver, the 1998 Super
Bowl champs, has opened on a Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL, which because of the demise of several traditional
powers was hurt last year by poor prime-time matchups late in the
season, is trying to ensure that won't happen again. Next year, the
league is considering leaving some Monday nights open to switch the
games with the most interest.
</P>
<P>
   The next-to-last Monday night game features St. Louis at Tampa
Bay, a rematch of last season's NFC title game, which was played in
St. Louis. The final game, on Christmas night, pits Dallas at
Tennessee -- the Cowboys always get an audience even if they are
mediocre.
</P>
<P>
   Another note of the volatility of the schedule: San Francisco,
which fell to 4-12 last season after nearly two decades of
dominance, does not have a prime-time game for the first time since
1981, the year they won the first of five Super Bowls.
</P>
</TEXT>
