<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Government Tests Alliance  </HEADLINE>
By SELCAN HACAOGLU, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- The fate of Turkey's government could rest
on Parliament's decision on whether to allow President Suleyman
Demirel to seek re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition to the proposal might lead to the collapse of the
10-month old government, hailed as the most stable in years. Prime
Minister Bulent Ecevit insists that the re-election of Demirel,
Turkey's most enduring politician, is crucial for stability.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition leaders pledged to support the bill in a second
round of voting today. The government needs the approval of at
least 367 deputies in the 550-member chamber to enact the bill
without going to an unwanted and risky referendum.
</P>
<P>
   The constitutional reform would reduce the president's term from
seven to five years, but would allow for a second term. A new
president must be elected by May 16.
</P>
<P>
   Presidents are elected by parliament and in theory fill a
largely symbolic post, however the presidency has been the power
broker in several government crises.
</P>
<P>
   Demirel, 76, has been active in Turkish politics for almost 40
years. Many see him as the symbol of immobility in Turkish
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Close to 100 deputies of the governing parties voted against the
amendment last week, causing serious strains in the coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Ecevit said as many as 406 deputies, including members of the
center-right opposition True Path Party, had initially backed the
proposal. The government alone has 352 seats.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister wants to prevent political bickering among
his coalition partners over Demirel's successor, which could hamper
the government's economic reform package and much-needed political
stability on the road toward membership in the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   In a bid to lure the support of the opposition, the government
has attached two other constitutional amendments, which offer a
lucrative pension plan to deputies and would make it more difficult
for courts to shut down political parties.
</P>
<P>
   But the latter failed to satisfy the Islamic Virtue Party, which
faces closure for activities deemed anti-secular. The party is
pushing for an additional amendment that would lift a political ban
on the leader of the Islamic movement, Necmettin Erbakan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-05-00 0254 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000405.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 02:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Martin Luther King Jr. Remembered  </HEADLINE>
By RUSS BYNUM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Warning that Georgia could face an economic
boycott similar to one being waged in South Carolina, the son of
Martin Luther King Jr. urged lawmakers to remove the Confederate
battle emblem from the state flag.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not saying that we're going to boycott. What we're
saying is that we're poised to, if righteousness and justice do not
occur and the flag does not come down,'' Martin Luther King III
said Tuesday during a rally to commemorate the 32nd anniversary of
his father's death.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere Tuesday, the life of the slain civil right's leader
was remembered with rallies and marches, including one in Chicago
led by the Rev. Jesse Jackson. In Memphis, Tenn., garbage
collectors had the day off in recognition of the sanitation
workers' strike that prompted King's fateful trip to that city.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia marked the day by establishing a King holiday, with
Gov. Jim Gilmore signing the legislation. The observation of his
birthday had shared the same day in January with those of
Confederate generals Robert E. Lee and Thomas J. ''Stonewall''
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, family members laid a wreath at King's tomb, then
gathered at the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Coretta Scott King, the slain leader's widow, also pledged to
fight the Georgia flag, which was changed in 1956, some believe in
defiance of segregation.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are going to keep marching and protesting until Georgia and
every state has a flag that respects and unifies people of all
races,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A boycott by black activists in South Carolina, which flies the
Confederate flag over its Capitol, has cost the state millions of
tourism dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the flag say it honors their Southern heritage.
Opponents call it a symbol of racism. While the issue has sparked a
major debate in South Carolina, Georgia lawmakers virtually ignored
the flag during the 40-day session that ended last month.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to change the Georgia flag have fizzled since former
Gov. Zell Miller pushed for a new banner in 1993. The controversy
nearly cost Miller re-election, and lawmakers have been hesitant to
touch the issue ever since.
</P>
<P>
   A recent poll by Georgia State University showed fewer than a
third of Georgians support changing the flag.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, King family members announced they have posted on
the Internet the full transcript of a trial in which a Memphis jury
concluded last year that government agents and others conspired to
murder King.
</P>
<P>
   They said the transcripts were important because the mainstream
media ignored or distorted details of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now people who want to learn what really happened in Memphis
can easily read the testimony firsthand and without any
interpretation,'' King's widow said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have long concluded that Ray acted as a lone gunman
and the Justice Department has refused to reopen the investigation,
despite the King family's insistence that a far-reaching conspiracy
was to blame.
</P>
<P>
   James Earl Ray confessed to King's murder soon after the
shooting, but spent the rest of his life in prison claiming
innocence. He died of liver failure in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In December, the Memphis jury sided with the Kings in their
wrongful death lawsuit against Loyd Jowers, a former restaurant
owner who said he paid someone other than Ray to kill King in 1968.
The family's lawyer claimed the FBI, CIA, the Mafia and the
military were involved.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Trial transcript: http://www.thekingcenter.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-05-00 0255 </TRAILER>
