<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 03:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Begins Budget Debate  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senate Democrats have a raft of amendments
ready for the Republican-written $1.83 trillion budget for 2001
that are aimed at forcing GOP lawmakers to take potentially
embarrassing election-year votes.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate planned to vote today on one of them, language aimed
at forcing legislators to create a new prescription drug benefit
for Medicare recipients before cutting taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The provision, sponsored by Sen. Charles Robb, D-Va., who is up
for re-election this year, seemed certain to be rejected. But
Democrats were hoping to cast Republicans as more eager to cut
taxes for the rich than to help the elderly pay for their
prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let's put our priorities in order and put seniors before tax
cuts,'' Robb said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Budget Committee Chairman Pete Domenici, R-N.M., said
that under the GOP budget, it ''will be permissible'' for lawmakers
to vote on prescription drugs this fall, even without Robb's
language.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate was likely to debate the budget all week and approve
it by Friday. That would set up negotiations with the House, which
adopted a similar plan two weeks ago. Congress' budget, which is
not signed by the president, sets overall tax and spending limits
but saves specific decisions for later bills.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP budget includes up to $40 billion over five years for a
prescription drug plan, but it omits details and does not require
any action. Such a benefit has been a top priority for President
Clinton the past two years, and Republicans have talked about
writing a similar but scaled-down package.
</P>
<P>
   Another Democratic amendment designed to embarrass Republicans
would oppose rolling back the 18.4-cent per gallon federal tax on
gasoline. Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., proposed the
rollback, but it has been criticized by some for jeopardizing money
for popular highway projects.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another would force a vote on including George W. Bush's
larger tax cut in the budget.
</P>
<P>
   Most GOP lawmakers would rather avoid that because it would
probably erode Social Security surpluses both parties want to leave
alone. Bush, the presumptive GOP presidential nominee, would cut
taxes by $483 billion from 2002 through 2006.
</P>
<P>
   In ways subtle and explicit, the budget debate underlines how
Republicans have sought to de-emphasize the size of their tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, cutting taxes remains a signature issue for GOP
lawmakers, who have spent much of the year trying to do just that.
Their budget envisions at least $150 billion in tax cuts through
2005.
</P>
<P>
   ''That money ought to be looked at very carefully,'' Domenici
said regarding the budget surpluses that would pay for the tax
cuts. ''Because it's the American people who are overpaying their
taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   GOP leaders also plan a Senate vote next week on reducing taxes
by $248 billion over 10 years for married couples, including
millions who face the so-called marriage penalty because they owe
higher levies than they would if single.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, much of the GOP's budget rhetoric emphasizes cutting
taxes less than other priorities like protecting Social Security
surpluses, debt reduction and financing defense and education. That
could reflect polls showing that most voters enjoying today's
healthy economy prefer bolstering Social Security, Medicare and
education to a dramatic effort to cut taxes.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Domenici said the spending plan he wrote has a
''modest tax reduction'' and contains $13 in debt reduction for
every $1 in tax cuts. And the Republican report accompanying the
budget describing the plan's ''general principles'' lists tax cuts
ninth -- right behind emergency aid for farmers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, this year's GOP budget covers five years instead of
the 10 years their plan covered last year, partly to show a smaller
total tax-cut figure. Many of them believe Clinton won last year's
tax battle when he vetoed their 10-year, $792 billion reduction
because he focused the debate on the dollar amount, not the types
of taxes to be cut.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said the GOP plan translated to at least $750 billion
over the next decade, similar to last year's vetoed package.
Republicans said it would be $450 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's budget called for $99 billion in tax reductions
through 2005, nearly offset by $96 billion in increased taxes on
cigarettes and some businesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
