<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 10:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Transplant Docs Face Murder Charges  </HEADLINE>
By BUSABA SIVASOMBOON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Three doctors and a former hospital
executive already penalized for ethical breaches involving a series
of kidney transplants now face murder charges, Thai police said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Police issued subpoenas for the four Wednesday on two charges of
conspiracy to commit murder after a commission found that they had
not followed proper procedures in declaring organ donors brain
dead. Conspiracy to commit murder carries the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Thailand's Medical Council revoked the license of
one doctor and suspended those of four others at the hospital after
finding that they had illegally traded in human organs.
</P>
<P>
   The council said it had sufficient evidence to show that surgeon
Sirot Kanchanapanchaphol and his colleagues improperly harvested
kidneys. The council also found the team violated brain-death
analysis standards. Sirot was one of those charged by police.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects, from Vachiraprakarn Hospital on the outskirts of
Bangkok, are also charged with falsifying documents.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects have previously denied all allegations.
</P>
<P>
   The police acted on a complaint by the Law Society of Thailand,
acting on behalf of the relatives of two people from whom kidneys
were harvested after they were declared brain-dead.
</P>
<P>
   They alleged that the kidneys were obtained by malpractice,
trickery and payment. The cases came to light about a year ago,
after one of the relatives took his story to the media.
</P>
<P>
   Trading in organs is prohibited in Thailand. Organ donation is
done by agreement between donors and recipients without any
payments.
</P>
<P>
   Sirot, former chairman of the hospital, and his colleagues
allegedly used false documents which claimed relatives of
brain-dead patients permitted them to remove kidneys.
</P>
<P>
   They were also accused of giving money to the relatives of the
organ donors, and then charging organ recipients.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-05-00 1006 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000405.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 10:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Down 97; Dow Off 29  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Investors beaten down and bewildered by
Tuesday's wild market returned to Wall Street with a measure of
caution today, sending technology shares and blue-chip stocks
moderately lower.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Nasdaq
composite index was down 97.94 at 4,050.95. The Dow Jones
industrial average was down 29.78 at 11,135.06.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were slightly lower. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index was down 14.87 at 1,479.86, and the Russell 2000
index of smaller companies was fell 0.63 to 500.03.
</P>
<P>
   Volume was fairly modest, but the volatility that marked
Tuesday's session remained, sending indexes fluctuating.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks fell from the opening bell as traders struggled to find
their footing after Tuesday's chaotic selloff, when both the Nasdaq
and the Dow fell more than 500 points only to finish the turbulent
session with modest, double-digit losses.
</P>
<P>
   The wildness on Wall Street rattled most overseas markets,
making it difficult for the U.S. market to mount any real recovery.
In Japan, the Nikkei stock average fell 0.6 percent, with
technology shares leading the decline. In afternoon trading,
Germany's DAX index was down 3.8 percent and France's CAC-40 was
down 4.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Trading on the London Stock Exchange was suspended Wednesday
because of a technical fault which wiped out accurate price data
from the opening.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks continued their slide, with large and small
names all lower. Cisco Systems fell 2 9/64 to 70 63/64, and
Broadcom, a maker of silicon semiconductors, fell 7 to 197.
</P>
<P>
   Sears helped offset the Dow's losses, rising 3} to 34\. The
company said today it expects first-quarter profits to beat
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Breadth was poor across the board. On the New York Stock
Exchange, decliners led advancers by a 4-to-3 margin. On the
Nasdaq, decliners led by a 7-to-3 margin.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE volume was 149.89 million shares, slightly ahead of
Tuesday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   This afternoon, two major players in the market's recent swings
are scheduled to speak at a White House conference on the new
economy. Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan will discuss the
Internet and productivity. Abby Joseph Cohen, chief investment
strategist at Goldman Sachs, is also scheduled to speak.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Cohen's recommendation that clients put some of their
stock holdings into cash sparked selling on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ------
