<HEADLINE> Third poll shows Giuliani support waning  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- A statewide poll today showed that Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani's former lead over Hillary Rodham Clinton in New
York's Senate race has evaporated in the wake of the Patrick
Dorismond shooting.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third such poll result in 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Giuliani's campaign manager, Bruce Teitelbaum, sent
his counterpart in the Clinton campaign, Bill de Blasio, a letter
asking for a meeting to discuss possible debates. There was no
immediate comment from de Blasio.
</P>
<P>
   While both Giuliani and Clinton have said they want debates,
they have yet to be arranged.
</P>
<P>
   The new poll, from the Quinnipiac College Polling Institute, had
the first lady favored by 46 percent of registered voters surveyed
while 43 percent backed the New York City mayor. Giuliani led
Clinton, 48 percent to 41 percent, in a March 2 poll from the
Hamden, Conn.-based institute.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier polls, from Zogby International for the New York Post
and from Marist College's Institute for Public Opinion, had similar
results.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the first time in months that Mrs. Clinton has been on
the plus side in this very close race and there's a one-word
explanation -- Dorismond,'' said Maurice Carroll, director of the
polling institute.
</P>
<P>
   Dorismond was fatally shot by New York City police last month.
In defending the police in the shooting of the unarmed black man,
Giuliani made public Dorismond's criminal record, including
court-sealed juvenile records. That has drawn heavy criticism of
the mayor, including some from fellow Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Quinnipiac's telephone poll of 1,058 registered voters was
conducted March 28-April 3 and has a margin of error of plus or
minus 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani campaign spokeswoman Juleanna Glover Weiss, noting that
the three recent polls all had the race close, said ''in light of
the recent media coverage, this is not unexpected.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I know he's been having a bad couple of weeks,'' Clinton said
this morning during a campaign stop in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll said the poll found that Giuliani's former lead among
white women had also disappeared. He is now favored by 44 percent
of those voters to 42 percent for Clinton, a statistical tie. In
the March 2 poll, the mayor had enjoyed a 14-point edge over
Clinton among white women.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, 50 percent of voters said they disapproved of
Giuliani's response to the Dorismond shooting, with the greatest
disapproval coming from New York City (72 percent) and in the
suburban counties surrounding the city (54 percent). ------
</P>
<P>
   On The Net, polling institute site: www.quinnipiac.edu
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
