<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Down 21.36; Dow Down 78.10  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Investors beaten down and bewildered by
Tuesday's wild market returned to Wall Street with a measure of
caution today, keeping most stocks trading in a narrow range.
Technology stocks crept higher after an early decline.
</P>
<P>
   In late morning on Wall Street, the Nasdaq composite index was
down 21.36 at 4,127.53, having recovered from a drop of 139.80
earlier in the session. The Dow Jones industrial average was down
78.10 at 11,086.74.
</P>
<P>
   Volume was fairly modest, but the volatility that marked
Tuesday's session remained, sending the indexes fluctuating between
positive and negative territory.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were slightly higher. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index was up 3.44 at 1,498.17, and the Russell 2000
index of smaller companies was up 9.04 to 509.70.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks fell at the opening bell as traders struggled to find
their footing after Tuesday's chaotic selloff, when both the Nasdaq
and the Dow fell more than 500 points only to finish the turbulent
session with modest, double-digit losses.
</P>
<P>
   The wildness on Wall Street rattled most overseas markets,
making it difficult for the U.S. market to mount any real recovery.
In Japan, the Nikkei stock average fell 0.6 percent, with
technology shares leading the decline. In afternoon trading,
Germany's DAX index was down 3.1 percent and France's CAC-40 was
down 3.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Trading on the London Stock Exchange was suspended today because
of a technical fault which wiped out accurate price data from the
opening.
</P>
<P>
   As the session wore on, some Wall Street investors went looking
for bargains, but there wasn't much enthusiasm, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We see it more as the eye of the storm,'' said Gail Dudack,
chief investment strategist at Warburg Dillon Read in New York.
''The danger for the market place has not ended.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks turned mixed. Microsoft fell 2 5/64 to 86
31/64 and Qualcomm, a wireless communications company that led the
Nasdaq's advance in 1999, fell 6] to 140\.
</P>
<P>
   Applied Materials, a leading maker of computer chip equipment,
rose 6 3/16 to 104 5/16.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks that are representatives of the ''old economy'' continued
to fare better. Sears rose 3} to 34\ after saying that it expects
first-quarter profits to beat expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Honeywell, an aerospace and automotive manufacturer, led the Dow
with a gain of 1 3/16 to 54|.
</P>
<P>
   Breadth was improving, with more stocks heading higher as the
session wore on. On the New York Stock Exchange, advancers led
decliners by a 10-to-9 margin. On the Nasdaq, decliners led by a
5-to-4 margin.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE volume was 353.57 million shares, behind Tuesday's early
pace.
</P>
<P>
   This afternoon, two major players in the market's recent swings
were scheduled to speak at a White House conference on the new
economy. Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan was to discuss the
Internet and productivity. Abby Joseph Cohen, chief investment
strategist at Goldman Sachs, was also scheduled to speak.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Cohen's recommendation that clients put some of their
stock holdings into cash sparked a round of selling on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
