<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 11:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Rejects Drug Benefit Vote  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate rejected a Democratic effort today
that would have forced creation of a Medicare prescription drug
benefit before lawmakers could vote on broad tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Though the provision was killed, the vote served Democrats'
political purposes of trying to cast Republicans as more eager to
cut taxes for the rich than to help the elderly pay for their
prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let's get our priorities straight and do what's correct,''
said Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was 51-49 in favor of the provision, which was
introduced by Sen. Charles Robb, D-Va. But it died because
Republicans used a procedural move that required 60 votes to
prevail.
</P>
<P>
   All 45 Democrats and six Republicans voted for the measure. They
were Sens. Peter Fitzgerald of Illinois, Arlen Specter of
Pennsylvania and four facing voters this fall: Spencer Abraham of
Michigan, Conrad Burns of Montana, Lincoln Chafee of Rhode Island
and Mike DeWine of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Robb's proposal was offered as an amendment to a $1.83 trillion
budget for 2001 that Republicans plan to push through the Senate by
week's end.
</P>
<P>
   Next for the budget will be negotiations with the House, which
adopted a similar plan two weeks ago. Congress' budget, which is
not signed by the president, sets overall tax and spending limits
but saves specific decisions for later bills.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP budget sets aside up to $40 billion over five years for
a prescription drug plan, but it omits details and does not require
any action. Such a benefit has been a top priority for President
Clinton the past two years, and Republicans have talked about
writing a similar but scaled-down package.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bill Frist, R-Tenn., said there is no need to link tax cuts
to prescription drug coverage, as the Democratic amendment would
have done. And he said it would be irresponsible to create new
Medicare benefits without also taking steps to assure the solvency
of the health-insurance program for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is deceptive, it is not right,'' Frist said. ''Seniors
deserve better.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Democratic amendment designed to embarrass Republicans
would oppose rolling back the 18.4-cent-per-gallon federal tax on
gasoline. Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., proposed the
rollback, but it has been criticized by some for jeopardizing money
for popular highway projects.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another would force a vote on including George W. Bush's
larger tax cut in the budget.
</P>
<P>
   Most GOP lawmakers would rather avoid that because it would
probably erode Social Security surpluses both parties want to leave
alone. Bush, the presumptive GOP presidential nominee, would cut
taxes by $483 billion from 2002 through 2006.
</P>
<P>
   In ways subtle and explicit, the budget debate underlines how
Republicans have sought to de-emphasize the size of their tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, cutting taxes remains a signature issue for GOP
lawmakers, who have spent much of the year trying to do just that.
Their budget envisions at least $150 billion in tax cuts through
2005.
</P>
<P>
   ''That money ought to be looked at very carefully,'' Sen. Pete
Domenici, R-N.M., the Budget Committee chairman, said regarding the
budget surpluses that would pay for the tax cuts. ''Because it's
the American people who are overpaying their taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   GOP leaders also plan a Senate vote next week on reducing taxes
by $248 billion over 10 years for married couples, including
millions who face the so-called marriage penalty because they owe
higher levies than they would if single.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, much of the GOP's budget rhetoric emphasizes cutting
taxes less than other priorities like protecting Social Security
surpluses, debt reduction and financing defense and education. That
could reflect polls showing that most voters enjoying today's
healthy economy prefer bolstering Social Security, Medicare and
education to a dramatic effort to cut taxes.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Domenici said the spending plan he wrote has a
''modest tax reduction'' and contains $13 in debt reduction for
every $1 in tax cuts. And the Republican report accompanying the
budget describing the plan's ''general principles'' lists tax cuts
ninth -- right behind emergency aid for farmers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-05-00 1153 </TRAILER>
