<DOCNO> APW20000405.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 12:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Common Mistakes When Filing Taxes  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- Older Americans who may be on a fixed income or
limited budget often overlook standard deductions and may make
mistakes when filing their income taxes, according to a tax expert.
</P>
<P>
   ''Taking your time and a little care can avoid most of these
mistakes,'' as well as save you some money, says Michael B. Cates,
a professional tax preparer and an academic assistant at the
College for Financial Planning.
</P>
<P>
   A common mistake is forgetting to take an additional standard
deduction for being age 65 or older, says Cates.
</P>
<P>
   ''That amounts to an additional $850 deduction on the 1999
return -- $1,700 for married couples if each is age 65 or older.
Unmarried taxpayers, age 65 or older, can take an additional
standard deduction of $1,050,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   To qualify, Cates says, a filer would have to turn 65 sometime
during the tax year, even if it is as late as Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Cates says you also can claim an additional standard deduction
if you are legally blind. So a married person age 65 and legally
blind can take a total of $1,700 in standard deductions in addition
to their regular standard deduction.
</P>
<P>
   Certain medical expenses are another common area older taxpayers
overlook. For example, you can claim 10 cents a mile for the trips
to the doctor, the hospital, pharmacy or other medical facility, as
well as expenses associated with those trips such as tolls and
parking fees. You also can claim public transportation costs. Most
transportation claims may appear small, but they can add up,
especially if you are regularly going to the doctor or other
medical facility, says Cates. You can also claim up to $50 a night
for lodging if you stay overnight on a medical trip.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget to claim the amount you pay for Medicare Part B
premiums. These premiums may not add up to a lot by themselves,
because the only medical expenses you can claim are those that
exceed 7.5 percent of your adjusted gross income. However, the
premiums might make a difference when combined with out-of-pocket
expenses and the premiums you pay for a supplemental Medicare
policy, perhaps a Medicare HMO, and long-term care insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Cates says that for 1999, the maximum you can deduct is $800 for
long-term care insurance premiums if you are aged 51-60, $2,120 for
those aged 61-70, and $2,660 if you are over age 70. Of course, the
cost of any medical expenses not reimbursed for long-term care also
is deductible.
</P>
<P>
   Points for the purchase of a home is another confusing deduction
area for taxpayers, says Cates. Perhaps you sold the home last year
that you raised your children in and you've moved into a smaller
home. You can fully deduct the points on the home you bought.
However, Cates notes that if you bought the new home late in the
year, it may actually pay to deduct the points over the life of the
loan instead of fully deducting them in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is, explains Cates, the mortgage interest deduction
for the new home would be very low for 1999, and it may have been
very low or nonexistent for the previous home if it was near the
end of its mortgage or paid off. Consequently, you may not have
enough home expenses to itemize for 1999 and you would lose the
points deduction. You may be more likely to benefit from amortizing
them over subsequent years.
</P>
<P>
   Refinancing is also confusing regarding deducting points. For a
first refinance on a home, you can only amortize points over the
life of the loan. For a second refinancing, you can deduct the
remaining points from the previous refinance in full in the year
you refinanced again.
</P>
<P>
   Cates emphasizes that taxpayers doing their own returns double
and triple check everything. The IRS reports up to an 18 percent
error rate on returns, involving everything from inaccurate math to
missing Social Security numbers. Since most people receive refunds,
that only delays their refund.
</P>
<P>
   Cates says you can automatically file for a four-month filing
extension using Form 4868, and you can request an additional
two-month filing extension using Form 2688, though you'll have to
get permission from the IRS for the second extension.
</P>
<P>
   A filing extension is not the same as a payment extension,
emphasizes Cates. Assuming you owe the IRS, you should make a
reasonable payment by the April deadline. If you don't end up
paying enough, you may be assessed interest and penalties, but you
won't get socked with a five percent a month failure to file
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ''Taxpayers do get one good piece of news this year,'' says
Cates. ''April 15 falls on a Saturday, so your taxes aren't due
until Monday the 17th. You get a two-day bonus.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
