<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 12:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barter in 2000? Sharing 'Sopranos'  </HEADLINE>
By JEFF BARNARD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEADWOOD, Ore. (AP) -- Deep into his second season as a rabid fan
of ''The Sopranos,'' Michael Zachai started thinking it might be
nice to follow mobster Tony Soprano's lead and become a waste
management consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ''But everybody in Deadwood burns their garbage or feeds it to
the pigs,'' said Zachai.
</P>
<P>
   HBO's conflicted mobster, who once fell in love with the idea of
wild ducks in his swimming pool, should take a look at Deadwood,
where Zachai mixes art and carpentry to make his living and must be
counted as the series' biggest fan.
</P>
<P>
   Tucked up a winding canyon in the rain-soaked Coast Range, where
the trees are heavy with luminescent green moss and sword ferns
blanket the forest floor, Deadwood could not be farther from the
gritty New Jersey sprawl that is the show's backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   Yet through satellite delivery, the hit series has penetrated
even here, and the pioneer tradition of barter has now evolved into
exchanging a taped episode for a home-cooked meal. Country folks
with urban roots, like the Brooklyn-native Zachai, depend on it for
a breath of gritty city air.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's like E.L. Doctorow said in 'Billy Bathgate': 'I can't
wait to get this country air out of my lungs,''' said Zachai.
</P>
<P>
   ''I like it here. There is something about living on 40 acres
that is reassuring. You don't have to see ugliness around you all
the time. You create your own world. But I am an urban person.
That's why I watch 'The Sopranos.'''
</P>
<P>
   Fans anywhere of popular premium-cable shows like ''The
Sopranos'' may swap the latest taped episodes with friends and
co-workers. But Deadwood is an extreme example.
</P>
<P>
   To say it is out in the country is to miss the mark. It is
waaaaaaaayyyyyy out in the country -- an hour and a half's drive
west from Eugene on a two-lane blacktop that climbs out of the
broad Willamette Valley, then down toward the Pacific along the
meandering course of Lake Creek.
</P>
<P>
   To a person driving by, Deadwood is a post office and
combination store-gas station, where you can rent a video, drink a
Coke or buy cattle feed.
</P>
<P>
   But those who fall under its ''Brigadoon'' spell will find 150
residents scattered up the lush valley: a mix of hippies, artists,
organic farmers, writers, loggers, carpenters and retirees who have
hung on or moved in since the collapse of logging as a way of life.
</P>
<P>
   Zachai, 57, came to Oregon in 1969 to get a masters degree in
geography at the University of Oregon in Eugene, but soon found he
had no sense of direction and turned to carpentry. Now, his
children grown and his marriage dissolved, he lives alone in a
house he built up the hill from Deadwood Creek, where salmon spawn
in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Though he's not Italian, Zachai feels a connection to Italy and
has studied the language. When the weather is warm, he eats lunch
in an arbor of clematis and climbing roses. There are neat beds of
daffodils, and a vegetable garden surrounded by an artful 7-foot
fence topped by bent alder branches to keep out the deer.
</P>
<P>
   On the porch roof is the mini-dish for HBO.
</P>
<P>
   Zachai saw his first episode of ''The Sopranos'' while hanging
out at the home of Boyd and Mary Upchurch. Boyd is a retired
science fiction novelist -- pen name John Boyd -- and Mary is a
former teacher. They came here from Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ''I only watch it because of Michael,'' said Boyd.
</P>
<P>
   But Zachai was hooked, and signed right up.
</P>
<P>
   '''The Godfather' was luxurious and lush and operatic,'' said
Zachai. ''This is documentary.''
</P>
<P>
   He tapes every episode, and retired Hollywood accountant Paul
Kovalchuk recently cooked him a nice dinner of lamb shanks and rice
pilaf, no dessert, when they got together to watch a string of
them.
</P>
<P>
   ''I read a review on it and thought, 'This is nice,' but I'm not
going to spend $12 a month on it,'' said Kovalchuk, who did the
books for a string of TV series and watches a lot of C-SPAN.
</P>
<P>
   The high point for Zachai comes every two weeks, when he drives
down off the mountain to buy his groceries at Costco in Eugene and
spends the night at the home of Jim and Pauline Lane, who became
friends when he did a remodeling job years ago.
</P>
<P>
   They watch his latest tape while eating a big Italian dinner
prepared by Pauline, who grew up Pauline Smarrella, the daughter of
a doctor in Dean Martin's home town of Steubenville, Ohio, and who
translates the Italian words for Zachai.
</P>
<P>
   ''It finally dawned on me that it would have been cheaper to get
HBO,'' Pauline quipped as she moved easily around the kitchen,
frying eggplant, stirring tomato sauce with shortribs, and offering
a taste of roasted peppers on bread.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have to notice in 'The Sopranos' that Carmela (Tony's
wife) is so efficient in the kitchen,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I read somewhere she doesn't know how to cook,'' returned
Zachai.
</P>
<P>
   ''Well, she does a good imitation,'' Pauline replied.
</P>
<P>
   ''The thing that is so good about 'The Sopranos' is that it is
kind of over the top, but it is also very true,'' Pauline added.
''You look at that show differently if you come from those
cultures. I think someone raised in Oregon on white bread and
mayonnaise ...''
</P>
<P>
   Zachai finished her sentence for her: ''It's like 'Star Wars' to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditional cops-and-robbers shows never really worked for
Zachai, who preferred the peculiarities of ''Northern Exposure''
over ''NYPD Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   ''When the cops always win every week, it's not that
interesting,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Deadwood, volunteer fire chief Michael Ager, himself a
Star Trek fan who crafts wooden salmon in Zachai's shop, caught a
couple episodes of ''The Sopranos'' while house-sitting for friends
who had HBO up the road in Greenleaf.
</P>
<P>
   ''I liked it,'' he said as he sat recently and watched neighbor
Adam Wagner, an organic farmer, split wood. ''It's not all that
shoot-'em-up. The characters have depth.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wagner's wife, Maria Kirwin, who teaches high school
Spanish, was put off by the profanity.
</P>
<P>
   ''They just used the 'f' word every other minute, and for no
good reason,'' she said as she patted the bare behind of her
10-month-old son, Dylan.
</P>
<P>
   Standing up for his favorite show, Zachai said it transports him
back to his youth in a Jewish section of Brooklyn, where kids knew
to stay out of the nondescript social clubs in the Italian
neighborhoods where the Mafiosi hung out.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe we are like salmon and we have to go back where we
were spawned,'' he said. ''I have to go back to Brooklyn.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-05-00 1206 </TRAILER>
