<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000405.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 12:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Books and Authors: Joyce Carol Oates  </HEADLINE>
By DEBORAH HASTINGS, AP National Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Marilyn Monroe has been dead for nearly four
decades and still the writers come, drawing from a well that is
shallow but never dry.
</P>
<P>
   The latest to appropriate Marilyn's soul is Joyce Carol Oates,
whose ''Blonde'' is 738 tortured pages of ''radically distilled''
reality.
</P>
<P>
   It is truth dressed up as fiction, to paraphrase the noted
author and women's advocate: an imagined look inside an actress who
died from barbiturates, written by someone who never met the
actress and didn't consult anyone who has.
</P>
<P>
   The novel, which reportedly earned more than $1 million from
advance fees and television rights, is scheduled for release Sunday
and is receiving national media attention before its publicity tour
even begins.
</P>
<P>
   CBS plans a four-hour miniseries. Oates plans a play.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter that finding gold in Monroe's tapped-out veins
is about as likely as striking another mother lode at Sutter's
mill. Nothing, it appears, will deter those hell-bent on sifting
her remains.
</P>
<P>
   She is an icon no longer in need of a last name. Marilyn is
accorded fame for being a victim -- by strangers who claim to speak
for a woman permanently silenced in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   ''I felt that I was adding an intellectual and spiritual depth
to her that the others didn't give to her,'' said Oates sitting in
her Princeton, N.J. home. ''I certainly didn't think of it as
exploiting a subject. I certainly don't think of a book as doing
any harm.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been scores of books, written by the famous and the
fickle: Norman Mailer, Gloria Steinem, ex-husband Arthur Miller,
half-sister Berniece Baker Miracle, confidante Susan Strasberg.
</P>
<P>
   Mailer, sounding like an over-stimulated adolescent with an
affected vocabulary, called Marilyn a ''Stradivarius of sex'' and
''a sweet peach bursting before one's eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   On the first page of ''Marilyn,'' his 1973 biography, he wrote:
''Take me, said her smile. 'I'm easy. I'm happy. I'm an angel of
sex, you bet.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Mailer declined to be interviewed. ''You can quote from what
he's written,'' said his assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Miller was criticized for ''After the Fall,'' his 1964
two-act play featuring Maggie, a blonde, disturbed, childlike
performer once married to the protagonist.
</P>
<P>
   The playwright was chided not only for borrowing the persona of
his dead ex-wife, but also for employing director Elia Kazan, who
had named Hollywood names to Communist-hunting members of the House
Un-American Activities Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who won a Pulitzer Prize for ''Death of a Salesman,''
does not like to talk about Monroe or their four-year marriage,
which began in 1956. In Oates' book, he is referred to not by name,
but as ''The Playwright.'' Joe DiMaggio, the legendary Yankee
Clipper whose union with Monroe in 1954 lasted nine months, is
''The Ex-Athlete.'' John F. Kennedy's brother-in-law, Peter
Lawford, is ''the President's Pimp.'' Monroe herself is ''the Blond
Actress,'' the ''Beggar Maid,'' the ''Fair Princess'' and ''Miss
Golden Dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, now 84, refused to discuss the literary lure of his
ex-wife. ''I don't know how to answer that,'' he said, reached by
telephone at his Manhattan office. ''You'll have to ask Joyce Carol
Oates that question. I can't help you.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates said she was enticed by an early photograph of Norma Jeane
Baker, a dreamy, needy teen-ager who hadn't yet changed her name.
</P>
<P>
   ''I felt I could identify with this girl,'' Oates said. ''I went
to high school and junior high with girls who looked very much like
that'' -- young women trading on sex in an age when the ability to
please men was a girl's best friend.
</P>
<P>
   But with the women's movement in the 1970s, Gloria Steinem and
other feminists slowly came to embrace Marilyn, to portray her as
independent as well as irrational. Smart and sexy. Vulnerable and
vital.
</P>
<P>
   ''Marilyn Monroe was twice cursed. When I was a child, she was
that naughty woman. When I was learning about feminism, she was
that bimbo,'' said mystery writer Carole Nelson Douglas, who edited
a 1997 collection of short stories created by crime novelists
titled ''Marilyn: Shades of Blonde.''
</P>
<P>
   Hair color dominates many Marilyn titles.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no doubt about the exploitation factor,'' said
Douglas. ''She was exploited all along by the men who made the
movies. A lot of women think we need to reclaim these images, and I
think it's healthy for Marilyn.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's getting a lot more respect these days than she ever did
when she alive. And if exploitation is the price for that, I don't
think there's anything wrong with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Others do. Last year, Miller briefly broke his self-imposed
silence to denounce a Christie's auction of Monroe possessions that
earned $13.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Included was the flesh-colored, sequined gown stitched onto her
so she could sing ''Happy Birthday, Mr. President'' during JFK's
1962 celebration at Madison Square Garden. The see-through dress
originally cost $5,000. It brought $1.15 million at auction.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was gruesome, and even more gruesome is the fact that
nobody seems to think it was gruesome,'' Miller said at the time.
''It's literally like selling the dead.''
</P>
<P>
   According to ''The Marilyn Monroe Encyclopedia'' published last
month, more than 224 authors have sold words about her.
</P>
<P>
   There also have been films, plays, TV movies, posters,
calendars, underwear, lapel buttons, jigsaw puzzles, statuary,
music videos and Thom McAn shoes and clutch bags.
</P>
<P>
   A former gofer on the set of Monroe's 1957 film with Laurence
Olivier, ''The Prince and the Showgirl,'' wrote a book earlier this
year that may take the prize for sleaze and silliness. In ''My Week
With Marilyn,'' 67-year-old Colin Clark claims that he and Monroe
slept together during London production of the movie. All emphasis
on the word sleep.
</P>
<P>
   There was no sex, said Clark.
</P>
<P>
   ''Do you love me, Colin?'' Monroe purportedly asked him,
according to his book.
</P>
<P>
   ''I love you like I love the wind, or the waves or the earth
under my feet or the sun coming out from behind a cloud,'' Clark
answered. ''You are a goddess to millions and millions of people.
Like an ancient Greek goddess, you can come down to Earth every now
and then, but you always remain out of reach to human men.''
</P>
<P>
   To which Marilyn succinctly replied: ''I'm not Greek.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark said he didn't understand public derision that followed
his book.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm mortified that people might think I'm a blackguard,
bragging about my conquests. I say, what a dreadful business.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates said she, too, expects criticism for her Monroe book.
She's seen it before. Her ''Black Water,'' a fictional version of
Chappaquiddick told from the drowning woman's perspective, and
''Zombie,'' a novel about a serial killer taken from the mutilation
and cannibalistic murders of Jeffrey Dahmer, both received mixed
reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Oates' latest work already has been panned.
</P>
<P>
   ''These clumsy attempts to channel her characters' most intimate
thoughts, like her embroidering of already melodramatic events,
cannot help but remind the reader of how shamelessly Ms. Oates is
using the life of Marilyn Monroe as a substitute for inventing an
original story, how shamelessly she is trying to cash in on her
subject's status as a legend,'' wrote Pulitzer Prize-winning book
reviewer Michiko Kakutani in last Friday's New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   ''Though 'Blonde' purports to reveal 'the inner, poetic, and
spiritual life' of the actress, it turns out to be just the latest
effort to exploit the tragedy and fame of Marilyn Monroe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-05-00 1207 </TRAILER>
