<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 12:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1,000 Years at British Library  </HEADLINE>
By AUDREY WOODS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- A 1,000-year-old book of riddles, a 15th-century
love letter and a 20th-century bear named Pooh: All are strands in
the rich history of English literature being celebrated this summer
by the British Library.
</P>
<P>
   This body of literature is ''the thing, above anything else,
that Britain has given to the world in the course of the last
millennium,'' government arts secretary Chris Smith says about the
national library's major exhibit for the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Called ''Chapter and Verse,'' it runs through Oct. 15 at the
vast, red-brick structure near King's Cross rail station that
houses the nation's collection of books, manuscripts and maps.
</P>
<P>
   The literature is not arranged chronologically, but by such
themes as love, loss, laughter, imagination, belonging and strife.
</P>
<P>
   One of the stars of the exhibit is a 1,000-year-old manuscript
of ''Beowulf,'' the Anglo-Saxon epic poem about a Scandinavian
warrior who rids the Danish kingdom of the monster Grendel. Written
in Old English, it is the first known major poem in a European
vernacular language and is believed to have been written in the
sixth century. The library says this copy, by an anonymous scribe,
may have been one of several, but is the only one known to exist.
</P>
<P>
   A prize-winning new translation of ''Beowulf'' by the Irish poet
Seamus Heaney is also part of the exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the 300 items on display are written in the author's
hand, creating an intensely personal tie between the observer and
the likes of William Blake, James Joyce and Sir Arthur Conan Doyle.
</P>
<P>
   The margin notes and crossings-out, the squiggles and lines and
arrows reveal not just the creative process that resulted in an
immortal work of literature but allow the moderately imaginative to
sense they are watching over the author's shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   A book of Joyce's notes for ''Ulysses'' looks like an abstract
drawing, a kind of visual stream of consciousness. It's filled with
small writing every which way over the page and almost entirely
crossed out in red and blue.
</P>
<P>
   A tidier Geoffrey Chaucer looks out from a small portrait in a
lavishly decorated manuscript of the ''Canterbury Tales.'' He is
wearing a jazzy pair of red socks -- the very sort of 14th-century
footwear a fan would expect of such an amusing fellow.
</P>
<P>
   A book at least 1,000 years old contains the riddles of a
religious teacher named Aldhelm who is said to have lured crowds by
singing popular songs. Then, having captured his audience, he
turned to religious subjects. It's not clear when he told the
riddles which, unfortunately, are written in 10th-century Latin
with occasional notes in West Saxon.
</P>
<P>
   In a love letter written in 1477, a Norfolk woman named Margery
Brews tells her beloved John Paston that her father will not
increase her dowry, but ''Yf that ye loff me, as I tryste verely
that ye do, ye will not leffe me therefor.''
</P>
<P>
   She put her trust in the right man. They were married within a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Here, too, you will find Elizabeth Barrett's secret sonnets to
Robert Browning, whom she loved ''to the depth and breadth and
height my soul can reach, when feeling out of sight for the ends of
being and ideal grace.''
</P>
<P>
   Jane Austen has an entire case to herself, displaying a newly
acquired writing desk that is believed to have been given to the
author by her father in 1794. With it is a small pair of spectacles
that have always been in the desk and are believed to be hers.
Manuscript pages of ''Persuasion'' display her small, neat
handwriting.
</P>
<P>
   The mahogany table on which the Bronte sisters did their writing
in the evenings is on loan to the library. It's ink-stained and
candle-burned -- apparently heavily used in the creation of Emily's
''Wuthering Heights,'' Anne's ''Tenant of Wildfell Hall'' and
Charlotte's ''Jane Eyre.''
</P>
<P>
   A section for children's literature is arranged in a
child-friendly way with recordings to hear through earphones.
''Winnie the Pooh'' and ''Robin Hood'' are celebrated there with
other more recent classics. ''Peter Pan'' and ''Alice in
Wonderland'' are placed in the main exhibit in the Imagination
category.
</P>
<P>
   There, too, are J.R.R. Tolkien's ''The Hobbit'' and J.K.
Rowling's stupendously successful 1990s creation, Harry Potter.
</P>
<P>
   A typescript of ''Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone'' is
single-spaced, the author says, in an attempt to conceal that it
exceeded the generally accepted length for children's books.
</P>
<P>
   She is not likely to have to worry about that ever again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-05-00 1208 </TRAILER>
