<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 12:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> On Stage: Anna Deavere Smith  </HEADLINE>
By BETH GARDINER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Anna Deavere Smith doesn't need big costume
changes or lots of props to transform herself into someone else.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing simple black slacks and a crisp white shirt, she just
slips on a tie, picks up a coffee cup or grabs a martini glass and
she's morphed from Abraham Lincoln to George Stephanopoulos,
shifting in between to Anita Hill and Gloria Steinem.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a playwright and performer best known for her one-woman
shows about riots in Los Angeles and Crown Heights, Brooklyn, is
back with a thoughtful, provocative play that seeks to shed light
on the America of today by taking stock of a quintessentially
American institution -- the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   In ''House Arrest,'' now playing at the Public Theater, Smith,
alone on stage, revives a technique she has used to powerful effect
in the past. In just under three hours, she portrays close to 50
real-life characters, re-enacting what they told her in interviews
or -- for those plucked out of history -- reciting words they wrote
or said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith hopes to understand the forces that have shaped America by
looking at the men who have led the country, from Thomas Jefferson
to William Jefferson Clinton. So she sifts through the history of
that most mythologized, most scrutinized American institution,
delving into issues of privacy, the press, power and bigotry.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh off her triumph with ''Twilight: Los Angeles, 1992'' --
about that city's deadly riots -- Smith went to Washington Arena
Stage for a new project in the mid-1990s, long before Monica
Lewinsky and Ken Starr forever changed the public's perception of
the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Its inhabitant, Smith decided, would make the perfect subject
for the next piece in her series, ''On the Road: A Search for
American Character.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I wanted to know, originally, to what extent the president
keeps us together, and to what extent he does not,'' she said
during an interview in a bare, spacious Public Theater rehearsal
room. ''I think we're living in a time now, more than ever, where
it's difficult to conceive of the one person who can have the one
explanation for how we are, and I wanted to know why that was.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to find the answer with ''House Arrest,'' she sings at
one moment in the drunken Scottish brogue of a 19th-century
Jefferson critic and orates the next in the aristocratic Virginian
tones of the third president himself.
</P>
<P>
   Her characters, all real people, living and dead, also include
high-powered Washington pundits, a rural South Carolina churchgoer
and FDR's longtime cook. She invokes them vividly and verbatim,
including every giggle, pause, um and uh as she combines pieces of
conversations and speeches into one smooth montage.
</P>
<P>
   Early versions of ''House Arrest'' were performed in Washington
in 1997 and in Los Angeles in 1998 with a cast of actors. But in
New York City, it opened recently as a one-woman show -- updated
with current events. It runs through April 16 but may be extended,
and Smith is likely to take it on the road, as she did with
''Twilight'' and ''Fires in the Mirror,'' about the 1991 riots in
Crown Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 49, spent more than five years bringing ''House Arrest''
to the stage. She followed Clinton and Bob Dole on the 1996
campaign trail, interviewed three presidents and some 300
journalists, scholars, politicians and government aides, and, with
a team of research assistants, pored through material on Jefferson,
Lincoln and Franklin Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   While the play's first half is historical, Act II focuses
entirely on the Clinton presidency -- sex and politics as only
modern Washington can combine them. Smith pursues the theme
suggested by her title, examining the peculiar paradox of a man who
has immense power but must live with the pressure of being watched
almost constantly.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're a celebrity culture and the president is the celebrity
in chief,'' Stephanopoulos says in the play, portrayed by Smith
with a martini glass in hand. ''The deal is you can do whatever you
want. The price is, everybody's going to know everything you do.''
</P>
<P>
   The scrutiny has a morbid side. Former U.S. News &AMP; World Report
photographer Brian Palmer -- Smith with a red baseball cap pulled on
backwards -- describes how he and his White House colleagues remain
constantly focused on the president during public events, just in
case disaster strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ''You wanna have the president in your view, in your viewfinder,
pretty much all the time,'' he explains.
</P>
<P>
   That's just what Smith does in a gripping segment that combines
past and present, as she re-creates Lincoln's last moments while
training a row of cameras on the doomed president.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you can't write a play about privacy in the White
House without mentioning Lewinsky and that blue dress. Smith
captures the fervid pursuit of sexual wrongdoing that lay beneath
the calm, legalistic face of Starr's investigation when she
performs as one of the special prosecutor's deputies questioning
Clinton for a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let me define 'phone sex' for the purposes of my question,''
the lawyer says in a segment that recalls the complicated language
Washington used to debate the meaning of a very simple act.
</P>
<P>
   The playwright, a Baltimore native who now lives in San
Francisco, sees the Lewinsky investigation as the culmination of a
cynicism that began with the Vietnam War and Watergate and has
grown deeper since.
</P>
<P>
   In today's public life, she said, ''There isn't so much a
pursuit of truth as there is a pursuit of lies. The question is,
how will we ever move out of that? ... Spiritually, it breeds a
dreadful, dreadful cynicism.''
</P>
<P>
   She hopes theater can help reinvolve Americans in the nation's
future, and bridge schisms like the one between blacks and whites.
That's the mission of her Harvard-based Institute on the Arts and
Civic Dialogue. In 1996, the John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur
Foundation gave Smith a so-called ''genius grant'' to promote her
work, and she is also a professor at Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   Her plays' inclusion of so many opposing viewpoints has been
praised for helping promote understanding and letting audiences see
the humanity of those who disagree with them.
</P>
<P>
   ''The mission of my adult life,'' Smith explains, ''is how to
cause communication across boundaries of difference, and how to use
art as part of that mission.''
</P>
<P>
   The rifts associated with color have long interested Smith, and
in ''House Arrest,'' she traces the divides to the nation's
earliest days.
</P>
<P>
   The play begins by musing over Jefferson's internal
contradictions and his complicated legacy. The eloquent and
passionately intellectual author of the Declaration of Independence
owned slaves, believed black people were inferior to whites and did
little to oppose the spread of slavery as America expanded.
</P>
<P>
   In the play, he comes to symbolize the moral ambiguity on which
America was founded, and which haunts us today.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson, Smith quotes documentary filmmaker Ken Burns as
saying, ''ensured that we would inherit the poison of the
indecision on race.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This idea that Jefferson was living in moral ambiguity every
single day of his life, and that there was a shadow side to
everything he did, is a part of human nature,'' Smith said. ''And
the question is, how do we work with the shadow, how do we keep it
in check?''
</P>
<P>
   Bit by bit, she answers herself, opening one mind at a time,
optimistic that America's deepest wounds can be healed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Slavery was a big mistake, so that seems to me to indicate
that there can also be a big lesson,'' she says. ''I don't know
that I will live to see the great symphony, the sort of Beethoven's
Ninth of America, but I believe that will happen in the next
century, and plan on living whatever time I have left to push that
along.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
