<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 12:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Down 137.44; Nasdaq Down 27.43  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks turned lower today as investors
beaten down and bewildered by Tuesday's wild market stopped
punishing technology stocks, but decided it was time to start
taking profits from other sectors that ran up last week.
</P>
<P>
   In midday trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was down 137.44 at 11,027.40, having given up an early
gain. American Express, down 2} to 144\, and J.P. Morgan, down 3 to
133 1/16, led the decline.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index was down 27.43 at 4,121.46, having
recovered from a drop of 139.80 earlier in the session.
</P>
<P>
   Volume was fairly modest, but the volatility that marked
Tuesday's session remained, sending the indexes fluctuating between
positive and negative territory.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was down 15.38 at 1,479.35, and the Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies was up 7.91 to 508.57.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks fell at the opening bell as traders struggled to find
their footing after Tuesday's chaotic selloff, when both the Nasdaq
and the Dow fell more than 500 points only to finish the turbulent
session with modest, double-digit losses.
</P>
<P>
   The wildness on Wall Street rattled most overseas markets,
making it difficult for the U.S. market to mount any real recovery.
In Japan, the Nikkei stock average fell 0.6 percent, with
technology shares leading the decline. In afternoon trading,
Germany's DAX index was down 2.6 percent and France's CAC-40 was
down 3.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In London, the FT-SE 100 index was down 2.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As the New York session wore on, some Wall Street investors went
looking for bargains, but there wasn't much enthusiasm, analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We see it more as the eye of the storm,'' said Gail Dudack,
chief investment strategist at Warburg Dillon Read in New York.
''The danger for the market place has not ended.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks were mixed. Microsoft fell 2 3/16 to 86] and
Qualcomm, a wireless communications company that led the Nasdaq's
advance in 1999, fell 6 9/16 to 140 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   Applied Materials, a leading maker of computer chip equipment,
rose 4\ to 102].
</P>
<P>
   Financial and consumer goods stocks, which rose sharply last
week, slipped as investors nervously took profits. Procter &AMP; Gamble
fell 1 7/16 to 62.
</P>
<P>
   Other stocks that are representatives of the ''old economy''
continued to fare better. Sears rose 4 9/16 to 35 1/16 after saying
it expects first-quarter profits to beat expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The market received a vote of confidence today from Abby Joseph
Cohen, chief investment strategist at Goldman Sachs, who spoke at a
White House conference on the new economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''For the past decade, we have been enthusiastic about the
outlook for U.S. stock prices in the United States, and we remain
so,'' Cohen said. She said the long-running bull market had been
driven by steady economic gains and therefore was justified.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Cohen's recommendation that clients put some of their
stock holdings into cash sparked a round of selling on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Later today, Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan was
scheduled to discuss the Internet and productivity at the same
conference.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, declining issues led advancers
by a 10-to-9 margin. On the Nasdaq, decliners led by a 5-to-4
margin.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE volume was 504.18 million shares, well behind Tuesday's
chaotic pace.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
