<HEADLINE> Britain Not Warned of Rover Sale  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Britain's trade secretary, criticized for failing
to avert the sale of Rover cars and the likely loss of thousands of
jobs, said Wednesday he had no chance to act because BMW gave no
warning of the sale.
</P>
<P>
   The German automaker played its cards ''very close to its
chest'' in the months before deciding to sell its loss-making
subsidiary, Trade and Industry Secretary Stephen Byers said during
two hours of questions by a parliamentary select committee.
</P>
<P>
   Rover chairman Walter Samann outlined a plan to stem Rover's
mounting losses when he met Byers on March 10 -- six days before the
BMW board voted to sell Rover.
</P>
<P>
   BMW had given the impression that it was ''business at usual''
at Rover despite daily losses of $3.2 million in 1999 and that it
was continuing with planned investment at its Longbridge Plant in
Birmingham, where 8,000 jobs are now at risk.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were not given information that BMW (was) considering
breaking up Rover and selling Longbridge,'' Byers said.
</P>
<P>
   BMW announced in mid-March its plan to sell Rover to a group of
British venture capitalists, Alchemy. The group has no experience
with auto-making, and has acknowledged that job losses are
inevitable as the plant becomes a niche producer of sports cars
under the name MG Car Co.
</P>
<P>
   Alchemy hopes to post a profit within three years and sell the
company within seven.
</P>
<P>
   Labor union leaders fear Rover will be allowed to die and
thousands of jobs will die with the company. They are trying to
find another buyer for the car group, but the response has been
torpid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
