<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dio Unleashes 'Magica'  </HEADLINE>
By GERARD O'LEARY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Heavy-metal singer Ronnie James Dio takes a sip
of herbal tea, collects his thoughts and reflects on his longevity
in the world of hard rock.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you do anything with quality, I think it will always
last,'' he said. ''Back in the early days of rock -- with Presley
and Little Richard -- people said that wouldn't last, but as history
tells us, it did.''
</P>
<P>
   Dio has lasted long enough to earn the title of ''legend,''
bestowed on him by fans and music insiders alike.
</P>
<P>
   ''I try to give the fans what they want even though rock 'n'
roll is very generational; you try to keep your main fan base
happy,'' he said. ''I knew from early on that if I do it well, my
music would always be accepted.''
</P>
<P>
   His career began in the late 1960s with Elf. When legendary
guitarist Ritchie Blackmore left Deep Purple in 1975, he enlisted
Elf's rhythm section and Dio's amazing vocals for his new band.
Rainbow recorded four albums before Dio and Blackmore parted ways
in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Dio then became known as a hired gun.
</P>
<P>
   He joined Black Sabbath to replace charismatic frontman Ozzy
Osbourne in 1979. He rejuvenated the popularity of Sabbath and
brought the band back on top.
</P>
<P>
   After three years with Sabbath, Dio left to form his own band.
He recruited guitarist Vivian Campbell, who went on to a successful
career with Whitesnake and Def Leppard, drummer Vinny Appice and
bassist Jimmy Bain. The band skyrocketed to success after the
release of its debut album ''Holy Diver.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyrically superior to many groups, Dio became known as the
thinking man's band with its array of subjects from mythology and
Arthurian legend to science fiction.
</P>
<P>
   ''Being an only child, I found comfort in reading books,'' Dio
said. ''Books by Walter Scott and books like the 'Knights of the
Round Table' and 'Mists of Avalon' have inspired my lyrics and the
way I want to tell a story.''
</P>
<P>
   Dio's tours were legendary, with the stage almost as big as an
aircraft carrier and with enough lights to power a small town.
</P>
<P>
   ''We would spend a half-million dollars on our tours,'' he said.
''We had a huge dragon, lights and lasers that we toured around the
world with for two years.''
</P>
<P>
   With the popularity of heavy metal currently at a standstill,
Dio said he's just bringing out the band and giving fans what's
most important -- the music.
</P>
<P>
   ''Magica'' (Spitfire Records) is his first concept album.
</P>
<P>
   ''The concept album was something I wanted to do for a long
time, and was pretty easy because you have a plan,'' he explained.
''You write a song about this guy or that place, suddenly you have
lyrics to go with a song and the story line falls into place.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Magica'' takes the listener on a mystical journey to a land
known as Blessing, where evil comes to destroy good. ''It tells of
how tyrants separate the old from the young and indoctrinate the
young with their own twisted ideas,'' Dio said.
</P>
<P>
   The album contains references to the holocaust. The evil ruler
Shadowlife begins to exterminate the people of Blessing and tries
to gain complete power.
</P>
<P>
   ''That is what tyrants do, they separate the people and burn all
their books and make them conform to their own beliefs,'' Dio said.
''And we can never forget that time in history.''
</P>
<P>
   The band consists of guitar virtuoso Craig Goldie, who replaced
Campbell in 1986, bassist Jimmy Bain and former AC/DC drummer Simon
Wright.
</P>
<P>
   The songs are a throwback to vintage Dio, a mixture of ''Holy
Diver'' and ''Last in Line.'' The tracks ''Fever Dreams'' and
''Turn to Stone'' give Dio fans what they want: good old-fashioned
heavy metal.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Pat Boone released ''In a Metal Mood: No More Mr. Nice
Guy,'' a tongue-in-cheek collection of classic heavy metal hits
rearranged to a jazzy easy-listening format. Boone covered Dio's
''Holy Diver.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I asked Pat, 'Do you know what this song is about?' and he
answered, 'It's not a Christian song,''' Dio said with a smile. ''I
told him, 'In actuality. ... the song is about Christ.'''
</P>
<P>
   Dio will be touring most of the year in support of his new
album.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Ronnie James Dio Official Web site:
http://www.ronniejamesdio.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-05-00 1336 </TRAILER>
