<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Underwood's Frenetic Lifestyle  </HEADLINE>
By ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blair Underwood is back in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that he's lived there for 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   Underwood, who played a young lawyer on the TV series ''L.A.
Law,'' now stars with Vivica A. Fox on the Los Angeles-based
medical drama ''City of Angels'' on CBS (Wednesday, 8 p.m. EDT).
</P>
<P>
   He also appears in the new film ''Rules of Engagement,''
directed by William Friedkin and starring Tommy Lee Jones and
Samuel L. Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   But Underwood manages to take this frenetic lifestyle in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ''In Los Angeles, there is such a drive for stardom and
celebrity,'' he said in an interview. ''It all becomes about the
showcase to get a pilot or a movie. But there's a balance. You can
take the work seriously, but not take yourself too seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Underwood, 35, certainly takes an earnest approach to his work.
He is committed to making the characters he plays believable -- and
is willing to endure some rigorous training to do so.
</P>
<P>
   For ''Rules of Engagement,'' military technical adviser Dale Dye
(who also worked on the set of ''Saving Private Ryan'') trained
Underwood and 30 other men in modern desert warfare to prepare them
for their roles as U.S. Marines.
</P>
<P>
   ''We spent seven days and six nights in basic training in the
Sahara desert in Morocco. Dye did not allow us to speak of
filmmaking or Hollywood. So we all really bonded, and by the time
we started filming, we were like a well-oiled machine,'' Underwood
said.
</P>
<P>
   He also drew from his childhood as an ''Army brat.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I was raised in an Army family. My father retired as a
full-bird colonel. So I have a tremendous understanding of what it
is to follow orders. I was raised with great discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Rules of Engagement'' is about a Marine officer (Jackson) who
is court-martialed for allegedly breaking the military's rules of
combat during a siege on the U.S. Embassy in Yemen. Underwood plays
Capt. Lee, who carries out the officer's command to open fire on a
crowd of protesters. The gunfire kills 80 civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Although he calls his time in basic training ''the most
extraordinary acting exercise I'd ever had,'' Underwood doesn't
think there is any special formula for taking on a certain role.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have to believe whatever you're doing in order to make the
audience believe what you're doing. Whatever it takes for you to
believe it is what's necessary for you to do,'' he said
</P>
<P>
   To prepare for the role of Dr. Ben Turner, chief of surgery at
the inner-city Angels of Mercy hospital on ''City of Angels,''
Underwood observed doctors performing brain surgeries and spent
nights in a trauma ward.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wanted to absorb the technical aspects of surgery and the
atmosphere of a hospital. I wanted to feel the demeanor of doctors,
how they interacted under the everyday stress of their work and in
trauma situations,'' he said
</P>
<P>
   ''City of Angels'' has a predominantly black cast, and black
directors and writers are key elements of the show. Underwood knows
that many people regard the series as an effort to put minority
characters on center stage.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot is riding on this show,'' he said. ''Most of the
so-called black shows on television are comedies. A lot of people
in Hollywood felt that a black drama could not succeed, that a
white audience won't watch a show with black leads.''
</P>
<P>
   But he is confident that the tide is turning for the success of
black dramas.
</P>
<P>
   ''People are smart enough to get beyond racial issues. They
either enjoy the show or not on its own merit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So how does Underwood manage to relax?
</P>
<P>
   ''Movies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When Underwood and his wife are not spending time with their two
young children, they take off for the local theater.
</P>
<P>
   ''We get popcorn, Raisinettes and a Coke and watch movies.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Rules of Engagement official site: http://www.rulesmovie.com
</P>
<P>
   City of Angels:
http://www.cbs.com/network/tvshows/primetime/shows/cityofangels
</P>
<P>
   End Adv for Immediate Release
</P>
</TEXT>
