<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> London Trading Extended After Halt  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The London Stock Exchange sputtered back to life
Wednesday after a technical fault forced the suspension of trading
for most of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The computer failure, which lasted 7{ hours, was the worst ever
experienced by Europe's biggest exchange. Trading finally resumed
at 3:30 p.m. (10:30 a.m. EDT).
</P>
<P>
   The market was paralyzed during what should have been one of its
busiest sessions -- the last day of the British tax year. Untold
numbers of people may have missed out on a chance to buy or sell
shares in a last-minute attempt to minimize their liability for
capital gains tax.
</P>
<P>
   The shutdown also came at a time of extreme uncertainty on
equity markets around the world, following the most volatile
session in Wall Street's history on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The breakdown coincided with a report in the Financial Times
that the London and Frankfurt stock exchanges were holding initial
talks about a possible merger.
</P>
<P>
   ''The timing could not have been worse,'' said Jim Wood-Smith,
head of research at London brokerage Greig Middleton.
</P>
<P>
   The computer failure wiped out accurate price data starting at 8
a.m. (3 a.m. EDT), the market's normal opening hour.
</P>
<P>
   Once the system was up and running, the exchange announced
extended trading hours until 8:00 p.m. (3 p.m. EDT) to help make up
for some of the time lost.
</P>
<P>
   The problem stemmed from a fault in the electronic feed that
transmits prices from the exchange to dealers' screens. To fix it,
technicians turned off all computer links with the exchange, a move
that also deprived investors and dealers of key announcements by
companies listed on the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been a very bad advertisement for the City of London.
This is not going to make us look good on the world stage,'' said
Mark Dampier, of the brokerage Hargreaves Lansdown.
</P>
<P>
   The shutdown came just two days after another less dramatic
glitch.
</P>
<P>
   Trading was disrupted Monday morning when the Financial
Times-Stock Exchange 100 Share Index of blue chip stocks and other
indexes could not be obtained due to a computer problem at the
financial information service group, Reuters PLC.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, unlike Wednesday, prices of individual shares
could still be obtained.
</P>
<P>
   Shares fell after trading resumed, with the Financial
Times-Stock Exchange 100 Share Index down 118.4 points, or 1.8
percent, at 6,308.6 in late trading.
</P>
<P>
   ''The market's a non-event and we'll just start again
tomorrow,'' said Leonard White, a trader at Daiwa SBCM Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The government's Financial Services Authority later announced an
investigation into Wednesday's collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ''The FSA sees the failure of major trading systems to open as a
serious matter that requires a prompt and thorough response,'' the
watchdog agency said in a statement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-05-00 1339 </TRAILER>
