<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll shows more people think New York City a good place to live  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- More than half of New York voters statewide
approve of how New York City police are doing their job and think
that the city is safer than it was five years ago, a statewide poll
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Quinnipiac College Polling Institute poll taken in
the wake of the Patrick Dorismond slaying by an NYPD officer showed
that 3 in 4 black voters disapproved of the police and only 13
percent had a favorable opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Quinnipiac Director Maurice Carroll said the breakdown was not
surprising since ''New York City has this racial split about the
cops.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorismond, a Brooklyn native of Haitian descent, was fatally
shot by undercover narcotics police in Manhattan. The incident,
coming just after four other city police officers were acquitted of
criminal charges in the slaying of Amadou Diallo, has outraged
black activists throughout the city.
</P>
<P>
   And while half of upstate voters and 64 percent of suburban
voters voiced their approval of New York City police, city
residents weren't so positive.
</P>
<P>
   Among city residents, 50 percent say they disapprove of the
police while 40 percent approved. Ten percent say they don't know
or had no opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll attributed distance as a factor in the disparity in
attitudes about the NYPD. While three-fourths of New York City
residents followed the Dorismond case somewhat or very closely, 68
percent of suburban voters and only 35 percent of upstate voters
paid attention.
</P>
<P>
   ''Familiarity dissipates and the attitude changes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most black voters (87 percent) and 58 percent of New York City
voters also believe that police in New York City generally use
excessive force against minority suspects even as the statewide
count found only 39 percent of voters have that opinion.
</P>
<P>
   But there is overwhelming agreement among voters -- nearly 70
percent -- that undercover police operations are a good idea. Black
voters also favored undercover operations, but the numbers were
lower, at 47 percent.
</P>
<P>
   New York City was deemed safer by 52 percent of voters across
the state. In addition, More than two-thirds of voters polled think
the city is a good place to live and 32 percent of those living
outside New York City say they're now more likely to visit the city
than five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Quinnipiac's telephone poll of 1,058 registered voters was
conducted March 28-April 3 and has a margin of error of plus or
minus 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of voters believe that NYPD will fight crime more
effectively if New York City concentrates on building good
community relations.
</P>
<P>
   The New York City Police Benevolent Association was not
immediately available for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
