<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Bank Merger Called Off  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE BOEHMER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Dresdner Bank AG has called off its
merger with rival Deutsche Bank AG after clashes over how to
integrate their operations, only a month after announcing a $30
billion deal to create one of the world's largest banks.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse, revealed Wednesday, was seen as a major
embarrassment for some of Germany's most esteemed corporate names,
and analysts called it a lost opportunity to begin the shake-up
many believe is needed to compete globally.
</P>
<P>
   ''A true chance for German banks is over,'' said Volker von
Kruechten, analyst at BHF Bank in Frankfurt. ''This deal would have
allowed the restructuring of the German banking sector.''
</P>
<P>
   In a terse statement, Dresdner said its management board
''unanimously decided to discontinue the merger process'' with the
bigger Deutsche Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Dresdner said that although the two banks had agreed to a
''merger of equals,'' Deutsche Bank proceeded after the deal was
announced March 9 to try to sell off Dresdner's investment banking
arm, Dresdner Kleinwort Benson.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank chairman Rolf Breuer denied that the merger was
ever intended to be one of equals. Deutsche was to hold close to
two-thirds of the combined banks, and Dresdner the rest.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, Breuer said ''no solution acceptable to
both sides could be found'' over the fate of Dresdner Kleinwort
Benson.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were not impressed with the planned merger, sending
both banks' share prices down more than 20 percent over the past
month.
</P>
<P>
   After a brief suspension of trading in Frankfurt on Wednesday,
both banks saw their stock prices climb more than 3 percent on the
day, with Deutsche finishing up 3.19 euros to 80.01 euros ($77.18)
and Dresdner closing up 2 euros to 49 euros ($43.28)
</P>
<P>
   However, shares in the Allianz insurance giant, a major
shareholder that had helped bring the two banks together, fell
nearly 14 percent when trading resumed, falling 61.16 euros to 380
euros ($365.50). Allianz had stood to gain a significant stake in
the two banks' retail operations as well as majority control of
Deutsche Bank's jewel DWS fund manager and insurer Deutscher
Herold.
</P>
<P>
   A major aim of the deal was to unravel the stakes Deutsche and
Dresdner have in Munich-based Allianz and vice versa. Currently
Deutsche Bank holds a 7 percent stake in Allianz, while Dresdner
holds 10 percent. Allianz holds 21.5 percent of Dresdner and 4.9
percent of Deutsche.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank, Germany's largest, swallowed New York-based
Bankers Trust last year, raising its total assets to $840 billion.
The merger with Germany's No. 3 player, Dresdner, would have
boosted assets to $1.2 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   That would have put the combined institution just behind the
Mizuho Financial Group of Japan, which announced last August it was
creating an institution with $1.3 trillion in assets by merging
Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank, Fuji Bank, and the Industrial Bank of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Freed of unprofitable retail operations, the combined German
behemoth wanted to focus on lucrative investment banking and global
expansion. Breuer said, however, that Deutsche planned no other
mergers for now.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated with their own uncertain futures, employees at both
banks were already defecting to other institutions.
</P>
<P>
   T.J. Lim, head of Dresdner Kleinwort Benson's fixed-income
division and a member of the merger integration team, quit Tuesday.
And Salomon Smith Barney earlier this week poached seven analysts
from Dresdner Kleinwort Benson.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Dobson, head of Deutsche Bank's asset management
division, resigned shortly after the merger was announced.
</P>
<P>
   The merger was expected to save the company $2.8 billion by
wiping out overlapping operations. But German unions and some
politicians had complained about plans to close about 800 of their
combined 2,500 branches, resulting in an estimated 16,000 layoffs,
mostly in Germany.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
