<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Plans for Pan-American Exposition centennial party slow going  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Organizers of a centennial celebration to
commemorate the 1901 Pan-American Exposition have already scaled
back their original grandiose plans.
</P>
<P>
   Now, even their hopes for a more modest celebration are fading
as they battle apparent apathy from corporate and government
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're limping along,'' said Robert Skerker, a co-chairman of
the Pan-Am 2001 Committee.
</P>
<P>
   More than 8 million visitors attended the 1901 event in Buffalo.
A Los Angeles consulting firm hired by a Pan-Am committee in 1998
predicted 1.5 million to 2 million visitors might attend events
over a five-month period during the centennial.
</P>
<P>
   But organizers have been unable to persuade top political and
business leaders to line up with funding for the project.
</P>
<P>
   ''The difficulty we so often have in accomplishing things in
this community reared its head,'' Kerry Grant, one of several
people who have been discussing the centennial since 1996, told The
Buffalo News.
</P>
<P>
   The consultants recommended a smorgasbord of events under one
umbrella, with possible themes being the Canadian border, Buffalo
as a transportation ''gateway to the West,'' the Erie Canal, the
city's historic grain milling industry and the assassination of
President William McKinley at the 1901 exposition, and Theodore
Roosevelt's subsequent inauguration in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   The celebration envisioned by MCM Group International would
carry a $40.9 million operating budget, plus a $9 million
''elective capital budget.''
</P>
<P>
   The firm forecast revenues totaling $50.6 million, including $30
million from corporate sponsors, ''yielding a break-even event''
but it also assumed ''a 25 percent funding subsidy from various
city, regional and state government sources.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Rudnick, president of the Buffalo Niagara Partnership,
said the business organization was never courted for the Pan-Am
once the exploratory planning phase ended.
</P>
<P>
   Skerker said he was told the group was too busy to get involved.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, individual groups are moving ahead with plans to
observe the Pan-Am's 100th anniversary. They agree all would
benefit from an umbrella group to package and sell the celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there were a coordinating entity, it would raise the
visibility and credibility of some things that are going on and
make fund raising easier,'' said William Siener, executive director
of the Buffalo and Erie County Historical Society. The society's
Greek Revival building is the only original exposition structure
still standing on the site and will be the site of a visitor
center.
</P>
<P>
   Other centennial plans in the works include conferences and
events focusing on female contributions to the 1901 exhibition and
a documentary for public television on the exhibition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-05-00 1446 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
