<HEADLINE> Bush Backer To Focus on Congress  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Texas entrepreneur who spent $2.5 million on
ads touting George W. Bush's environmental record plans to
reorganize his Republicans for Clean Air to focus on Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The group will lobby lawmakers on clean-air issues and also air
issue ads meant to influence congressional races, spokeswoman Mona
Taylor said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A day earlier, Sam Wyly said he was getting out of presidential
politics, noting that his TV efforts had failed to garner attention
for environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
   Wyly's group will use direct mail and an Internet site to
recruit support and dues-paying members, Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Wyly, who with his brother has donated more than $210,000 to
Bush, stirred the presidential campaign last month with TV ads that
praised Bush's environmental record and criticized rival John
McCain. The ads were strongly criticized by the McCain camp, which
said they were an improper effort by Bush. The Bush campaign denied
any connection.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech Tuesday in Seattle, Wyly said the ads during the
presidential primaries were not effective in publicizing his
message about environmentally friendly power and that he would not
be making any more.
</P>
<P>
   ''Many of you are aware of my recent foray into presidential
politics. I have already decided it is to be my last,'' he said
upon receiving an award from the Climate Institute. ''I thought I
had a clever idea to get America to focus on the clean air issue
and to help my presidential candidate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
