<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Up 122.66; Dow Down 76.32  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks moved higher today as
investors shook off memories of Tuesday's head-spinning selloff and
stepped in looking for bargains. Blue-chip stocks fell, although
losses were contained.
</P>
<P>
   With an hour remaining in Wall Street's regular session, the
Nasdaq composite index was up 122.66 at 4,271.55, having recovered
from a drop of 139.80 earlier in the session.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was down 76.32 at 11,088.52
after giving up an early gain.
</P>
<P>
   Volume was fairly modest, but the volatility that marked
Tuesday's session remained.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mostly higher. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index was up 6.50 at 1,501.23, and the Russell 2000
index of smaller companies was up 24.10 at 524.66.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks fell at the opening bell as traders struggled to find
their footing after Tuesday's chaotic selloff, when both the Nasdaq
and the Dow fell more than 500 points only to finish the turbulent
session with modest, double-digit losses.
</P>
<P>
   The wildness on Wall Street rattled most overseas markets,
making it difficult for the U.S. market to mount any real recovery
in the early going.
</P>
<P>
   But as the session wore on, bargain-hunting investors stepped
in, their confidence boosted by some calming words from major
market movers.
</P>
<P>
   This morning, Abby Joseph Cohen, chief investment strategist at
Goldman Sachs, delivered an upbeat message at a White House
conference on the new economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''For the past decade, we have been enthusiastic about the
outlook for U.S. stock prices in the United States, and we remain
so,'' Cohen said. She said the long-running bull market had been
driven by steady economic gains and therefore was justified.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Cohen's recommendation that clients put some of their
stock holdings into cash sparked a round of selling on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   In early afternoon, the market drew some additional support from
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, who gave credit to the
''extraordinary surge in technological innovation'' for America's
current record-breaking economy.
</P>
<P>
   Even as investors returned to the market, most confined their
technology buying to the best-known names. Applied Materials, a
leading maker of computer chip equipment, rose 11\ to 109]. Oracle
rose 4{ to 80 7/16. Hewlett-Packard rose 9[ to 147\.
</P>
<P>
   Financial and consumer goods stocks, which rose sharply last
week, slipped as investors nervously took profits. Procter &AMP; Gamble
fell ~ to 62| and J.P. Morgan fell 2~ to 133 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   Other stocks that are representatives of the ''old economy''
continued to fare better. Sears rose 5 9/16 to 36 1/16 after saying
it expects first-quarter profits to beat expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Even as stocks stabilized, some analysts remained skeptical of
the market's strength.
</P>
<P>
   ''We see it more as the eye of the storm,'' said Gail Dudack,
chief investment strategist at Warburg Dillon Read in New York.
''The danger for the market place has not ended.''
</P>
<P>
   Breadth was improving. On the New York Stock Exchange, advancing
issues led decliners by a 4-to-3 margin. On the Nasdaq, advancers
overtook decliners by a 5-to-4 margin.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE volume was 896.87 million shares, well behind Tuesday's
chaotic pace.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
