<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nabisco Asks Icahn To Join Bidding  </HEADLINE>
By MATT MOORE, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A day after Carl Icahn proposed buying Nabisco
Group Holdings Corp. for $16 a share, Nabisco Group's chairman
invited the suitor to join the process the company's financial
advisors have set up to assure shareholders get the best deal.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman Steven F. Goldstone told Icahn in a letter released
today that by doing so, Icahn could qualify to obtain confidential
information and would be informed about the procedures for
presenting a formal bid.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our board will consider all bona fide proposals at the
appropriate time,'' Goldstone wrote.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Icahn said he was willing to pay $16 per share for
the 90.5 percent of Group Nabisco he doesn't already own. That
would value the company at $5.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   It was an improvement on his proposal last week to pay $13 a
share under certain conditions for about 30 percent of Group
Nabisco shares.
</P>
<P>
   In afternoon trading today, Nabisco Group shares were up 50
cents a share at $15 on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Parsippany, N.J.-based Nabisco Group is the successor to RJR
Nabisco Holdings which spun off its tobacco holdings to
shareholders last June amid mounting legal challenges to cigarette
companies. Icahn, who had made three unsuccessful efforts to unseat
the RJR board, wanted RJR to spin off its food holdings instead.
</P>
<P>
   Since the split, Nabisco Group has retained an 80.6 percent
stake in Nabisco Holdings, maker of Oreo, Chips Ahoy!, Newtons,
Ritz crackers and Snackwells. The company also makes condiments
such as Grey Poupon mustard as well as Milk-Bone dog biscuits.
</P>
<P>
   Nomi Ghez, an analyst with Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., said Nabisco
Group's board is likely to find itself caught in a bidding war,
which would benefit shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the board of directors will say they will consider the
offer,'' Ghez said Tuesday. ''But essentially it puts the companies
on the block and Icahn and anyone else could bid up for them.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sometimes terse letter to Nabisco Group's board of
directors, Icahn offered to buy the company on a ''friendly basis''
and said ''there should be no problem in facilitating the
acquisition of NGH, especially in light of the large amount of
capital my companies would contribute to the transaction.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Nabisco Group's board passed on Icahn's original
offer of $13 per share saying it didn't accurately convey the true
worth of the company's operations. The company also said it was
exploring the sale of the company or its majority stake in Nabisco
Holdings.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, Icahn chided the company's directors, saying:
''If you are not willing to go forward with me and do not
officially put the company up for sale now, stockholders can only
conclude that your press release was simply designed to give them
false hopes and prevent your losing a proxy contest.''
</P>
<P>
   Icahn said he believes the company is undervalued, even at $16
per share, but he didn't want to see the company given away for
something less.
</P>
<P>
   ''From my point of view I want to be sure that they're sincere
about putting it up for sale,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
