<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 15:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> $40B Set Aside for Aviation  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton on Wednesday signed a bill
that designates $40 billion for aviation improvements, from airport
construction to collision-avoidance systems and safety standards
for traveling pets.
</P>
<P>
   The Wendell H. Ford Aviation Investment and Reform Act for the
21st Century increases aviation spending by more than $10 billion
beyond current levels over three years. It seeks to accommodate an
expected burst in air travel from 600 million passengers last year
to more than 1 billion by the end of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the improvements, Clinton said he is still concerned
that there will not be sufficient funding in the future for air
traffic control and other safety functions.
</P>
<P>
   ''I call on Congress to join me in moving forward to further
system-wide reform of air traffic control,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bud Shuster, R-Pa., chairman of the House Transportation
and Infrastructure Committee, said the bill would be a great relief
to an overburdened aviation system. He was particularly pleased
that money from ticket taxes will be dedicated solely to improving
safety and efficiency in the aviation system.
</P>
<P>
   ''Air travelers are the big winners,'' Shuster said in a
statement. ''This new law will make our skies safer and help to
improve air service in our big cities and in our small
communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Aiming to increase flights to smaller markets, the bill phases
out flight limits at Chicago's O'Hare in 2002 and at New York's
LaGuardia and JFK in 2007. It permits 24 more flights out of
Washington's Reagan National, including 12 beyond the current
1,250-mile ''perimeter rule,'' which limits the distance planes can
travel nonstop into and out of the airport.
</P>
<P>
   The bill allows airports to raise their passenger taxes, or
''passenger facility charges'' from the current ceiling of $3 to
$4.50 a person, a move which could bring in an extra $700 million a
year for local airport projects.
</P>
<P>
   Also included in the bill are provisions to help airlines buy
regional jets if they use them to serve small airports, money to
improve the training of airport screeners, requirements for
emergency locator devices on small jets and guidelines for air
tours over national parks.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   The White House: www.whitehouse.gov
</P>
<P>
   Bill summary: www.house.gov/transportation
</P>
</TEXT>
