<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Further Testimony in Marine's Death  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- A Marine captain accused in the
heat-stroke death of a reservist during a training march brushed
off concerns about the hike's fast pace, a sergeant testified
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Victor Arana, 28, is charged with dereliction of duty and
failure to obey an order in the death last year of Lance Cpl.
Giuseppe ''Joey'' Leto, 21. Arana could get up to nine months in
prison if convicted in the non-jury court-martial.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Timothy Lucas, a squad instructor in Arana's company, said
he complained to Arana that the pace was too fast and that the 180
Marines were ''spread out real bad.'' Lucas said Arana told him
that ''we weren't going that fast and to tighten up.''
</P>
<P>
   The sergeant said he then pushed the Marines, each carrying up
to 30 pounds of gear, to hurry up.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys begin presenting their side Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Leto died July 7 after an eight-mile nighttime hike in 80-degree
temperatures at Camp Lejeune. Prosecutors say Arana marched his
unit too fast and without enough time for rest breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers contend Arana wasn't given proper guidance by
his superiors. Outside of court Wednesday, attorney Mark Stevens
described Arana as ''a sacrificial lamb.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, Sgt. Jonathan Ginsberg, who was Leto's squad
leader, testified that Arana skipped a two-minute gear assessment
break during the first leg of the hike. He said he told Arana
during the first rest stop that the company was marching too fast.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Ginsberg testified, Arana said ''tell them three
(more) minutes, we've got to get there sometime.''
</P>
<P>
   Ginsberg said one Marine was evacuated by helicopter to a
hospital for heat problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
