<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Rebound  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures rebounded Wednesday on
the Chicago Board of Trade, finishing mostly higher in a technical
recovery to the previous day's Wall Street-inspired selloff.
</P>
<P>
   Soybeans led the way, regaining a majority of the ground that
prices lost Tuesday when funds took profits on agricultural
commodities to cover their losses in equities.
</P>
<P>
   Market-watchers said rumors that China had purchased a cargo of
U.S. soybeans also underpinned the mild rally.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat prices were near flat. The late rally in soybeans pushed
wheat into positive territory for the session after being under
early pressure from generally good conditions for the winter wheat
crop. Sri Lanka's purchase of U.S. wheat also helped the market,
traders said.
</P>
<P>
   Corn finished mixed, as support related to the stock market's
regained equilibrium was offset by pressure from slightly wetter
forecasts for Midwest growing regions this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for May delivery rose { cent to $2.56\ a bushel; May corn
was unchanged at $2.32 a bushel; July oats rose \ cent to $1.20{ a
bushel; May soybeans rose 4{ cents to $5.43 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Beef futures advanced while pork futures retreated on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   June live cattle rose .43 cent to 69.10 cents a pound; May
feeder cattle rose .58 cent to 83.75 cents a pound; June lean hogs
fell .13 cent to 72.32 cents a pound; May pork bellies fell .42
cent to 95.15 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
