<HEADLINE> Iran: Jewish Suspects Get Lawyers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) -- Iran's judiciary has agreed to allow 13
Iranian Jews accused of spying to hire their own lawyers, Iran's
only Jewish legislator said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The statement by Manouchehr Eliassi came after conflicting
reports suggested the defendants would have to use state-appointed
lawyers for the espionage trial.
</P>
<P>
   Iran's Jewish Society had urged Monday that the suspects be
allowed to choose their own lawyers. But Iranian officials had said
the court had appointed lawyers for the suspects because they had
missed the deadline for choosing their own.
</P>
<P>
   The society also asked for a delay in the espionage trial, which
is due to begin April 13 in Shiraz, 550 miles south of the capital,
Tehran.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't known whether the court will agree to postpone the
trial.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects, arrested more than a year ago, are accused of
spying for the United States and Israel. If convicted, they could
be executed. The U.S. and Israeli governments have denied any ties
to the suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Iran, which has been under international pressure to free the
Jews or ensure that their trial is fair, says religion has no
bearing on the case.
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish society also asked that the suspects be freed on bail
for this month's Jewish holiday of Passover, with the release also
covering Ashoura, a period when Muslim Shiites mourn the death of
their most revered saint. Ashoura is April 15.
</P>
<P>
   There were 80,000 Jews in Iran just before the 1979 Islamic
revolution, but the community has dwindled to 25,000. It remains
the largest Jewish community in the Middle East outside Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Iranian Jews are allowed to practice aspects of their religion,
but are forbidden to teach Hebrew, the liturgical language.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
