<HEADLINE> Congress Seeking Key Documents  </HEADLINE>
By PETE YOST, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The chairmen of the House and Senate Judiciary
committees demanded Wednesday that the Justice Department turn over
key memos on its decision not to appoint an independent counsel to
investigate Democratic fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Attorney General Janet Reno, Rep. Henry Hyde,
R-Ill., and Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, asked for memos by former
fund-raising task force chief Charles LaBella and FBI Director
Louis Freeh that favor an independent counsel to investigate the
conduct of Vice President Al Gore and other top Clinton
administration officials.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the letter requested a memo by Lee Radek, chief of
the department's public integrity section, who opposed appointment
of an independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Reno in the past has refused to give the LaBella and Freeh memos
to another congressional committee.
</P>
<P>
   Also signing the letter were Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., and Rep.
Charles Canady, R-Fla., who head subcommittees.
</P>
<P>
   Among other documents covered by the request:
</P>
<P>
   --A second Freeh memo written late in 1998 recommending an
independent counsel for Gore, according to legal sources aware of
the existence of the document. The memo was written after the last
of two interviews the FBI did of the vice president regarding his
knowledge of fund-raising practices in the 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
   --A memo written at about the same time as the second Freeh memo
by Judith Feigin, a detailee to the department's public integrity
section who favored appointment of an independent counsel to
investigate Gore, said the legal sources, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   --Any legal opinions from the department's Office of Legal
Counsel relating to fund-raising phone calls or events in the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   ''The requested documents were written by political appointees
or senior managers whose decisions are clearly subject to
congressional oversight,'' said the letter.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Reno refused to turn over the LaBella and Freeh memos
to the House Government Reform and Oversight Committee, led by Rep.
Dan Burton, R-Ind.
</P>
<P>
   ''The department has a substantial interest in avoiding a
chilling effect on the candor of future prosecutorial
deliberations,'' Reno wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The two senators and two representatives said that ''this
reason'' given in the letter to Burton ''is not enough to justify
your refusal to comply'' with the new request.
</P>
<P>
   The four also are seeking e-mail and any other records relating
to the key memos as well as all records received by Reno regarding
whether to seek appointment of an independent counsel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
