<HEADLINE> Shalala Backs Tobacco Regulation  </HEADLINE>
By KAREN GULLO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Taking a new tack, Health and Human Services
Secretary Donna Shalala urged lawmakers to approve government
regulation of tobacco because it's ''a political winner.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's an election year. Are you for protecting kids or aren't
you?'' Shalala said in an interview Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In an open letter to congressional leaders to be published
Thursday, Shalala said Congress should ''pick up the flag''
following a Supreme Court ruling that current law doesn't allow the
Food and Drug Administration to regulate tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   In a tongue-in-cheek gesture signifying that Cabinet secretaries
don't usually hand out political advice to lawmakers whose
decisions may help or hinder their agencies, the op-ed letter is
written as a memo from ''Anonymous.'' It will be published Thursday
in the Capitol Hill newspaper Roll Call.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton called on Congress to give the FDA power to
regulate tobacco after the March 21 Supreme Court ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-tobacco members of Congress have pledged to revive
legislation and presidential contenders Vice President Al Gore and
Texas Gov. George W. Bush have both said Congress should act to
reign in cigarette makers and tobacco ads aimed at children.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans in Congress have aggressively fought previous
efforts to regulate the tobacco industry. Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott, R-Miss., one of four congressional leaders to whom
Shalala addressed the letter and the lawmaker who has final say on
what legislation gets to the Senate floor, has said he opposes FDA
regulation of tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think they do a very good job with what they're doing
now without more requirements being dumped on them,'' Lott said
after the Supreme Court ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Shalala said legislation should allow the FDA to regulate
tobacco, increase prices for cigarettes, strengthen anti-smoking
campaigns and impose fines for companies that don't comply with
requirements for anti-smoking advertising and lowering teen
smoking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-05-00 1623 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000405.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hastert Sets Vote on China Trade  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House will vote during the week of May 22
on legislation granting China permanent trade privileges, House
Speaker Dennis Hastert said Wednesday. The move gave President
Clinton the early vote he had sought on one of the top priorities
of his final year in office.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're looking to ultimate victory,'' Hastert, R-Ill., told
reporters. He said he set the timetable after consulting with the
White House and looked forward to working with the president to
build support for the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ''This will have to be a bipartisan effort,'' he said. Both
sides predicted an extremely close vote.
</P>
<P>
   The setting of a certain time for House debate on the measure
heartened its sponsors, who feared that delaying it until the
summer in an election year could sink it.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, Hastert had hinted that he would wait until the
president could guarantee about 100 Democratic votes for the
measure. Democratic sponsors have suggested that the best they can
do is probably about 70 to 80 Democratic votes.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is strongly opposed by organized labor, environmental
groups and some conservative organizations.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton welcomed Hastert's move and announced it at a
White House conference on the new economy. ''This is very good
news,'' Clinton said. ''I want to thank the speaker and the
leadership of the House for doing this, and I assure you I will do
what I can to pass it.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright also greeted the vote
while suggesting that much work needs to be done to build support,
given labor's strong opposition. ''Economically, it's a no
brainer,'' she said in an interview with Associated Press editors
and reporters. ''It's an opening up of China.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert indicated he would bring the bill up whether he has the
votes or not. ''We're going to move it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While there is wide Republican support for the bill, House
Democrats are deeply divided. The measure was expected to win
easier approval in the Senate, where free-trade sentiment is higher
in both parties.
</P>
<P>
   Labor unions fear that expanded trade with China will cost U.S.
jobs. They also decry China's lack of worker rights.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would grant China the same low-tariff access to U.S.
markets that all but a handful of U.S. trading partners now enjoy.
Currently, China's trade status must be renewed annually.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation calling for permanent normal trade relations,
formally known as most favored nation status, is part of an
agreement the Clinton administration reached with China in
November.
</P>
<P>
   As part of that pact, the United States also agreed to support
China's bid to join the World Trade Organization, the Geneva-based
body that sets rules for international trade.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors of the trade bill suggest that rejecting it would not
keep China out of the WTO but could result in China closing its
markets to U.S. goods in retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   The bill ''gives us a chance to break down barriers and build up
trust between our two nations,'' Hastert said.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert said he was hopeful that the measure could generate
about 150 Republican and 100 Democratic votes. But he said he
realistically expected the tallies to be lower than that on both
sides of the aisle. The bill needs 218 votes if all members of the
House vote.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Dreier, R-Calif., a leading supporter of the bill and
chairman of the House Rules Committee, accused Democratic opponents
of having ''tied themselves to the ideological baggage of the
past.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Clinton's aggressive lobbying campaign in behalf of the
China trade pact, the House Democratic leadership has not helped
the administration with the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., remains undecided.
House Minority Whip Rep. David Bonior, D-Mich., the second-ranking
Democrat, is actively working to defeat it.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt's spokeswoman, Laura Nichols, said Wednesday that
Gephardt still has not decided how to vote. But, she said, he
welcomed Hastert's decision. ''We've been arguing, the sooner the
better,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Robert Matsui, D-Calif., the administration's point man
among Democrats for the bill, said that Democrats are ''well within
the range of getting 70-80 (Democratic) votes,'' but that dozens of
Democrats are still uncommitted.
</P>
<P>
   He said the setting of a certain date ''will hopefully change
the dynamics'' and bring more members off the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Matsui said, ''This is going to be a tough battle.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, the setting of a certain House date was applauded
by Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., a leading supporter of the bill.
''Delay on this issue is not an option,'' Baucus said.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Finance Committee is expected to take up the
legislation later this month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
