<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Government Attacks Cos.  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE COHEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) -- South Africa on Wednesday accused
international drug companies of taking advantage of the country's
lenient regulations to test unsafe AIDS drugs on human subjects.
</P>
<P>
   In an address to Parliament, Health Minister Manto
Tshabalala-Msimang said she recently learned five South African
women had died during a clinical trial of the anti-retroviral AIDS
drug Nevirapine, a cheaper alternative to AZT.
</P>
<P>
   An investigation by South Africa's Medicines Control Council
into the deaths showed that Nevirapine was a ''probable'' cause of
death in three women. The other two died of hepatitis.
</P>
<P>
   The council found that 510 patients had been recruited for the
trial, which compared the effects of the drugs FTC and lamivudine.
Some of those tested were given Nevirapine as part of a ''drug
cocktail.'' The council halted further recruitment for more trials.
</P>
<P>
   The trial was being conducted by Quintiles Clindepharm on behalf
of the U.S.-based firm Triangle Pharmaceuticals, she said. A
spokeswoman for Triangle, based in Durham, N.C., was not available
for comment after several phone calls from The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Nevirapine has been used successfully in Uganda to reduce
mother-to-child transmission of HIV, the virus that causes AIDS,
and other drug trials have proved it to be highly effective.
</P>
<P>
   But Tshabalala-Msimang said the Ugandan studies had not
adequately considered the drug's long-term safety. South Africa was
conducting its own testing, which would be completed by midyear,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The government has been criticized for not distributing AZT to
pregnant women to prevent transmission of HIV from mother to child.
The government has said it can't afford the expensive drug, and
lobbyists have called for Nevirapine to be made available.
Tshabalala-Msimang dismissed the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would be immoral and unethical for government, despite the
numerous requests that we are receiving and the demonstrations
which have been staged, to attempt to make policy decisions
regarding the use of Nevirapine in our country, until the full
results of the clinical trial of the drug are available,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   President Thabo Mbeki's government has been engaged in a
long-running battle with drug companies, accusing them of putting
profits before lives. The government estimates about a tenth of the
country's 42 million people are infected with HIV or AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia de Lille, a member of Parliament with the opposition
Pan African Congress, said 13 academic and research institutions
and 15 drug companies were conducting clinical trials of AIDS drugs
in South Africa. She called for more stringent controls on drug
testing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
