<HEADLINE> Smithsonian Chief Wants Night Hours  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Lawrence M. Small, the new head of the
Smithsonian Institution, said Wednesday he would open its 16
museums and the National Zoo at night if he could get enough money
to do it.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he would strongly oppose any attempt to charge
entrance fees at Smithsonian facilities because most visitors are
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ''If 90 percent of the visitors are Americans,'' he said,
''Americans who have already paid with their income taxes and their
philanthropy, I see no reason for putting in a regressive tax that
likely would fall hardest on the shoulders of those people whom
you'd like to see come into the museums more than any others: young
people, minorities, and people who maybe haven't been to a museum
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Small, who spoke at a National Press Club luncheon, said there
was no question in his mind that people would come if he could get
the money for the museums and zoo to stay open at night.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's an enormous need for money,'' he told one questioner,
''money from the federal government, money from private
philanthropists and money from private commitments.'' But Small
emphasized that an institution ''like the Smithsonian should never
put itself in the position of endorsing products for people.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't see any reason why business shouldn't be able to
provide money for museum exhibits. There is a difference between
providing the funding and having an endorsement or having a
commercial relationship with the museums,'' Small said.
</P>
</TEXT>
