<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Krispy Kreme Has Sweet Nasdaq Debut  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL NOWELL, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) -- Like a fresh serving of its tasty
treats, Krispy Kreme Doughnut Corp.'s reception on Wall Street on
Wednesday was hot and sweet, with its shares climbing more than 75
percent in their first day of trading.
</P>
<P>
   The Winston-Salem company's initial public offering was priced
at $21 per share, and opened at $32 on the Nasdaq Stock Market. At
4 p.m., the shares under the KREM ticker symbol stood at $37, after
7 million shares had changed hands during the day.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's almost like a dream,'' president Scott Livengood said in
a telephone interview from New York. ''It's a culmination of a lot
of work for generations.''
</P>
<P>
   Livengood said the Nasdaq's roller coaster ride on Tuesday only
''added a little excitement to the day.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I would bet the timing could be better,'' he said. ''But the
sector Krispy Kreme falls into seems to be doing OK. We're a
63-year-old business, so we're keeping that kind of perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Livengood remembers selling boxes of Krispy Kreme doughnuts in
high school. He's been with the company for 22 years.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Lombardi, an executive vice president at Technomic Inc.,
a Chicago food-service consulting firm, wasn't surprised by the
public interest in Krispy Kreme shares.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think lots of people want to be friends and family to this
type of deal,'' he said Tuesday. ''The real question is where will
the stock be two months from now? A lot of food-service stocks come
out and peak and then they go back to the IPO price in a few
weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   The foodservice industry has been struggling lately, but
Lombardi said Krispy Kreme's aura might defy the trend.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have virtually a cult following,'' he said. ''The closest
thing I can think of that's similar is Coors beer back in the '70s.
When people couldn't get Coors anywhere but in Colorado, everybody
wanted it. But it became a national brand, and it lost its aura.''
</P>
<P>
   Krispy Kreme, founded in 1937 by Vernon Carver Rudolph in a
Winston-Salem storefront, is issuing 3 million common shares,
putting the value of the IPO at about $63 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to use the proceeds to repay debt, renovate
some older stores and finance expansion.
</P>
<P>
   During the past six years, the Southern institution has ventured
into such decidedly un-Southern markets such as Manhattan and Las
Vegas. Krispy Kreme now has 141 stores in 27 states, from New York
to California.
</P>
<P>
   Each store makes and sells about 20 different kinds of
doughnuts. But their signature item remains the Hot Original Glazed
doughnut. True fans find the urge irresistible to stop at Krispy
Kreme when the ''Hot Doughnuts Now'' sign is on.
</P>
<P>
   According to the prospectus, Krispy Kreme's net income for the
first nine months of last year was $5.7 million on sales of $231.9
million.
</P>
<P>
   Underwriters for the offering are J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co., Deutsche
Banc Alex. Brown, Dain Rauscher Wessels and BB&AMP;T Capital Markets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
