<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers OK Controversial Artwork  </HEADLINE>
By TONY CZUCZKA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- After impassioned debate, lawmakers Wednesday
narrowly approved installing a controversial artwork in the
Reichstag parliament building that many believe raises the
uncomfortable question of who is a German.
</P>
<P>
   The lower house voted 260-258 in favor of the piece by artist
Hans Haacke, whose dedication ''To the Population'' is meant as a
liberal, modern-day counterpart to the old inscription above the
Reichstag's entrance: ''To the German People.'' Thirty-one
legislators abstained.
</P>
<P>
   But the contrast of the two inscriptions goes to the heart of
current debates over immigration and citizenship: whether those who
live within Germany's borders are a ''people'' or a ''population.''
</P>
<P>
   It poses the question of whether being German means ''being of
German descent,'' or if it includes anyone who feels at home here.
</P>
<P>
   The thrust of Haacke's proposal -- a wooden flower trough, 23
feet wide and 70 feet long -- has also sparked controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The trough is to be filled with dirt brought by each of the 669
legislators from their hometowns -- something that many lawmakers
across party lines say draws an awkward allusion to the mythical
veneration of German ''blood and soil'' practiced by the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   Parliament President Wolfgang Thierse had come out in favor of
the project hours before the vote, saying it would remind lawmakers
at a time of rising immigration of their obligation to everyone
living in Germany -- not just those of German descent.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let us not react with fearful defensiveness to the
contradictions raised by Hans Haacke's project,'' Thierse implored
the packed chamber under the Reichstag's new glass dome during the
debate.
</P>
<P>
   Parliamentary leaders ordered a recount because of the close
ballot. However, the result was not expected to change.
</P>
<P>
   Haacke, a German based in New York, said he intended his artwork
to be a statement against xenophobia and rising neo-Nazi violence.
</P>
<P>
   ''Millions lost their lives because of an understanding about
who belongs or does not belong to the German people,'' he said in
an interview Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We know that there are again people in this country who attack
passers-by on the street if they don't look German enough,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the piece called it inappropriate and unnecessarily
provocative.
</P>
<P>
   Norbert Lammert, a member of the conservative opposition
Christian Democrats, whose motion to block the project was rejected
in Wednesday's vote, called Haacke's proposal ''politically and
esthetically a failure.''
</P>
<P>
   He said German lawmakers ''need lessons from no one'' on how to
protect the rights of people living here.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives insist Germany is not a country of immigrants,
even though almost 10 percent of its 83 million people are
foreigners. New laws that went into effect this year cut the
decades-old link between blood and citizenship, but only after much
heated debate.
</P>
<P>
   Haacke has said he would neither accept changes to the work nor
agree to install it elsewhere.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
