<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton warns kids about smoking, backs smoke-free bars  </HEADLINE>
By BETH J. HARPAZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton on Wednesday said she
supports the concept of smoke-free bars.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would vote for it if I were on the City Council,'' Clinton
told reporters. ''I made the White House a no-smoking zone because
I think it's a terrible imposition on others. It's not only what
you do to yourself but what you inflict on others.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been recent talk of tightening a New York City law
that bans smoking in restaurants seating more than 35 people. The
current law permits smoking in the bar area of such establishments,
but some anti-tobacco activists would like to see smoking banned
there as well. No formal legislation is pending.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's Republican rival for the Senate seat, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, does not support changing current regulations, which he
signed into law in 1995. Giuliani spokesman Ed Skyler said he
thinks the existing law ''strikes the right balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Clinton appeared at a public middle school, the Salk
School, where she lectured 350 students in grades 6-8 on the evils
of smoking as part of Kick Butts Day, a national anti-tobacco event
aimed at young people.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need to kick butts out of the way of every single
teen-ager, child and hopefully even adults,'' she said. She also
accused tobacco companies of targeting children, saying: ''They're
trying to get that advertising into your mind to enable you to
cross the barrier of health and science and start smoking.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also said that she supports legislation to give the Food
and Drug Administration the authority to regulate tobacco as if it
were a drug. The Supreme Court ruled last month that the FDA cannot
do so under the current law.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently buoyed by a new poll showing her support inching up,
Clinton appeared relaxed and chatty throughout the day. The new
survey from Quinnipiac College showed Clinton leading Giuliani
46-43, a statistical dead heat but cause for celebration in the
Clinton camp because it confirmed two previous recent polls showing
that the first lady is finally making a dent in the support for the
mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know he's having a bad couple of weeks,'' she said
gleefully.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Clinton appeared at a National Council of Jewish Women
luncheon at a conservative synagogue in Rockville Centre, Long
Island. The organization is working on an anti-domestic violence
campaign in Nassau County to support women escaping abusive
situations and to post cards offering emergency help in public
restrooms and other places around the county.
</P>
<P>
   A domestic violence survivor, Harriet Feldman, brought the
audience to tears as she described her 30-year marriage to a doctor
who regularly beat her. He died 15 years ago but she said the abuse
had scarred her children, who are both recovering alcoholics.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton thanked Feldman for her ''courage and eloquence,'' and
called for a reauthorization of the Violence Against Women Act,
which provides federal funding for local assistance to rape
victims, prosecution of batterers and related projects.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Julian Cook paid tribute to Clinton's ''inspirational
leadership'' and the 300 women assembled gave her a standing
ovation. But afterward, some said they remain undecided about her
Senate candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ''She spoke beautifully on this issue but there are a hell of a
lot of other issues out there,'' said NCJW member Marilyn Lamstein.
''I think she's a brilliant woman and I admire her intellect, but I
don't know who she really is ... She should get a real identity and
not waste time denigrating Rudy Giuliani. He's doing a good job
denigrating himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ended her day by participating in a global conference on
women and business that connected 160 sites via satellite. Asked if
female politicians have a different leadership style from men, she
said she thought women were more likely to lead by ''consensus and
create a win-win situation than a zero-sum game.''
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Global conference on women in business is available
Thursday at www.womenfuture.com. (Eds: Thursday is cq.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
