</P>
<P>
   Yahoo! Earnings Top Expectations
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- First-quarter earnings at Yahoo! beat
expectations as people continued to flock to the world's leading
Web destination to buy and sell products or find information on the
Internet. For the three months ended March 31, Yahoo! reported net
income of $77.8 million, or 13 cents a share, compared to $1.8
million, or 0 cents a share in the year-ago period. Excluding a
$40.7 gain made from investments and charges relating to
acquisitions and income taxes, Yahoo! earned 10 cents per share.
Analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial had expected
earnings of 9 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   London Trading Extended After Halt
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The London Stock Exchange sputtered back to life
today after a technical fault forced the suspension of trading for
most of the day. The computer failure, which lasted 7{ hours, was
the worst ever for Europe's biggest exchange. Trading finally
resumed at 3:30 p.m. The market was paralyzed during what should
have been one of its busiest sessions -- the last day of the British
tax year. Untold numbers of people may have missed out on a chance
to buy or sell shares in a last-minute attempt to minimize their
liability for capital gains tax. Once the system was up and
running, the exchange announced extended trading hours until 8 p.m.
to help make up for some of the time lost. At the end of trading,
British stocks were lower.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan Warns White House Meeting
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton boasted today that America
is enjoying its strongest economy in history but heard warnings
about stock market turbulence, the threat of rising inflation and
the huge U.S. trade deficit. Clinton presided over a daylong White
House conference on the ''new economy,'' attended by economists,
investment bankers, thinkers -- and Microsoft's Bill Gates and
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan. Greenspan warned against
inflation. Gates, speaking of technological breakthroughs, said
''The magic has really just begun ....''
</P>
<P>
   Netscape Shows Browser Update
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Netscape Communications Corp. today showed
the long-awaited update of its Web-browsing software in a bid to
usurp Microsoft Corp.'s dominance of the way people travel the
Internet. Netscape, bought by America Online last year, also
announced a deal with Gateway to build a family of small, home
Internet appliances designed to use Netscape 6. They would include
a small, tablet-like screen that users can carry from room to room
while surfing the Web. Netscape 6 is faster and far more flexible
than other Internet browsers, AOL Chairman Stephen Case said in a
speech touting the new browser and appliances at the Internet World
2000 conference.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Penalty Phase Scheduled
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The judge who ruled that Microsoft illegally
competed by taking advantage of its monopoly power set a schedule
today to consider what kind of punishment to impose on the software
giant. U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson is tentatively
scheduled to begin holding hearings on the case on May 24,
according to sources close to the case. During a private meeting,
he gave attorneys for the Justice Department and the 19 states
suing Microsoft until the end of this month to submit their
proposed remedies. Jackson gave Microsoft slightly less than two
weeks to respond to that proposal, and the government another week
for a rebuttal. Earlier, there had been some mention of a possible
fast-track appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Internet Bill Paying Service Offered
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Wary of losing its lucrative bill and payment
delivery business to the Internet, the Postal Service has decided
to offer one-stop bill paying via computer. Many Americans have
grown comfortable paying bills electronically and now they will be
able to do all their business at a single site using a password,
Postmaster General William Henderson announced today. He said the
service is being made available immediately, with new customers
getting the first six months of service free. People interested in
the service, USPSeBillPay, can get details and sign up at the
Postal Service's Internet site.
</P>
<P>
   Krispy Kreme Has Sweet Nasdaq Debut
</P>
<P>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) -- Wall Street took a liking to
doughnut-maker Krispy Kreme on its first trading day today, as
shares climbed about 76 percent. The Winston-Salem company's
initial public offering was priced at $21 per share, and was up 16
at 37 for the day. ''It's almost like a dream,'' president Scott
Livengood said in a telephone interview from New York. Livengood
said the Nasdaq's roller coaster ride yesterday only ''added a
little excitement to the day.''
</P>
<P>
   MetLife Stock Up on First Day
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- MetLife Inc., the nation's second-largest life
insurer, was up up 1 at 15\ in its first day of public trading
today. The company had raised $2.88 billion after pricing its
initial public offering as it converts to a public company from one
owned by policyholders. MetLife sold 202 million shares yesterday
at $14.25 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Nabisco Asks Icahn To Join Bidding
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A day after Carl Icahn proposed buying Nabisco
Group Holdings Corp. for $16 a share, Nabisco Group's chairman
invited the suitor to join the process the company's financial
advisors have set up to assure shareholders get the best deal.
Chairman Steven F. Goldstone told Icahn in a letter released today
that by doing so, Icahn could qualify to obtain confidential
information and would be informed about the procedures for
presenting a formal bid. ''Our board will consider all bona fide
proposals at the appropriate time,'' Goldstone wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Legend Airlines Makes First Trip
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- Legend Airlines' maiden flight from Love Field
took off this morning without a hitch to Washington Dulles, making
it the first long-haul commercial flight to leave the Dallas
airport in more than a quarter-century. Legend's reconfigured DC-9,
with a capacity of 56, left with 50 passengers aboard at 9 a.m.
CDT. Legend's inaugural flight, originally scheduled to take off
Feb. 29, was delayed after the Federal Aviation Administration said
custom-made galleys for the cabins failed crash tests. The FAA has
now cleared the way for flights.
</P>
