<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protesters Gather at Reno Fla. Home  </HEADLINE>
By MILDRADE CHERFILS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Carrying signs depicting Janet Reno as the devil,
anti-Castro activists protested outside the attorney general's
Florida home Wednesday against the government's effort to send
Elian Gonzalez back to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, a former Miami-Dade County state attorney, was not in
Florida, but several dozen demonstrators targeted her house in the
Kendall neighborhood anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ''My message here is to give freedom to Elian,'' said one of the
protesters, Barbara Nunez.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami's Little Havana neighborhood, other demonstrators
maintained a vigil outside the home of Elian's great-uncle Lazaro
Gonzalez, who has had temporary custody of the 6-year-old boy since
he was rescued from an inner tube at sea in November.
</P>
<P>
   Sasha Sanchez shouted denunciations of President Clinton through
a bullhorn, saying: ''You might as well send Elian back to the
ocean and let him die there.''
</P>
<P>
   Details of a possible reunion between Elian and his father, Juan
Miguel Gonzalez, are being negotiated by attorneys for the Miami
relatives and the Immigration and Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   One of the issues is whether the father, who has been granted a
U.S. visa, would stay in the United States until the Miami
relatives' court battle to keep Elian is over.
</P>
<P>
   The talks are suspended until Thursday. But INS officials have
said that once Elian's father arrives in the United States, they
will go about turning the boy over to him.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Craig, the American lawyer for Elian's father, was in
Cuba on Wednesday to discuss his client's possible trip to the
United States. U.S. officials said they understood Craig made the
trip to try to persuade him to travel to the United States to be
reunited with his son.
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Remirez, head of the Cuban diplomatic mission in
Washington, said the father's travel plans depend on ''the
assurance he will get temporary custody.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Department has granted visas to Juan Miguel Gonzalez,
his wife and their infant son, as well as a cousin, a kindergarten
teacher and a pediatrician. The agency said it is reviewing visa
requests from 22 other Cubans, including 12 of Elian's classmates
and Ricardo Alarcon, a top adviser to Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   Marisleysis Gonzalez, the cousin who has served as Elian's
surrogate mother in Miami, was released from a hospital Wednesday
after an overnight stay for treatment of exhaustion. A family
spokesman said she was staying temporarily at the home of other
relatives.
</P>
</TEXT>
