<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Down 130; Nasdaq Up 20  </HEADLINE>
By EILEEN GLANTON, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks suffered another bout of
volatility Wednesday, giving up a major advance to finish with
slender gains and proving that the nervousness that sent Wall
Street into a tailspin on Tuesday lingers.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were torn between hunting for bargains and waiting for
the dust to settle after Tuesday's head-spinning session.
Ultimately, the largest, best-known technology names held their
gains. Profit-taking continued in both the technology sector and
the blue-chip Dow Jones industrials.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not behaving nearly as dramatically as yesterday, but
this is still a wild market,'' said Larry Lawler, manager of equity
trading at Dreyfus Corp. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index rose 20.33 to 4,169.22. During the
regular trading day, the index fell as much as 139.80 and rose as
much as 133.40.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average dropped 130.92 to close at
11,033.92 after giving up an early gain. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index fell 7.36 to 1,487.37.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000, which has also dropped sharply this week, rose
11.92 to 518.04.
</P>
<P>
   Volume was fairly modest, but volatility remained. Stocks were
down at the opening as traders struggled to find their footing
after Tuesday's chaotic selloff, during which both the Nasdaq and
the Dow fell more than 500 points only to close with modest,
double-digit losses.
</P>
<P>
   The wildness on Wall Street rattled most overseas markets, which
made it even more difficult for the U.S. market to mount any real
advance in morning trading. As the session wore on, however, some
bargain-hunting investors stepped in, their confidence boosted by
some calming words from major market movers.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning, Abby Joseph Cohen, chief investment
strategist at Goldman Sachs, delivered an upbeat message at a White
House conference on the new economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''For the past decade, we have been enthusiastic about the
outlook for U.S. stock prices in the United States, and we remain
so,'' Cohen said. She said the long-running bull market had been
driven by steady economic gains and therefore was justified.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Cohen's recommendation that clients put some of their
stock holdings into cash sparked a round of selling on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   In early afternoon, the market drew some additional support from
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, who gave credit to the
''extraordinary surge in technological innovation'' for America's
current record-breaking economy.
</P>
<P>
   But even as investors returned to the market, most confined
their technology buying to the best-known names. Applied Materials,
a leading maker of computer chip equipment, rose 6 1/16 to 104
3/16. Oracle gained 2 5/16 to 78\ and Hewlett-Packard rose 4} to
142~.
</P>
<P>
   Investors' shifting sentiment played out in companies including
i2 Technologies, a business-to-business service provider for the
electronic commerce industry. Shares rose 10 9/16 to 105 Wednesday
after Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette boosted its rating on the stock.
</P>
<P>
   But just Monday, i2's shares had tumbled 24 percent after
Prudential Securities cut its rating. Ultimately, concern over that
type of decline undermined the market's attempts to rally sharply,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Financial and consumer goods stocks, which rose sharply last
week, slipped as jittery investors took profits. Procter &AMP; Gamble
fell 1 15/16 to 61 9/16 and J.P. Morgan fell 1 9/16 to 134{.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola fell 4} to 47| after the company lowered its long-term
annual earnings-per-share growth target to 15 percent Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some representatives of the ''old economy'' fared better.
Sears rose 7 to 37{ after saying it expects first-quarter profits
to beat expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Two initial public offerings that are far removed from the
dot-com world attracted buyers. MetLife, the nation's
second-largest life insurer, rose 1[ from its offering price to
close at 15] in heavy trading. And Krispy Kreme, a doughnut company
with massive brand loyalty, rose more than 70 percent from its
offering price, ending at 37 per share.
</P>
<P>
   Amid Wednesday's uncertain performance, some analysts remained
skeptical of the market's short-term prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ''We see it more as the eye of the storm,'' said Gail Dudack,
chief investment strategist at Warburg Dillon Read in New York.
''The danger for the market place has not ended.''
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 9-to-7 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange. On the Nasdaq, eight stocks rose for every
seven that fell.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE volume totaled 1.33 billion shares, compared with 1.82
billion in Tuesday's turbulent session.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.6 percent,
Germany's Xetra DAX index fell 2.6 percent and France's CAC-40 fell
3.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's FT-SE 100 index fell 0.7 percent after markets
reopened following a technical problem that suspended trading for
7{ hours.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
