<HEADLINE> Former Spy Files Returned to Germany  </HEADLINE>
By TONY CZUCZKA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- The CIA has given Germany a first batch of spy
files obtained from the former East Germany that could expose many
agents who operated in the West during the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   The archive, said to contain 320,000 names, was obtained by the
U.S. intelligence agency after the Berlin Wall fell in 1989, though
the circumstances have never been officially explained.
</P>
<P>
   Government spokesman Uwe-Karsten Heye said Wednesday that the
first CD-ROM arrived at Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's office last
Friday. It was still sealed and had not yet been analyzed, he said.
Some 1,000 further discs are to follow over the next 1{ years, Heye
said.
</P>
<P>
   The CIA agreed last year to share the records, believed to
contain information about thousands of former communist East German
spies and informants. However, the CIA said it would withhold data
that compromises U.S. sources.
</P>
<P>
   German officials have said they believe the files will identify
as yet undiscovered spies who worked for East Germany's Stasi
intelligence agency, including Cold War agents who operated in
former West Germany.
</P>
<P>
   But Heye stressed that is was unclear how many revelations the
files actually contain.
</P>
<P>
   ''First we have to know what's really in there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Heye said experts from the government and the agency that
oversees the Stasi archive in Berlin will analyze the data, then
determine how much of it should be open to the public. He said it
was too early to tell how long that would take.
</P>
<P>
   But Schroeder pledged Wednesday to treat the material
confidentially.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will handle it in such a way that there are no
indiscretions,'' he told reporters in the eastern city of Dresden.
</P>
<P>
   A German newspaper reported Wednesday that the CIA acquired the
files from the former Soviet KGB in 1992 after the Stasi spirited
them to Moscow during the peaceful democratic revolution that
brought down the Berlin Wall in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   That contradicts the widely held theory that the CIA got hold of
the files in East Berlin in 1990, the Sueddeutsche Zeitung said in
a report to appear in Thursday's editions. The report gave no
details of the alleged transaction.
</P>
<P>
   The poor quality of the files -- which are also believed to
contain handwritten notes -- makes scanning them onto discs
''extraordinarily hard'' and explains the lengthy process, Heye
said. The data is contained on up to 600,000 individual file cards,
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
