<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey: McCain Can Help GOP  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID ESPO, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Former Republican presidential contender John
McCain is well liked by swing voters who could be decisive in the
battle for control of the House this fall, according to a GOP
survey.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, taken since McCain suspended his campaign for the
White House, indicates the Arizona senator is favored -- more than
Al Gore and George W. Bush -- by voters who describe themselves as
uncommitted in a hypothetical matchup of congressional candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The finding emerged from a poll conducted for SAFE, an
organization associated with Rep. J.C. Watts of Oklahoma, to help
assure continued GOP control of the House in the fall elections.
Watts presented the data at a closed-door meeting of the House
Republican leadership earlier in the week, according to party
officials who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clearly McCain has appeal among undecided congressional
voters,'' said David Winston, the pollster who conducted the
survey.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans already were moving eagerly to enlist McCain's
aid in campaigning in key districts around the country. The Arizona
senator won seven primaries -- five New England states and Michigan
as well as his home state -- and attracted the support of thousands
of moderates and Democrats before suspending his campaign last
month.
</P>
<P>
   McCain aside, the survey showed congressional Democrats still
lead Republicans by double-digit margins on several key issues, but
the GOP has made ''incremental improvement'' in areas such as
education, health care, Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Asked which party cares more about them, 42 percent of those
surveyed said Democrats, and 33 percent said Republicans. That was
a slight change from a 44-31 Democratic advantage in a previous
survey.
</P>
<P>
   The SAFE survey showed that in a hypothetical matchup of two
congressional candidates, the Democrat won 44 percent support, the
Republican 42 percent, 12 percent were undecided, and 2 percent
didn't know.
</P>
<P>
   Of the uncommitted 14 percent, McCain got the support of 41
percent in a separate, hypothetical three-way presidential ballot
test, while Democrat Gore drew 19 percent and Republican Bush drew
21 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Material from the survey was made available to The Associated
Press.
</P>
<P>
   It tracks findings in public polls, including a Voter.com
Battleground 2000 survey that found McCain a benefit in swing
congressional districts. Bush's support in those districts rose
from 49 percent to 61 percent with McCain on a hypothetical ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Bill McInturff, who conducted polls for McCain's campaign, said
that based on several surveys he's seen, ''McCain voters are the
absolute swing part of the electorate.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who frequently challenged Bush and his own party to
support campaign finance legislation and other items on his
''reform agenda,'' has indicated a strong desire to campaign on
behalf of Republican congressional candidates. He made his first
foray this week, appearing for New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, a
candidate for the Senate. He also has plans to campaign for Sen.
Lincoln Chafee, seeking his first full term from Rhode Island, and
GOP challengers Mark Nielsen in Connecticut and Greg Becker in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Other stops are planned this month in Michigan, New Jersey,
Illinois, Pennsylvania and Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the survey was made available, Republican House
campaign officials had been advising rank-and-file lawmakers to
take advantage of the strength McCain demonstrated beyond their own
party.
</P>
<P>
   In a memo late last month, Rep. Tom Davis of Virginia, chairman
of the party's campaign committee, said, ''Every House Republican
must open their arms to these independent and like-minded Democrat
voters and let them know they are welcome in our family.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-05-00 1812 </TRAILER>
