<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Gore Gaining Among Women  </HEADLINE>
By WILL LESTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Al Gore is making progress among women voters,
but George W. Bush is showing enough strength among certain groups
of women to cause continuing concern among Democrats about a
crucial voting bloc, a poll released Wednesday suggests.
</P>
<P>
   The poll by Emily's List, a political network for Democratic
women who support abortion rights, showed Gore with a 6-point edge
among women. It also gave the advantage to Democrats on having the
right approach to education, a top issue in the presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush led the vice president by 10 points among men.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the likely Democratic presidential nominee, and Bush, the
presumed Republican presidential nominee, were even among women
voters in the same poll in December.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's support is stronger now among women who are black,
Hispanic, from union households, white and college-educated, and
earning at least $50,000, according to the survey of likely voters
by Democratic pollsters Geoff Garin and Celinda Lake. Bush's
support was stronger among high-school educated and evangelical
white women.
</P>
<P>
   In the overall race, Bush led Gore 44 percent to 42 percent, and
Pat Buchanan had 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Recent independent polls have reflected Gore's gains among
women, and also have shown Bush, the Texas governor, with an
advantage among men.
</P>
<P>
   Double-digit advantages among women aided Bill Clinton's
victories in 1992 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Gore were close among women who are independent,
suburban, seniors, Midwestern, Western and Protestant, while Bush
led among white married mothers and evangelical women.
</P>
<P>
   ''Gore has not finished his work,'' said Garin. ''Bush is making
a pretty strong play for women with his focus on education.''
</P>
<P>
   Education was cited as a top campaign issue by 37 percent in the
survey, followed by health care and Social Security -- all issues
that have been traditionally stronger for Democrats. Moral values,
a stronger issue for Republicans, dropped out of the top three; it
was No. 2 in December.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats were given the edge on education by 42 percent of
women; Republicans by 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Six of 10 women said education was an extremely important issue
for the next president. Just under half of the men surveyed felt
that way. About six of 10 women said increasing funding for
education should be a higher priority than cutting taxes; just
under half of the men said that.
</P>
<P>
   The poll of 809 women and 408 men, all likely voters, was taken
March 21-24 and has an error margin of plus or minus 3 percentage
points, slightly higher for subgroups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
