<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Corzine emerges from county battles with advantage in ballotposition  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In an important early test, Democratic Senate
candidate Jon S. Corzine has secured a prime spot on June 6 primary
ballots in nine counties where more than two-thirds of registered
Democrats live.
</P>
<P>
   By ''winning the line'' in those counties -- including Essex and
Hudson, home to 24 percent of New Jersey Democrats -- Corzine
ensured that his name will appear alongside those of the
best-known, officially endorsed Democrats in congressional and
county races.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine's opponent, former Gov. Jim Florio, won the line in 11
counties. Somerset County, which holds its convention April 6, will
give Corzine his ninth party line because Florio has conceded that
contest. In tiny Hunterdon County, Florio and Corzine each won
enough support to share equal ballot position.
</P>
<P>
   All told, about 32 percent of registered Democrats live in
counties where Florio is the endorsed candidate; the remaining 68
percent live in Corzine territory.
</P>
<P>
   Florio counties are in the southern and northwestern parts of
the state, while Corzine has the ballot advantage in a swath of
counties from Bergen to Mercer to Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Few Democratic leaders deny that ballot position matters. The
question is how much. Campaigns are influenced by many unexpected
events, like the controversy that engulfed Corzine last week when
he apologized for joking comments about Italian-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the last time there was a Democratic primary for
statewide office, Woodbridge Township Mayor Jim McGreevey won the
line in counties that were home to about two-thirds of registered
Democrats. He did win the nomination -- but only narrowly.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think (ballot position) can make a difference,'' said Tom
Giblin, the Democratic state chairman. ''People look at a column
and see a candidate for sheriff or a candidate for (county) clerk
identifying with a candidate for senator or governor or president.
It does have an impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Goldstein, one of Corzine's two campaign managers, said
Corzine's success at winning party support in major counties
''sends a message that the people who know Governor Florio and Jon
Corzine best, those in public service, prefer Jon Corzine by two to
one.''
</P>
<P>
   But Florio said an increasingly independent-minded electorate
cares less and less about whom party leaders endorse.
</P>
<P>
   A county-by-county breakdown makes for ''an interesting
analysis,'' Florio said, ''but it presupposes that everybody votes
monolithically. And that's not the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Florio and Corzine both pulled out the stops to win
county lines. In wooing county leaders, both candidates tried out
arguments they hope will appeal later in the year to rank-and-file
voters.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, the former chairman of Goldman Sachs, pitched himself
as a new face who would apply private-sector can-do enthusiasm to
stubborn national problems.
</P>
<P>
   Florio stressed the importance of government experience and
raised questions about whether Corzine was offering deep
convictions or deep pockets.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, a longtime financial supporter of the Democratic party,
has written large checks this election cycle to several county
organizations, including $30,000 to Bergen County's Democratic
party and $25,000 each to the parties in Union and Ocean counties.
He won the line in all three counties.
</P>
<P>
   ''His investments have paid off handsomely,'' said Michael
Murphy, a spokesman for the Florio campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But Goldstein said such suspicions were put to rest when Corzine
won party conventions in Bergen and Mercer, traditionally among the
most democratic and competitive contests in the state.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, the party chairman in a county that endorsed
Corzine ended up with a paid job with his campaign. But Goldstein
said that chairman, Al Santoro of Ocean County, was offered the job
only after the county endorsement was decided.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid being exiled to a lonely part of the ballot in counties
where they lost the line, Florio and Corzine can choose to align
themselves with candidates in other races who also did not win
county support.
</P>
<P>
   Florio said he intends to do just that in every county where
Corzine holds the party line. In fact, he conceded Somerset County
-- where Corzine was likely to win anyway -- so that he could run on
the same line as Fanwood Mayor Maryanne Connelly, a candidate for
House who is not supported by party leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein said Florio is hurting the party by running competing
slates in local races. Murphy replied that Florio has neither
drummed up nor sought out disgruntled Democrats to run with.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think there are people out there who are anti-organization,
and now they've found a home,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine has not said whether he will field slates of competing
candidates in counties where Florio has the prime ballot spot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-05-00 1821 </TRAILER>
