<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Norway Train Fires Spur Evacuations  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSLO, Norway (AP) -- Fears that burning propane tankers from a
train wreck could explode prompted police on Wednesday to evacuate
more than 2,000 people from the center of a small Norwegian city.
</P>
<P>
   Two freight trains collided and caught fire at about 1 a.m.
Wednesday at the Lillestroem train station, some 10 miles north of
Oslo.
</P>
<P>
   Both trains involved in the crash had an automatic train stop
system that should have prevented a collision.
</P>
<P>
   However, one train's brakes apparently failed on a downhill
grade into the station, Arne Tordhol, of the national railroad
NSB's freight division, told the Norwegian news agency NTB.
</P>
<P>
   No one was injured in the crash, but police evacuated a 800-yard
area around the trains because they feared the cargo of about 90
tons of propane gas in two cars could explode in a devastating
fireball.
</P>
<P>
   Citing experts, newspapers said if the tanks were half-full, an
explosion would last 14 seconds and cause a deadly fireball
extending up to 200 feet around the cars.
</P>
<P>
   It could take days before people would be allowed to return to
the homes, schools, businesses and a medical clinic because fire
experts say gas leaking from one or both cars must be allowed to
slowly burn off.
</P>
<P>
   ''The best thing that could have happened was that it started to
burn,'' said Tore Dahlbo, of the Norwegian Directorate for Fire and
Explosion Prevention. He said if unburned gas had spread, the
slightest spark could have caused a huge explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Firemen were using a remote-controlled water cannon to pump
thousands of gallons per minute onto the tank cars to cool them
without dousing the flames.
</P>
<P>
   The station where the crash occurred is a key railway crossroad,
so the wreck has stopped service that includes express service from
the capital to Norway's main airport.
</P>
<P>
   The accident came as the country was engaged in an anguished
debate over railroad safely prompted mainly by a crash in January
between two passenger trains that killed 19 people, some of whom
burned alive when a fire swept the wreckage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
