<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sen. Roth Having Back Operation  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sen. William Roth, chairman of the Senate
Finance Committee, will have back surgery next week to remove bone
spurs.
</P>
<P>
   The 78-year-old Republican from Delaware stumbled in public at a
recent White House meeting because of numbness in his feet, then
experienced the same sensation on a few other occasions. His
physician, Dr. David Cornblath of the Johns Hopkins University
School of Medicine, said tests revealed that bone spurs on the
senator's spine were the cause.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Wednesday, Cornblath described the operation as a
''standard procedure'' for ''a common ailment for which hundreds of
thousands of Americans are treated each year.''
</P>
<P>
   The operation is set for April 12 at Johns Hopkins University
Hospital in Baltimore. A spokeswoman said Roth expects to
recuperate for up to a month, and Cornblath said Roth should
recover completely. Congress will be on a two-week recess during
much of that time.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am eager to get this behind me so I can return to my work in
the Senate,'' Roth said.
</P>
<P>
   Roth, who was first elected to the Senate in 1970, is facing a
stiff challenge for re-election this year from Delaware Gov. Tom
Carper, a Democrat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
