<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Twists, Turns in Mexico Murder Case  </HEADLINE>
By JULIE WATSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A slain television host with a taste for
cocaine. His ridiculed sidekick. An alleged drug smuggler known as
the Amphetamine King. An aspiring young actress.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a year after television funnyman Paco Stanley was gunned
down in broad daylight, the already bizarre case has taken even
more twists -- and Mexicans are following every one.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Mexico's two national television networks aired
footage of the key witness retracting his testimony, saying
authorities forced him to testify against the three main suspects.
</P>
<P>
   City authorities scoffed at the retraction and said it was a
ploy by the federal government to distract attention from their
attempt to bring corruption charges against a Cabinet minister.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government, in turn, suggested the city, run by an
opposition party, was using the corruption scandal to discredit the
ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone was trying to divert attention, they couldn't have
picked a better case than the June 7 killing of Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   Television newscasts lead with even the smallest development in
the case. Web pages are dedicated to Stanley, and chat rooms have
sprung up to discuss the case on the Internet. When a radio program
recently asked for opinions on the case, the switchboard lit up
with more than 4,000 calls.
</P>
<P>
   ''I watch it every day,'' said Ignacio Arroyo, a 57-year-old
butcher. ''I like to see the officials make a mess of everything.
It gives me insight into how incapable they are in resolving
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   When Stanley was gunned down outside a restaurant in Mexico
City, it was portrayed as an example of the crime wave that has
plagued the largest city in the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   But it soon became clear this was no common crime. Revelations
of Stanley's cocaine use and links to an alleged smuggler created
speculation about a drug link, and the case exploded with the
spectacular arrest of his television sidekick, who had lingered in
the restaurant's bathroom at the time of the attack, saying his
hemorrhoids were acting up.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Stanley's killing was ordered by alleged drug
smuggler Luiz Amezcua Contreras, whom U.S. and Mexican prosectors
call the Amphetamine King. The case against Amezcua is based
largely on testimony from Luis Gabriel Valencia Lopez, who
authorities say worked as Amezcua's cook.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Amezcua, who is in jail on drug and
money-laundering charges, was angered that Stanley owed him money
for his cocaine habit and recruited Mario Rodriguez Bezares,
Stanley's television sidekick and the butt of most of his jokes, to
help carry it out in exchange for forgiving his own drug debt.
</P>
<P>
   Valencia testified that the intermediary in the plot was Paola
Durante Ochoa, a 23-year-old aspiring actress who worked as an
assistant on Stanley's show.
</P>
<P>
   But the prosecution's case suffered a blow Monday when Valencia
said that he had lied in his testimony and that the three suspects
he had named all are innocent.
</P>
<P>
   ''I lied because they forced me with threats of hurting my
family and with the promise I'd be freed soon and that they'd help
me financially,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico City Attorney General Samuel del Villar dismissed the
retraction. He claimed federal officials were trying to divert
public attention from his office's embezzlement investigation into
Tourism Secretary Oscar Espinosa Villarreal.
</P>
<P>
   President Zedillo said in letter to the media late last month
that even if there was a case against Espinosa, it would be
lamentable if it was ''electorally motivated.'' Mexicans elect
their next president on July 2 in one of the closest races in
history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-05-00 1831 </TRAILER>
