<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wife of Bosnian Suspect Appears  </HEADLINE>
By RADUL RADOVANOVIC, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALE, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) -- The wife of Bosnia's most wanted
war crimes suspect, Radovan Karadzic, appeared Wednesday at a rally
of the hard-line Serb party once led by her husband -- an effort to
boost its chances of a comeback in this weekend's municipal
elections.
</P>
<P>
   About 500 supporters of the Serb Democratic Party stood and
cheered as Ljiljana Zelen-Karadzic entered the small, packed hall
in this hard-line Bosnian Serb stronghold east of Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
   Party faithful chanted her husband's nickname: ''Rasho, Rasho.''
</P>
<P>
   Zelen-Karadzic's appearance -- her first in years at such a large
public gathering -- came two days after NATO troops arrested her
husband's former aide, Momcilo Krajisnik, on charges of genocide,
crimes against humanity and violating the customs of war.
</P>
<P>
   Karadzic, who was the Bosnian Serb president and head of the
Serb Democratic Party during the 1992-1995 war, remains at large.
He is rumored to be living in the Serb-ruled part of
Bosnia-Herzegovina, despite the presence of NATO troops.
</P>
<P>
   At the rally, Zelen-Karadzic refused to comment on her husband's
whereabouts, but admitted her family was afraid he might be
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Her appearance was designed to rally the hard-line party in
advance of Saturday's municipal balloting.
</P>
<P>
   Karadzic had to withdraw from politics after he was indicted by
the U.N. war crimes tribunal. He has been charged with crimes
against humanity and genocide for allegedly masterminding the 1995
slaughter of Muslims in the U.N.-protected enclave of Srebrenica in
northeastern Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Karadzic's Serb Democratic Party lost its grip on absolute power
two years ago when some of its prominent members defected and
formed an alliance with moderate opposition parties, which took
half of the seats in the Bosnian Serb parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The party's main opponent in the weekend elections is the
Bosnian Serb prime minister, Milorad Dodik -- blamed by hard-liners
for having steered the Bosnian Serbs toward the West and for
abandoning the goal of an ethnically pure Bosnian Serb mini-state.
</P>
<P>
   An ethnically pure entity goes against the terms of the 1995
Dayton Peace Accords, which ended the Bosnian war.
</P>
<P>
   Republika Srpska, as the Serb entity is known, is politically
divided into the pro-Dodik west, with its headquarters in Banja
Luka, and the nationalist-run east, based in Pale.
</P>
<P>
   ''I expect only victory'' for the party, Zelen-Karadzic told
reporters when asked about the coming election.
</P>
<P>
   She described the arrest this week of top war crimes suspect
Momcilo Krajisnik as a ''very bitter'' loss for Pale and the
hard-line faction.
</P>
<P>
   Krajisnik signed the Dayton deal but afterwards advocated Serb
secession from Bosnia. He was arrested Monday by French
peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   ''A man who signed the Dayton Peace Agreement together with
Clinton was arrested in a way they arrest mafiosi,'' she said.
''But the Americans can only do it that way. But we are decent
people and will wait for the vote and the results will show our
victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Zelen-Karadzic said she was concerned her husband could be the
next arrested. ''But we have confidence in God and we pray,'' she
added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-05-00 1843 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000405.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Highlights From Albright Interview  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Highlights from Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright's interview Wednesday with Associated Press editors and
reporters:
</P>
<P>
   On Elian Gonzalez:
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a terrible, terrible issue. It's a question of a child
needing to be with its natural parent and the desire for that child
to have a good life. It's very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   On President Fidel Castro:
</P>
<P>
   ''The question I always have about any of these dictators is are
they really interested in their people.''
</P>
<P>
   On US-Cuban relations:
</P>
<P>
   ''The embargo is the law of the land. We worked hard to put
measures that would provide additional space for the Cuban people.
We had hoped there would be enough of a change in Cuba to make more
changes possible, but that has not been Castro's choice.''
</P>
<P>
   On overtures to Iran:
</P>
<P>
   ''On Iran, my speech stands as the record of where we think
we've been, what our agenda is and where we think we can go in
mutually balanced and small steps...''
</P>
<P>
   On China-Taiwan relations:
</P>
<P>
   ''There needs to be a peaceful dialogue ... This is the only way
this can be resolved. I think we are in a phase where they are
watching each other very carefully. (Taiwanese President-elect Chen
Shui-bian's) language has moderated from the way it was earlier.
... I think that some of the tension has reduced.''
</P>
<P>
   On Chinese threats against Taiwan:
</P>
<P>
   ''We definitely don't brush (them) off. Obviously, China is an
increasingly strong and powerful and important country and we watch
very carefully and listen very carefully. But it's important not to
overreact because some of the statements have been made previously.
Our job is to make clear to them -- both actually -- that it's very
important to keep the rhetoric down.
</P>
<P>
   On relations with Congress:
</P>
<P>
   ''The Constitution is set up in such a way that it is an
invitation to struggle because Congress is given ... a lot of power
in terms of trade, and there are more and more economic issues that
are part of foreign policy. They do have increasing power. I think
this is a period where Congress is playing a huge role. I am all
for a very strong role for Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   On congressional failure to approve funding for Kosovo:
</P>
<P>
   ''We have been working very hard to try to work with the
Europeans to provide a larger part of what they need in terms of
troops and money and police and all that for Kosovo. At the same
time, I've been dealing with the (congressional funding) problem
... that I do not think has foreign policy roots .. It's very
difficult to press the Europeans to do more if I have to say this
has now been delayed for whatever reason.''
</P>
<P>
   On Mideast peace talks:
</P>
<P>
   ''It's clear that the Israelis are going to withdraw (from
Lebanon.) It would be much better that that be done within the
context of negotiation ... I think it would be an internationally
legitimatized way of doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   On the difference between Russian President Valdimir Putin and
former Russian President Boris Yeltsin:
</P>
<P>
   ''You have a sense you are getting through a meeting, in
contrast to Yeltsin who made grand statements, then we all worked.
President Yeltsin and President Clinton had a very special
relationship where they kind of looked at the future together.
Putin strikes me as a more pragmatic man who wants to get through a
very serious agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   On Latin American democracy:
</P>
<P>
   ''When I about Latin America in the varying conversations I've
had with Latin Americans and others is there is a sense of the
fragility of democracy in Latin America ... that these countries
have moved into the democratic column but because there has not
been as much work done on some of the social and economic
development issues, there is the question of what is the payoff of
democracy for the people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
