<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gap Inc. COO Resigns  </HEADLINE>
By RACHEL BECK, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Gap Inc.'s chief operating officer resigned on
Wednesday, the third top executive to leave the giant retail chain
in the last five months.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of John Wilson's departure came as the company
named a new president of its struggling Gap stores division and
reported disappointing sales for the month of March.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's resignation follows the exodus of Jeanne Jackson, who
left as head of the Banana Republic division in March to head
Wal-Mart.com, and the November departure of Gap stores president
Robert Fisher, the son of the chain's founders.
</P>
<P>
   The Gap said it will not fill the COO position.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Gap is a mature company and total corporate growth may be
at this point considered very limited,'' said Kurt Barnard,
president of the retail consulting firm Barnard's Retail Trend
Report. ''These people are very talented and they see that there
are better opportunities for themselves in other places.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the darling of the retailing world, Gap has been struggling
to find its way over the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Its namesake Gap stores -- long the anchor and big money maker of
the San Francisco-based Gap Inc. chain -- have been the most
troubled. Many of its shoppers have fled to rival retail chains as
well as its sister division -- Old Navy -- which offers trendier
fashions at cheaper prices.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Gap Inc. reported that its sales at stores open at
least a year, an industry gauge of performance, fell 11 percent,
below analysts' expectations. Much of that decline was attributed
to weakness at the Gap stores.
</P>
<P>
   The company said that the slump in March was due to the fact
that it held fewer sales promotions and there was a shift in the
Easter calendar. Most holiday sales last year took place in March
because Easter fell on April 4, but this year they will be tallied
in April, with the holiday falling on the 23rd.
</P>
<P>
   New Gap division president Ken Pilot will be charged with
stepping up sales in its stores here and abroad. Pilot was formerly
the president of Gap International.
</P>
<P>
   The company also announced a few other executive changes on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Gust was promoted to executive vice president and chief
administrative officer, responsible for real estate, corporate
communications, global affairs, legal services and human resources.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Crovitz was named executive vice president and chief
supply chain officer, while Heidi Kunz will add responsibility for
strategic planning to her title of executive vice president and
chief financial officer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-05-00 1850 </TRAILER>
