<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Tests Called for in Nazi Case  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE JAHN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- The state prosecutor on Wednesday asked
that an aging doctor accused in the deaths of nine children in a
Nazi-run clinic face new psychiatric tests to determine whether he
is fit to be retried.
</P>
<P>
   The formal request was submitted less than three weeks after Dr.
Heinrich Gross' trial was indefinitely suspended because he was
found to be suffering from dementia. It will likely be granted.
</P>
<P>
   Last month's court session was the third attempt to prosecute
Gross, 84, on charges linked to the deaths of thousands of children
killed by the Nazis because they were deemed physically, mentally
or otherwise unfit for Adolf Hitler's vision of a perfect world.
</P>
<P>
   The judge ordered the suspension March 21 after a
court-appointed psychiatrist testified that Gross' dementia had
worsened since two examinations in 1998. Although the judge had
ordered more tests over the next six months, leaving open the
possibility the trial could resume, it had appeared unlikely that
Gross would ever be prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   The new tests were requested earlier than expected, however,
after prosecutor Michael Klackl viewed a post-hearing televised
interview that showed Gross alert and able to deal with fairly
complex questions.
</P>
<P>
   Klackl told the Austria Press Agency that he had ''strong
misgivings'' about Gross' inability to stand trial after viewing
the videotape. The agency cited unnamed legal officials as saying
that a Swiss expert witness would probably examine Gross after
criticism that most Austrian psychiatrists were on cordial terms
with him.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Gross became a prominent neurologist, publishing
research based on the preserved brains of children killed by the
Nazis and was himself an expert witness at numerous court hearings
up to the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Under Nazi rule, 75,000 people across Europe, including 5,000
children, were murdered for being mentally or physically
handicapped. Children were killed by injection, medical
experimentation or simply starved. The Nazis called them ''unworthy
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Gross was put on trial twice before, but the case was thrown out
in 1950 because of legal technicalities and again in the 1980s
because the 30-year statute of limitations on manslaughter had
expired.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors filed a new set of charges, accusing him of
complicity to murder in the cases of nine children who allegedly
died as a result of abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Gross pleaded innocent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
