<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli-American's Release Postponed  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE COPANS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- The Israeli Supreme Court on Wednesday
postponed the early release of an Israeli-American serving a life
sentence for killing a Palestinian in retaliation for the stabbing
of an Israeli.
</P>
<P>
   Yoram Skolnick, a Jewish settler from an area near the West Bank
city of Hebron, was to have been released Friday after serving
seven years in prison, according to a parole board ruling last
month. President Ezer Weizman had already reduced his sentence to
11 years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Skolnick shot Moussa Abu Sabha nine times as he lay on
the ground, his hands tied behind his back, unarmed and
blindfolded. Abu Sabha had stabbed and injured a Jewish settler
moments earlier. Skolnick maintained he thought Abu Sabha had a
grenade.
</P>
<P>
   Left-wing lawmaker Zehava Galon petitioned the Supreme Court to
overturn the parole board's decision, which was denounced by peace
activists. Attorney General Elyakim Rubinstein also issued a legal
opinion saying Skolnick, 31, had not grasped the severity of his
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Skolnick told reporters before the hearing that he regretted his
action, which he called ''a one-time act, something that took one
second.''
</P>
<P>
   After listening to three hours of arguments from both sides, a
seven-judge panel decided to postpone its ruling, and issued a
temporary restraining order against Skolnick's release until it
rules. It did not say when that would be.
</P>
<P>
   Nationalist lawmaker Benny Elon, who petitioned the court to
permit the early release, argued that it was unfair to release
Palestinian militants who have harmed Israelis as part of a peace
agreement with the Palestinian Authority and not release Jews who
have harmed Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   Weizman said Wednesday that Israel's release of Palestinian
militants prompted him to reduce Skolnick's sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has released hundreds of Palestinians who injured
Israelis in attacks before peace accords were signed, but has
refused to negotiate the release of Palestinians who killed
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Skolnick was born in Israel and has U.S. citizenship through his
parents, who immigrated to Israel from New York in 1963.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
