<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Courting Hispanics With New Ad  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA MECKLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Going after the traditionally Democratic
Hispanic vote, Republicans are airing a Spanish-language TV ad in
California that asks voters to at least consider the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   ''This year I plan to keep an open mind and vote for the best
person, and that includes Republicans,'' Christina Bustos, a Latina
from Los Angeles says in the ad, which is also airing in English.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Committee is spending $125,000 to test
the ad in the Fresno, Calif., area and plans to take it national if
it proves effective. This year, the party plans to spend $7 million
to $10 million on a media campaign reaching out to Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   Fresno, with a sizable Hispanic population, is located in
central California in the heart of the state's richest agricultural
area. The ads there will run enough times so that the average TV
viewer will see them 12 times.
</P>
<P>
   As the fastest growing ethnic group in America, Hispanics are
being courted by both Democrats and Republicans. Historically,
Democrats have had the advantage, and the GOP wasn't helped in
California by pushing Proposition 187, an effort to deny government
services to illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide Republican candidates were getting around 40 percent
of the Latino vote in California before that battle and are now
getting 20 to 25 percent, according to exit polls.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's an ebb and flow in politics,'' Republican national
chairman Jim Nicholson told reporters in Sacramento, Calif.
''That's the past. Whatever that was is the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats noted that while the GOP is airing in an effort to
attract Hispanics, former California Gov. Pete Wilson, a supporter
of George W. Bush, has raised money for a group that is running ads
criticizing Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the Republicans want to attract more Hispanic voters,
they'll have to change their policies to reflect what our community
believes in,'' said Rep. Loretta Sanchez of California, general
co-chair of the Democratic National Committee. ''The discriminatory
policies that the Republican party and people like Pete Wilson
advocate have sent a loud and clear message to Latinos across the
country that unlike Democrats, there is no room for us in their
party.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans think they have a new opportunity to attract
Hispanics this year.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. Bush, who speaks Spanish, attracted as much as half
the Hispanic vote during his 1998 re-election victory, and Bush has
rejected anti-immigration views that marked the California debate.
</P>
<P>
   ''There isn't that much difference between Latinos and
Republicans. We share the same core values,'' Nicholson said.
</P>
<P>
   The new ads open with images of modern downtown Los Angeles
skyscrapers, then a Latino neighborhood market. The pictures move
to shots of family scenes and suburban streets as Bustos describes
the progress of her family from Mexican immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ''My parents were dreamers. They came to Los Angeles from Mexico
wanting a better future. They learned the language, worked hard and
raised a family,'' Bustos says.
</P>
<P>
   She concludes that she will consider Republicans because ''now,
it's our time to dream.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-05-00 1941 </TRAILER>
