<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Toyota To Shift Sienna Production  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRINCETON, Ind. (AP) -- Toyota Motor Corp. will shift production
of its Sienna minivan from Georgetown, Ky., to this southwestern
Indiana city in 2003, company officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota also announced Wednesday that its factory in Cambridge,
Ontario, will start producing the Lexus RX 300 sport utility
vehicle in 2003. Employment at the plant 80 miles west of Toronto
is expected to increase from 2,700 to 3,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Ontario plant already builds the Corolla and the Solara, so
to make room for the RX 300, production of the Solara will be moved
to Georgetown that year.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota announced in December that it would spend $800 million to
expand the Indiana plant to accommodate production of a third
vehicle. Toyota already has invested $1.2 billion in the plant,
which now makes the Tundra pickup truck and will begin producing a
new sport utility vehicle, the Sequoia, this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion will increase the plant's work force by 2,000,
bringing total employment there to 4,300. It will also double
annual production capacity to 300,000 vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The move won't affect the number of jobs at the Kentucky plant
because it will begin building the Camry Solara, said Michael Goss,
a spokesman for the Toyota Motor Manufacturing Indiana Inc. plant.
</P>
<P>
   The Kentucky plant, which has a production capacity of about
500,000 vehicles per year, also will continue to manufacture the
Camry and the Avalon, which share the same platform as the Solara.
</P>
<P>
   ''This will really enable them to maximize their production
efficiencies there,'' said Barbara McDaniel, a spokeswoman for
Toyota Motor Manufacturing North America Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The RX 300 will be the first Lexus vehicle manufactured outside
of Japan, McDaniel said. It will be the ninth Toyota model built in
the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The changes will boost the automaker's total North American
annual production capacity from 1.25 million vehicles to 1.45
million vehicles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
