<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Post-Dispatch Editor Resigns  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Cole Campbell resigned Wednesday as editor of
the St. Louis Post-Dispatch to become a fellow at the Poynter
Institute of Media Studies.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, 46, has been editor since October 1996. He came to the
Post-Dispatch from The Virginian-Pilot in Norfolk, Va.
</P>
<P>
   During his tenure, the newspaper changed its graphic design,
launched three new zoned editions and created the ''Imagine St.
Louis'' section.
</P>
<P>
   The Post-Dispatch, flagship of Pulitzer Inc., became an
independent, publicly traded company in March 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Publisher Terry Egger said Campbell ''made significant
contributions when we were rudderless as a company. His work and
leadership in developing a strategic plan for this company was
outstanding and will benefit this company for a long time to
come.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell will join Poynter, a journalism education center and
think tank, on May 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
