<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arnn Named Hillsdale College Head  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HILLSDALE, Mich. (AP) -- Trustees at conservative Hillsdale
College on Wednesday named the president of a California think tank
as the school's new president.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Arnn replaces George Roche III, who abruptly retired in
November amid allegations he had a lengthy affair with his
daughter-in-law, Lissa Roche. She had committed suicide in October.
</P>
<P>
   Arnn, an outspoken critic of affirmative action who leads the
Claremont Institute in Claremont, Calif., was chosen unanimously by
the school's 35-member board of trustees.
</P>
<P>
   ''He brings loads to Hillsdale College. He has terrific skills,
all of the skills that will help Hillsdale move forward smartly,''
said William Brodbeck, who led the presidential search committee.
</P>
<P>
   During his tenure, Roche transformed Hillsdale from a
little-known college to a beacon of the conservative movement. The
college gained national attention for refusing to accept any
federal aid so it wouldn't have to comply with federal regulations,
including affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   But Roche stepped down abruptly after allegations surfaced about
the alleged 19-year affair with Lissa Roche, who was 41 when she
died Oct. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Arnn, who is expected to take over duties at Hillsdale in June,
has led the Claremont Institute since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   An outspoken critic of affirmative action, he was the founding
chairman of Proposition 209, a successful 1996 ballot initiative
that banned affirmative action in California. He also is a member
of the Congressional Policy Advisory Board, which helps decide
policy for Republicans in the U.S. House.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
