<HEADLINE> Fla. Arms Store To Warn New Yorkers  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) -- A Florida-based weapons store will
warn customers in New York that some of its products are illegal
there after a 13-year-old boy obtained deadly weapons from the
company's Web site, the New York attorney general said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The boy used a parent's credit card to obtain weapons that are
illegal in New York from Family Defense Products Inc. of Ocala,
Fla., said Attorney General Eliot Spitzer. The stun guns,
switchblades, blackjacks and eight-pointed martial arts stars the
boy purchased were seized by authorities after the boy's parents
intercepted the items.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer described the boy as emotionally disturbed but would not
give details and would not comment on whether he made threats or
why he bought the weapons. Because his parents immediately
contacted authorities, the boy will not face criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   ''The notion that a 13-year-old could go online and get all
these weapons, the very weapons that we see kids bringing into
schools and causing such horrendous incidents, is what really
concerns us,'' Spitzer said.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said Family Defense's owners claimed to be unaware of
New York's laws. A woman who answered the phone for the company
Wednesday refused to give her name and said the owners were out of
town.
</P>
<P>
   Under the settlement, the company's Web site will say that it
will not sell illegal weapons to New Yorkers. The company will also
warn past customers that they might be subject to arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: attorney general's site, http://www.oag.state.ny.us
</P>
</TEXT>
