<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Joke controversy, reaction to 'threat' test newcomer's politicalskills  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- ''I know politics can be tough. I do know
how to take a punch. But sometimes people go too far during
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   And with that, Democratic U.S. Senate candidate Jon Corzine
firmly denounced a man who had left a testy phone message with a
staff member.
</P>
<P>
   This, combined with a second phone call in which the man was
rude to his wife, prompted Corzine to assemble the New York
television media in Newark this week to share his outrage over what
he proclaimed to be the dirtiest form of gutter politics.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., joined Corzine, though he
continues to insist that he is neutral in his primary contest with
former Gov. Jim Florio. Torricelli said he attended only to
sympathize with Corzine and to hope for the day when such horror
tactics will be banished from New Jersey politics.
</P>
<P>
   The culprit behind all this was one Michael Cino, an officer in
the Columbus Coalition, an Italian-America political group.
</P>
<P>
   Joanne Corzine said Cino called her at home and threatened to
expose ''dirt'' if Corzine did not agree to have a meeting. Corzine
says Cino had wanted a job with the campaign, which has turned
heads by paying $20,000-a-month salaries to a whole team of
staffers.
</P>
<P>
   ''There will be no meeting, not today, not ever,'' Corzine said
as a room full of reporters began to question the candidate openly
about whether this alleged offense was worth so much attention.
</P>
<P>
   Cino has not returned several telephone messages this week from
The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   The event marked a strange week in a state where strange
politics is the norm.
</P>
<P>
   -- The news breaks that an Italian-American anti-defamation group
has evidence that Corzine insulted Italians at two meetings,
greeting one businessman with, ''Oh, you make cement shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Corzine announces a half-denial: ''I shouldn't have said what
I am reported to have said, and if I did, I apologize.''
</P>
<P>
   His subsequent revisions include: ''I am not trying to deny that
I said or didn't say anything. I don't remember what I said,'' and,
''If I offended, I apologize, and that is where I want to leave
this because I can't deny or confirm the kind of language that was
used in a conversation (nine months ago).''
</P>
<P>
   -- Corzine holds another news conference to decry Cino as a
midnight blackmailer evidently because he was threatening to make
public another Italian joke Corzine may or may not have said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   At issue here is how Corzine reacts, how he copes with pressure
from the news media and how he handles mistakes that all human
beings make.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have spent millions trying to craft a careful image here
of a rags to riches guy who became a world-class business leader,''
said David Rebovich, a political analyst at Rider University. ''He
is trying to show himself as a serious businessman who knows how
the world works.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebovich said Corzine fraying under stress suggests ''the
tenuousness of the image that his campaign has crafted.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebovich said the blackmail allegations against Cino, who has
proclaimed innocence, fed the stereotype. ''All this does is
perpetuate the Italian-American issue. Now the mob is chasing me,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Independent political analyst Jim McQueeny said the news
conference this week to repeat the apology and to demonize an
insignificant figure was an astonishing mistake. ''Everybody who
sees this sees weakness,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McQueeny also said this was not the right moment to have
Torricelli rally to his side with an in-person endorsement. ''Bob's
appearance at that press conference made Corzine look like even
more of a victim,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Corzine's candidacy is really damaged. The events of
the past week are too minor and too early. Manny Alfano, the head
of the group that disclosed the jokes, said Corzine apologized, and
that is good enough for him.
</P>
<P>
   ''A huge reality about the Corzine campaign, when it is factored
in, is that when he makes mistakes, he has a $10 million eraser on
the end of that pencil,'' McQueeny said.
</P>
<P>
   But McQueeny said political skills are required for political
victory, and in the past week Corzine has not displayed skill.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is the allure of saying you are the non-politician. So
many have taken that and cloaked themselves with it. So many of
them take that with them into oblivion,'' he said. ''That is a
problem. He is not enough of a politician.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine wants to avoid a fistfight with Florio but Rebovich said
mistakes like this make the street brawl harder to avoid. ''Jon
Corzine may have to mix it up a little more on Jim Florio's terms,
and go beyond his general and generous campaign ad that says I am
for everything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The next trap for Corzine is openly set.
</P>
<P>
   The Florio campaign intends to hammer Corzine for his
association with Goldman Sachs. Corzine has used his chairmanship
of the investment firm as a feather in his political cap, boasting
of his role there in creating ''700,000 New Jersey company jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   When the question was asked whether it would be fair for Florio
to attack him on less favorable aspects of his Goldman Sachs
background, Corzine cried foul, saying he is the candidate, not his
firm.
</P>
<P>
   It is doubtful this defense will play well with Democrats, many
who see tough politics as a test of desire. ''People want to see
that you really want it,'' McQueeny said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-05-00 2018 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
