<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heavy Security at S.C. Flag March  </HEADLINE>
By JIM DAVENPORT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANDY RUN, S.C. (AP) -- With police leading the way to ease
tensions, protesters on Wednesday continued their march to the
Statehouse to object to the flying of the Confederate Flag.
</P>
<P>
   Each time the roughly 50 marchers approached Confederate
flag-waving supporters along U.S. 176, state law enforcement
officers emerged from a motor home in front and talked to the flag
supporters until the marchers passed.
</P>
<P>
   Few cross words were exchanged and the police and protesters
repeated the scene every couple of miles. A police plane circled
overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Those who want the flag lowered from the Statehouse in Columbia
say it represents hate and slavery. Supporters see it as a heritage
symbol that honors Confederate war dead.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature is squabbling about what to do. Lawmakers raised
the flag in 1962 to commemorate the Civil War centennial and in
1995 gave themselves sole power to lower it.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People
has started a tourism boycott of the state in protest. South
Carolina's largest convention and visitor bureaus have reported 122
conventions and group meetings canceled statewide with losses
approaching $10 million. Tourism officials say exact numbers on the
boycott's impact are impossible to calculate.
</P>
<P>
   Charleston Mayor Joseph P. Riley Jr. has led the ''Get in Step''
march through the state's rural heartland since it left his city
Sunday, hoping that more public attention will force lawmakers to
act. A protest is planned Thursday in Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   He has noticed some of the signs that flag supporters have put
all along the route proclaiming, ''Keep the flag, Dump Riley.''
</P>
<P>
   The people putting them up ''are obviously unemployed,'' Riley
said. ''They are the minority.''
</P>
<P>
   John Bradley, one of the leaders of the pro-flag group, said he
was retired, not unemployed. The march won't work, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The flag is flying right now ... No matter what Riley says,''
Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   The marchers spent the day in one of South Carolina's most
racially balanced counties. Calhoun County has about 600 more
blacks than whites in its population of just around 13,700 people
and many of them are descendants of cotton mill and sharecropper
families. Racial tensions have been seen there, however, as
desegregation was forced.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the town of Cameron chose to tear down its
whites-only school rather than integrate. The town's school
district had been labeled a ''hard core resistor'' by the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   The march started with about 600 people on Sunday and was down
to 50 Wednesday afternoon. Marchers were being shuttled in and out
so those who can spend only a short time still can participate.
</P>
<P>
   The state said the Public Safety Department has spent at least
$23,000 to provide security at a pro-flag Statehouse demonstration
in January and at a Martin Luther King Jr. Day rally nearly two
weeks later that attracted 46,000 people. Two rallies planned for
the Statehouse grounds Thursday will add even more expense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-05-00 2022 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
