<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ford To Give Ads Environmental Bent  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. will give all of its corporate
brand advertising an environmental theme, starting with a special
edition of Time magazine commemorating Earth Day, the company said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ford is the exclusive sponsor for the magazine, which goes on
sale April 19 worldwide. Ford also will air TV ads, put up outdoor
ads in major cities before Earth Day on April 22, and host a
concert in San Francisco on April 15.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is part of a broader push at Ford to reduce
pollution from its operations and improve its image. Ford's
chairman, William Clay Ford Jr., is a self-described ''lifelong
environmentalist'' and has pledged to make the world's No. 2
automaker the industry leader in developing clean vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The ads will use the corporate logo -- the words ''Ford Motor
Company'' in script lettering -- rather than the familiar blue oval
Ford logo.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Cervantez, manager of Ford corporate marketing, said
the ads were the first Ford corporate campaign to focus on a single
theme. She declined to say how much the company was spending on the
ads or the magazine, but said it was comparable to the ad spending
for a new car introduction.
</P>
<P>
   The edition of Time, ''How to Save the Earth and the Heroes for
the Planet Who Are Making it Happen,'' is the first global special
edition of the magazine, which has 30 million readers worldwide.
Time officials said Ford had no say in the magazine's editorial
content.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.ford.com
</P>
</TEXT>
