<HEADLINE> Report: Driver Didn't Heed Warning  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- The driver of a school bus struck by a
freight train did not observe warnings before crossing the tracks,
according to a state police report released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Rhonda Cloer drove the bus that crossed in front of a CSX train,
killing three children in Tennga, Ga., just over the Tennessee
line, on March 28. According to the Tennessee Highway Patrol
report, Cloer failed to obey traffic signs posted at the railroad
crossing and did not observe other warnings, such as the train's
whistle blowing.
</P>
<P>
   Polk County District Attorney Jerry Estes will decide if charges
should be filed, said Highway Patrol spokeswoman Dana Keeton. Estes
was in staff training and unavailable Wednesday, his office said.
</P>
<P>
   Cloer's attorney, Greg Melton, said the driver will not talk to
investigators until she is allowed to view a videotape taken from a
camera aboard the bus. Police said the tape is evidence that cannot
be released.
</P>
<P>
   National Transportation Safety Board investigators have said
they do not know how fast the school bus was going or if Cloer
tried to stop, but are reviewing copies of the videotape.
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturer examined the bus' antilock braking system and
told the NTSB it was working properly. The train's crew members
said they sounded their whistle before the crash and tried to apply
the emergency brake, but could not stop in time.
</P>
<P>
   Cloer and four other children were injured in the wreck. Cloer's
5-year-old daughter and an 8-year-old boy remained hospitalized in
critical condition Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
