<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Down in Early Trading  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell slightly early Thursday after
further weakness on Wall Street. The dollar was lower against the
yen.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 4.05 points,
or 0.02 percent, to 20,458.72 in the first 30 minutes of trading.
On Wednesday, the average closed down 132.16 points, or 0.64
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar bought 104.98 yen, down 0.12 yen from late Wednesday
in Tokyo but above its late New York level of 104.66 yen.
</P>
<P>
   On the stock market, the Nikkei index weakened as investors
remained cautious amid recent volatile trading in New York.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 130.92
points to 11,033.92 at Wednesday's close. But the Nasdaq composite
index gained 20.33 to 4,169.22.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was down 6.17 points, or 0.36 percent, to 1,688.88.
The TOPIX closed down 19.24 points, or 1.12 percent, the day
before.
</P>
<P>
   In currency dealings, the dollar remained under some selling
pressure amid expectations Japan's economy will continue to recover
under new Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori.
</P>
<P>
   A ruling party insider, he was elected Wednesday to replace
Keizo Obuchi, who remains in a coma and on life support at a Tokyo
hospital after suffering a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said players were avoiding making significant moves
ahead of a meeting of finance officials of the Group of Seven
industrialized nations late next week.
</P>
<P>
   Finance Ministers and central bankers from the United States,
Japan, Britain, France, Germany, Italy and Canada are scheduled to
meet in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 100.88 yen, down
from 101.44 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell
to 1.7500 percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.7750 percent. Its
price rose 0.22 point to 101.29.
</P>
</TEXT>
