<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wednesday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Liberals Accused of Politicizing Health Care
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Premier Mike Harris accused the federal Liberals
of playing politics with medicare Wednesday as he rejected Ottawa's
claim Ontario is the obstacle to an agreement on health care.
</P>
<P>
   Harris says federal Health Minister Allan Rock brought nothing
constructive to the table at last week's two-day meeting of health
ministers near Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ''To date, we've heard the word reform but not one little bit
about what he likes about ours, what he dislikes, what he'd like to
see nationally,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government, he suggested, is trying to portray
itself as a defender of medicare, while holding back money the
provinces need so it can go on a health-care spending spree in the
next election, expected within 15 months.
</P>
<P>
   Rock has rejected that allegation, but Nova Scotia Health
Minister Jamie Muir said Wednesday he has doubts about Ottawa's
motives.
</P>
<P>
   Muir also said Prime Minister Jean Chretien's refusal to hold a
quick first ministers' meeting on health suggests Ottawa isn't
prepared to take an activist role.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Klees's Withdrawal From Ontario Race Questioned
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- Some Canadian Alliance MPs are questioning the
credibility of Ontario provincial politician Frank Klees's
explanation for suddenly withdrawing from the party's leadership
race.
</P>
<P>
   MP Ian McClelland called Klees's rationale for bowing out
''fishy,'' and suggested the whole story has yet to come out.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's insane, which further underscores the fact that the
excuse that he gave for deciding not to run, in my opinion, was
specious at best,'' McClelland said outside the Alliance's caucus
meeting Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Klees announced Tuesday he wouldn't run for the leadership
because he could not agree to a condition placed on him by a key
campaign donor. The unnamed donor allegedly wanted him to throw his
support behind another candidate if he lost the first ballot of the
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Klees denies any ulterior motive for backing out, but some
Alliance members doubt that.
</P>
<P>
   They note that since voting for a leadership occurs by mail
rather than at a convention, it would be difficult to ensure
thousands of members agree to throw their support behind a
particular candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Fatal Accident Spurs Debate on Senior Driving
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- A fatal accident in which an 84-year-old driver
is accused of striking a pedestrian and dragging her several blocks
under her car has touched off debate about whether seniors are safe
behind the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Police have not determined if age played a role in the deadly
incident, but safety activists cited studies Wednesday that suggest
driving abilities deteriorate as a person gets older.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Canada Safety Council says forcing seniors to hang up
their car keys would be a disservice to society, making the elderly
virtual shut-ins or leaving responsibility for their transport to
their families.
</P>
<P>
   A 43-year-old pedestrian was struck Tuesday at a crosswalk and
dragged for almost one kilometer before the vehicle turned into a
residential driveway. There, the woman's body dislodged and
slumped, as the car headed for the garage.
</P>
<P>
   The body sat on the driveway for 30 minutes before a neighbor
made the grisly discovery around 10:30 p.m. and phoned police.
</P>
<P>
   Pilar Hicks was charged with failing to stop causing death and
careless driving.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
