<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NC School Ends Same-sex Classes  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIAN TRAIL, N.C. (AP) -- A middle school ended the experimental
use of same-sex classes for some eighth-graders after the American
Civil Liberties Union complained the classes discriminated against
girls.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Parkwood Middle School began the program in October
to see whether students going through puberty learned better
without distractions from the opposite sex.
</P>
<P>
   The ACLU filed a complaint in February with the federal Office
for Civil Rights. School officials sent a letter to the OCR office
last week saying the classes had been disbanded.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Ross, executive director of the state chapter of the
ACLU, said the classes violated a 1972 law barring sexual
discrimination at schools that receive federal money.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bottom line is that it violates the law on its face,''
Ross said Wednesday. ''The history of separating women and men and
boys and girls for academic classes has always redounded to the
detriment of girls, politically and professionally.''
</P>
<P>
   Parkwood principal Larry Stinson said the classes were
temporary, involved only 55 of the school's 335 eighth graders, and
parents were notified well in advance.
</P>
<P>
   Stinson said he believes the students showed improvement during
the brief experiment. ''If it wasn't working, we would have jerked
it out of there a long time ago,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
