<HEADLINE> Jimmy Carter Visits White House  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- After talking all day with economic experts,
President Clinton, who is leading the nation during its largest
period of expansion, got a house call Wednesday from a predecessor
whose re-election defeat was partly blamed on a recession.
</P>
<P>
   Former President Jimmy Carter and his wife, Rosalynn, dropped in
on Clinton in the afternoon to show some of their family members
their old digs. Carter, dressed in a blue check shirt, dark blazer
and gray slacks, and Mrs. Carter, bundled in a tan trench coat to
block a cool breeze, stood on a balcony overlooking the South Lawn
and waved to Clinton as he boarded a helicopter bound for
Chappaqua, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   About a half-dozen young people joined the 39th president and
took snapshots of Marine One as it flew toward the illuminated
Washington Monument.
</P>
<P>
   ''He just wanted to show his grandchildren the house -- give them
the tour,'' the White House press office said.
</P>
