<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AM-CT-XGR--Treasurer Reform, Conn Bjt,600  </HEADLINE>
sdstfpr
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- A controversial treasurer reform bill
debated in the House on Wednesday was attacked by opponents who
said the measure doesn't contain enough safeguards to prevent
another corruption scandal in the state Treasurer's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said the measure will strengthen oversight of state
pension fund investments and eliminate the controversial ''finder's
fees'' that formerly were paid in connection with investment
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would replace the deputy treasurer with a chief
investment officer and also prohibit the state treasurer, any
candidate for state treasurer or any member of the Investment
Advisory Council, from seeking campaign contributions from persons
connected to an investment company.
</P>
<P>
   Finance Committee co-chairwoman Anne McDonald, D-Stamford, said
the bill would go a long way toward ensuring there are no further
scandals in the state treasurer's office.
</P>
<P>
   But House Minority Leader Robert Ward, R-North Branford, said
finder's fees will still exist but will be called something else.
The State Ethics Commission should be given the responsibility of
defining what constitutes a finder's fee, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Plofsky, executive director of the State Ethics Commission,
said the House bill actually weakens the current law and
essentially leaves oversight in the hands of the treasurer.
</P>
<P>
   ''This doesn't cure the problem. It makes it worse,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Plofsky noted that the House bill permits fees to be paid to
''investment professionals.'' He added, ''Anybody can hang out a
shingle and call himself an investment professional.''
</P>
<P>
   Plofsky said he supported a failed Republican amendment that
would have allowed fees to be paid only to licensed financial
counselors who have met rigorous standards set down by Federal
Communications Commission.
</P>
<P>
   If the state Senate doesn't repair the bill, Plofsky said he
will ask the governor to veto the measure.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP amendment, offered by Ward, was defeated 91-57, with the
voting following party lines.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment called for the creation of a powerful, bipartisan
board of trustees that would have superseded the current Investment
Advisory Council and would have the final say on all investments.
Republicans said 47 other states currently use this investment
approach.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald said the bill supported by the Democrats will require
the treasurer to adopt an investment policy and present it to the
IAC. The IAC will provide adequate oversight, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill supported by the Democrats, the treasurer would
be barred from awarding a contract for trust fund-related activity
until the IAC has reviewed the recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   The reform was inspired by last year's corruption scandal
surrounding former state Treasurer Paul J. Silvester. He pleaded
guilty in September to charges of racketeering and money laundering
related to fund-raising in his failed 1998 campaign. He admitted
accepting kickbacks in the form of campaign donations from
companies with which he invested state pension money, and raising
money for the campaigns of others including Gov. John G. Rowland,
who appointed Silvester after the former treasurer resigned to go
to work for an investment company that had done business with the
state.
</P>
<P>
   The reform bill would require the treasurer to wait at least one
year from the date a contract is negotiated before going to work
for the company, if the contract amounts to at least $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also restricts the governor's power to appoint someone
to fill a vacancy in the Treasurer's Office when the General
Assembly is not in session.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-05-00 2217 </TRAILER>
