<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sweepstakes Firm Settles Suits  </HEADLINE>
By HUNTER T. GEORGE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) -- Mary Blake wanted to win a sweepstakes so
badly that she often went without groceries and medicine so she
could buy merchandise that boosted her chances.
</P>
<P>
   When the mail came, family members say, the 82-year-old Olympia
woman would immediately fill out the entry forms and rush to the
post office with the idea of beating deadlines for free gifts. She
wrote notes on her checks, asking in vain for the sweepstakes firms
not to cash them until her Social Security check was deposited.
</P>
<P>
   Blake is the kind of consumer that the nation's attorneys
general are hoping will benefit from a settlement announced
Wednesday with one of the country's biggest sweepstakes firms.
</P>
<P>
   United States Sales Corp. of Northridge, Calif., agreed to
refund $30 million to consumers in 48 states and the District of
Columbia, and to change its marketing practices. Connecticut and
Iowa are not involved in the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the firm, which does business as United States
Purchasing Exchange or USPE, agreed to a separate $20 million
settlement that resolves a class-action lawsuit filed in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal with the states, USPE agreed to provide
''Sweepstakes Facts'' in big print on its contest entry forms
explaining that entrants have not yet won prizes and are not
required to buy anything to enter or improve their chances of
winning. It also will disclose the odds of winning a prize.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement was negotiated by a task force representing
attorneys general from every state except Iowa and Connecticut. It
was praised across the country as a blueprint for the industry,
which is under fire for alleged deceptive marketing practices.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Washington state sued Publishers Clearinghouse,
American Family Publishers and Time Inc. Those companies have
denied any wrongdoing. Trial is scheduled in September.
</P>
<P>
   ''A favorite target of these companies are the elderly, who are
duped into believing a small investment will net them millions,''
Washington state Attorney General Christine Gregoire said. ''This
should send a very clear message that it's time to stop the
deception.''
</P>
<P>
   USPE has been in business since 1967 and has undergone a recent
downsizing, admitted no wrongdoing under the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the company recognized that growing attention to the
issue and ''inappropriate purchasing by some customers'' made it
clear that changes were needed, spokesman Harvey Englander said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're a model for the entire industry in this settlement,'' he
said. ''We stepped up to the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   The firm sells low-cost household items and has given away
millions in prizes, including a $3.3 million jackpot a few weeks
ago to a winner in Florida, Englander said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the settlement, USPE customers who spent at least $1,870
in either 1997, 1998 or 1999 are eligible for restitution. Eligible
consumers will be contacted within six months by a private company
hired by the states to administer the restitution.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Walsh, an assistant Washington attorney general who was
involved in the negotiations, said more than 150,000 consumers
nationwide could receive restitution under the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   USPE also agreed to discontinue mailings to ''high activity''
customers, defined as those who make more than 25 purchases or
spend more than $935 on sweepstakes offers in a year.
</P>
<P>
   It will come too late for Blake, who now lives in the
Alzheimer's wing of a nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   Her family cleaned out ''truckloads'' of useless merchandise
that Blake bought over the years from companies offering big
prizes, daughter-in-law Sherry Blake said Wednesday. Mary Blake
bought magazines, sports memorabilia and even videocassette tapes,
although she does not own a VCR.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mom was a firm believer that, to win, you have to buy,''
Sherry Blake said, adding that the family sometimes paid as much as
$800 to $1,000 to cover the monthly bills.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's really sad. She always wanted to win a car because hers
was so bad. She could have bought 10 or 12 of them for the money
she spent. She was so depressed because she never won and she
couldn't understand why.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-05-00 2220 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
