<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressGeorge W. Fry:
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- George W. Fry, a former superintendent
of the Great Smoky Mountains National Park, died Tuesday of
complications from surgery. He was 89.
</P>
<P>
   Fry, who had a 40-year career with the U.S. Forest Service and
the National Park Service, first joined the Civilian Conservation
Corps as a forester, then the park service. Rising through the
ranks at several national parks, Fry received the Interior
Department's Meritorious Service Award and Distinguished Service
Award.
</P>
<P>
   He was superintendent of the Smokies from 1963 to 1969.
Roy Grizzell:
</P>
<P>
   MOSS POINT, Miss. (AP) -- Roy Grizzell, a reverend and military
veteran who was awarded France's highest honor for his service in
World War I, died Tuesday. He was 108.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Grizzell was honored by French Consul General Jean
Paul Manchou with France's highest honor, the Medal of Chevalier of
the Legion of Honor.
</P>
<P>
   He was a pastor at 14 churches in Mississippi and Alabama during
his 50 years in the ministry.
Earl L. Hanson:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Earl L. Hanson, a prominent criminal defense
attorney who successfully defended pornography star John Holmes,
died Saturday of a heart attack. He was 67.
</P>
<P>
   Hanson represented about 3,000 defendants during a four-decade
career.
</P>
<P>
   The Criminal Justice Section of the Los Angeles County Bar
Association recently named Hanson as attorney of the year.
</P>
<P>
   He was best known for representing Holmes, who was charged with
murdering four people in 1981. Hanson and Egers won a jury verdict
of not guilty, though Holmes' former wife testified the actor told
her he was present during the slayings.
Mary Smith McClain:
</P>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- Blues singer Mary Smith McClain,
better known to fans as ''Diamond Teeth Mary,'' died Tuesday. She
was believed to have been 97 or 98.
</P>
<P>
   McClain was a teen-ager posing as a boy when she hopped a train
in her native West Virginia to begin a new life as a traveling
blues musician more than 80 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   She went from singing at carnivals with the Rabbit Foot
Minstrels to the Chicago Blues Festival, New York City's Carnegie
Hall and Europe. She sang with such music greats as B.B. King, Duke
Ellington, Billie Holiday and Louis Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   McClain, who once had diamonds set in her teeth, was considered
the world's oldest-performing true blues musician, appearing at
local clubs until two weeks ago.
Terence McKenna:
</P>
<P>
   SAN RAFAEL, Calif. (AP) -- Terence McKenna, spiritual theorist
and author of several books proclaiming the virtues of psychedelic
mushrooms, died Monday of brain cancer. He was 53.
</P>
<P>
   One of McKenna's best known books was 1975's ''The Invisible
Landscape: Mind, Hallucinogens, and the I Ching,'' which he
co-wrote with his brother Dennis. ''Food of the Gods,'' published
in 1992, and 1993's ''True Hallucinations'' followed in the same
vein, exploring the idea of consciousness and its link with nature
and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   McKenna traveled extensively through Asia, Europe and South
America before completing a self-tailored degree in Shamanology at
Berkeley in 1975.
Robert E. Miller:
</P>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- Robert E. Miller, an Associated Press
reporter who covered the Ohio Statehouse for more than 30 years,
died Tuesday of complications from cancer. He was 66.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who covered the administrations of five Ohio governors
and seven national political conventions, joined the AP in
Charleston, W.Va., in March 1957. Two weeks later, he was named
Bluefield, W.Va., correspondent and the following year, he
transferred to the news cooperative's Huntington, W.Va., bureau.
</P>
<P>
   He transferred to Columbus in 1960, joining the bureau as a
radio newsman. He moved to full-time coverage of the Ohio
Legislature in 1964. He resigned in 1968 to join Gongwer News
Service, which provides daily Statehouse coverage to statewide
trade and professional organizations, then returned to the Ohio AP
Statehouse bureau in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   The former president and a lifetime member of the Ohio
Legislative Correspondents Association also served as lead
political writer for the Ohio AP until his retirement on Feb. 1,
1994. He returned to Gongwer on a part-time basis, covering
legislative sessions until he became ill last year.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's career was not limited to government and political
coverage. He was one of the lead writers in the AP's coverage of
the December 1967 collapse of the Silver Bridge, which connected
Gallipolis, Ohio, to Point Pleasant, W.Va., across the Ohio River.
The collapse, which killed 46 people, prompted federal regulations
requiring states to inspect bridges every other year and post
weight limits on those spans.
</P>
<P>
   He was a stickler for getting the story straight -- so much so,
that he wrote his own obituary.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors include two sisters, Rosemary Jewell of Columbus, and
Connie Adkins of Hilliard; a niece and two grandnephews.
Lee Petty:
</P>
<P>
   GREENSBORO N.C. (AP) -- Lee Petty, a stock car pioneer and the
patriarch of a racing dynasty, died Wednesday following surgery for
a stomach aneurysm. He was 86.
</P>
<P>
   Petty was one of the princes of racing during the stock car
circuit's infancy in the 1940s and 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   He was the first winner of the Daytona 500 and a three-time
champion on what has become the Winston Cup circuit. He also won
the inaugural Daytona 500 in 1959, beating Johnny Beauchamp in a
photo finish that wasn't decided for three days.
</P>
<P>
   Petty was one of the first stars in stock car racing's formative
years. He began his career with an eight-race schedule in 1949 and
went on to score 55 career wins, becoming a three-time Grand
National champion.
</P>
<P>
   His 55 career wins placed him seventh on the list of the most
victorious drivers in NASCAR Winston Cup history. Richard Petty
ranks first with 200 wins.
John Rollins :
</P>
<P>
   DOVER, Del. (AP) -- Businessman, Republican fund-raiser and
one-time Delaware Lt. Gov. John Rollins died Tuesday. He was 83.
</P>
<P>
   Born a poor Georgia farm boy, Rollins took a $500 investment in
a car dealership and parlayed it into a fortune that saw him found
five companies that made it onto the New York Stock Exchange and
carried him into the presence of senators, presidents and American
heroes.
</P>
<P>
   He founded Rollins Truck Leasing Corp., the Rollins
Environmental Services Inc., which managed hazardous waste, and
Rollins Inc., which acquired Orrin Pest Control.
</P>
<P>
   In his office in Wilmington, photographs cover the walls --
Rollins with former Presidents Bush, Reagan and Nixon; with Senate
Majority Leader and one-time Republican presidential nominee Bob
Dole; former Vice President Dan Quayle; and former chairman of the
Joint Chiefs of Staff Colin Powell.
William Alfred Shack:
</P>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) -- William Alfred Shack, a scholar of
African cultures and professor emeritus of anthropology at the
University of California, Berkeley, died Friday of cancer. He was
76.
</P>
<P>
   Shack, who was dean emeritus of the school's graduate division,
was internationally known for his work on the Gurage people of
Ethiopia and for a series of books on African society.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Berkeley awarded him its highest honor, the Berkeley
Citation, in recognition of his multiple contributions.
Carl Sitter:
</P>
<P>
   PUEBLO, Colo. (AP) -- Carl Sitter, a Pueblo native who won the
Medal of Honor for his service as a Marine captain in the Korean
War, died of pneumonia Tuesday. He was 77.
</P>
<P>
   Sitter received the Medal of Honor -- the nation's highest
military award -- for his actions as a commanding officer during a
two-day battle at Hagaru-Ki in November 1950. The fighting lasted
36 hours, and Sitter endured grenade burns to his face, arms and
chest.
</P>
<P>
   He refused to evacuate as the fight continued. More than half of
his company was killed, wounded or captured, but a successful
defense of the area was mounted by U.S. soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Sitter later was presented the Medal of Honor by President
Truman and is expected to be buried at Arlington National Cemetery.
William S. Street:
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- William S. ''Bill'' Street, a department store
executive who served as chairman of the 1962 world's fair and led
safaris in search of rare mammals after he retired, died Sunday of
Alzheimer's disease. He was 95.
</P>
<P>
   In 1924,he left college in to work at Hale Bros. stores in San
Francisco and Los Angeles and later became president of Frederick &AMP;
Nelson and a vice president of the parent company at the time,
Marshall Field and Co. of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   After serving as vice president of the Seattle Chamber of
Commerce, he retired from Frederick &AMP; Nelson to become chairman and
chief promoter of Century 21, the world's fair in Seattle in 1962.
The next year he became president of United Pacific, later Univar,
which had interests in real estate, chemicals and other areas.
Anna Bell Washington:
</P>
<P>
   ST. SIMONS ISLAND, Ga. (AP) -- Anna Bell Washington, whose
paintings depicted the life of blacks in the rural South, died
Monday. She was 75.
</P>
<P>
   The artist, who signed her works Ana Bel Lee, created vibrant
oil paintings that portrayed daily life, including a midwife
walking along a dirt path, a church wedding party, a baptism on a
creek bank or neighbors gathering for an oyster roast.
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit native retired to St. Simons in 1984 after a 38-year
career in social work in Michigan.
</P>
