<HEADLINE> Mich. Newspaper Probed Over Ads  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN FLESHER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHEBOYGAN, Mich. (AP) -- Police are investigating allegations
that the Cheboygan Daily Tribune gave a candidate for mayor special
deals on campaign advertisements, authorities said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper's publisher, Roy Trahan, said he could not comment
on the investigation on advice from the paper's lawyers, but he
confirmed police executed a search warrant at the Tribune offices
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our concern is there may be a much larger political picture
here,'' Trahan told The Associated Press. He would not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Police Chief Kurt Jones said his office received a complaint
about the alleged special treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily Tribune reported Wednesday that one of its employees
had made the complaint. Neither Trahan nor Jones would identify the
person.
</P>
<P>
   ''We opened an investigation. We are collecting evidence to
determine whether it's true or not,'' Jones said. No charges have
been filed.
</P>
<P>
   Police are investigating whether mayoral challenger Tom Verwys
received a cheaper rate than incumbent Mayor Bill Chlopan. Chlopan
defeated Verwys on Monday 373 to 205.
</P>
<P>
   The Michigan Campaign Finance Act requires that if media grant
any discounts, they must go to all candidates in a race, according
to Liz Boyd, a spokeswoman with the secretary of state's office.
</P>
<P>
   Corporations that violate the act can be fined up to $10,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
