<HEADLINE> Jailed Mexican Peasant Wins Prize  </HEADLINE>
By AMPARO TREJO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- The imprisoned leader of a Mexican peasant
group has been awarded an environmental prize for his efforts to
protect forests in the western state of Guerrero.
</P>
<P>
   Rodolfo Montiel, 44, the leader of a band of ''peasant
ecologists'' that battled against forest companies, received the
$125,000 Goldman Environmental Prize.
</P>
<P>
   Montiel says he was arrested, tortured and jailed on trumped-up
drug and weapons charges last year in retaliation for his efforts
to protect the trees. Human rights groups have backed his claims.
</P>
<P>
   Local authorities have said that Montiel and his supporters were
protecting marijuana fields, not the environment. Montiel and
members of his group have denied that.
</P>
<P>
   The group formed in February 1998 after rivers and streams were
drying up due to excess logging, Montiel told The Associated Press
in an interview earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   His group would form human chains to stop logging trucks,
sometimes threatening to burn the trucks and their shipments of
old-growth pine and fir. Most of the group's leaders were
eventually forced to flee and Montiel and another member of the
group, Teodoro Cabrera, were arrested May 2.
</P>
<P>
   The human rights group Amnesty International and the
environmental group Sierra Club have been campaigning for the
release of the Montiel and Cabrera.
</P>
<P>
   The award is one of six that the San Francisco-based Goldman
Environmental Foundation gives annually to environmentalists from
around the world to give them the ''recognition, visibility, and
credibility their efforts deserve.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-05-00 2304 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000405.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 23:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Transportation Bill Proposed  </HEADLINE>
By STEVE LAWRENCE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- In an effort to loosen California's
notorious traffic gridlock, Gov. Gray Davis on Wednesday proposed
spending $5.2 billion on transportation projects around the state.
</P>
<P>
   The plans range from a new ferry on San Francisco Bay to a study
on a proposed 700-mile high-speed rail system.
</P>
<P>
   Davis spokesman Michael Bustamante said the plan would slow the
spread of gridlock as California's population climbs.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are in some cases easing congestion and in some cases all
we can do is break even,'' he said. ''Did Governor Davis create
congestion? No. Is he going to solve congestion? No. But it will
certainly make the situation better.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis proposes spending $4.7 billion for a variety of rail, bus
and highway projects, including $1.5 billion in the San
Francisco-San Jose area, $2.24 billion in the Los Angeles area,
$481 million in the San Diego area, and $518 million in the Central
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   He recommends spending $500 million to ease a backlog in road
maintenance and asks lawmakers to allocate $5 million to begin
environmental studies for a high-speed rail system that would link
Sacramento, San Francisco, Los Angeles and San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would be funded in part with $3 billion from the
state's largest budget account, the general fund, that would be
spread over four years, and $2.2 billion from a bond measure that
Davis wants to put on the November ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The plan drew criticism earlier this week from Democratic Senate
leader John Burton and Republican Assembly Minority Leader Scott
Baugh, who said it failed to address long-term needs.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal now goes before the state Legislature.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
