<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 23:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore: Remember the Previous Bush  </HEADLINE>
By ALICE ANN LOVE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Al Gore told union members on Wednesday that
electing George W. Bush would mean a return to the economic hard
times of Bush's father's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ''We face an opportunity to build on today's prosperity, use it
to make sure no one is left behind, or to choose the other
direction, which would mean a right wing U-turn back to the
Bush-Quayle deficits, the Bush-Quayle recession, the Bush-Quayle
assault on working families,'' said Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Workers and union leaders who gathered for a meeting of the
Construction and Building Trades Department of the AFL-CIO, which
has endorsed Gore for the presidency, welcomed the vice president
with raucous applause and shouts encouraging him to be a
''Bushwhacker.''
</P>
<P>
   In a wide-ranging speech, Gore conspicuously avoided a sore
point in his relationship with the labor movement: U.S.-China trade
relations. The AFL-CIO is helping to mobilize demonstrators for a
march on Washington next week against the World Trade Organization
and Clinton administration policy, including permanent normal trade
status for China.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in his only reference to trade, said ''I will fight to
keep our prosperity going, which means keeping our budget balanced
and paying down our national debt, (and) fighting for free and fair
trade because open markets can create high-paying jobs for our
people here at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore focused on domestic issues instead, including the nation's
booming economy, which has had record expansion during the Clinton
administration, with unemployment reaching its lowest in three
decades. A recession had just started to lift when Clinton won the
White House from George Bush in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ''Don't let anybody ever forget what the contrast has been these
last seven years compared to the Bush-Quayle years,'' said Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also attacked the younger Bush's record as Texas governor
and his proposals for the White House. He said Bush would raise the
retirement age and divert public education money into
private-school vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   ''You shouldn't be asked by Governor Bush or anyone else to keep
carrying bricks or pouring cement until you're 70 years of age.
Give me a break. Talk about being out of touch,'' Gore told the
crowd of construction workers.
</P>
<P>
   Texas ranks 48th in the nation in the percentage of high school
students who go on to graduate from college, Gore said. The vice
president said anew that he would devote federal money to school
renovation and construction and to hire more teachers if he is
elected.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign on Wednesday released a statement
counterattacking Gore on education, saying that nationally test
scores have not improved among poor and minority students during
the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ''After having had eight years to lead, Al Gore fails to make
the grade,'' said Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls show the two candidates are evenly matched with
voters.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said running against Bush is a ''real close, hard-fought,
neck and neck race,'' but added, ''We have a choice that is as
stark a contrast, that is as clear as any we have ever faced in an
election year.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was tending to state business in Austin, Texas, on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Raking in $600,000 for the Democratic National Committee at an
evening dinner in Annapolis, Md., Gore summed up the Republican
Party's economic message as, ''Let's abandon what has worked so
spectacularly well.''
</P>
<P>
   In order to visit a sick friend, he scuttled plans to fly from
Annapolis to North Carolina. His campaign schedule is to resume
Thursday evening in Florida, with events Thursday and Friday in
Palm Beach, Fort Lauderdale and Tampa. Gore's visit to the Marie G.
Davis Middle School in Charlotte, N.C., was being rescheduled for
April 13, a spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who has been courting political independents as well as
traditional supporters such as union members, also will meet next
week with Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura, the nation's best-known independent officeholder, will
travel to Washington for the meeting next Wednesday hoping ''to get
the ear of the vice president on federal priorities for the
state,'' spokesman John Wodele said.
</P>
<P>
   The two met in Minnesota last month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
