<HEADLINE> Protesters Gather at Cemetary  </HEADLINE>
By TOM HARRIGAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Family members and protesters gathered
Wednesday outside the padlocked gate of a cemetery the state closed
after finding human remains scattered above ground.
</P>
<P>
   An inspection in February revealed that graves at Woodlawn
Cemetery in Compton had been dug up and new coffins placed on top
of old ones.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were told on Saturday by a state official that cemetery was
full in 1968, and they shouldn't have been burying anybody there
since then,'' said Lawanda Hawkins, one of about 20 protesters.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Consumer Affairs obtained a court order to
have the cemetery closed, saying it ''unlawfully converted single
burial graves to multiple graves, disturbed previously interred
remains and then failed to properly reinter all of the remains
during these conversions.''
</P>
<P>
   The cemetery will remain shut pending administrative hearings on
whether the company that runs it, Evergreen Memorial Care Inc.,
should hold a license to operate.
</P>
<P>
   The phone number for the cemetery office has been disconnected,
and phone calls made to Evergreen Memorial Care after business
hours Wednesday night were not answered.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're doing everything we can to make sure justice is
served,'' said department spokeswoman Tracee Weatherby. ''We are
returning every call that is received. People are asking if the
graves of their loved ones were involved.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.dca.ca.gov/press--releases/000328.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
