<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Fall  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell moderately Thursday morning
carrying over weakness on Wall Street. The dollar was lower against
the yen.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 120.72 points,
or 0.59 percent, to 20,342.05 at the end of the morning session. On
Wednesday, the average closed down 132.16 points, or 0.64 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar bought 104.72 yen in late morning trading, down 0.38
yen from late Wednesday in Tokyo but above its late New York level
of 104.66 yen.
</P>
<P>
   On the stock market, the Nikkei index moved lower as investors
remained cautious amid recent volatile trading in New York.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 130.92
points to 11,033.92 at Wednesday's close. But the Nasdaq composite
index gained 20.33 to 4,169.22.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was down 18.48 points, or 1.09 percent, to 1,676.57.
The TOPIX closed down 19.24 points, or 1.12 percent, the day
before.
</P>
<P>
   In currency dealings, the dollar came under some selling
pressure amid expectations Japan's economy will continue to recover
under new Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori.
</P>
<P>
   A ruling party insider, he was elected Wednesday to replace
Keizo Obuchi, who remains in a coma and on life support at a Tokyo
hospital after suffering a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said many investors were avoiding making significant
moves ahead of a meeting of finance officials of the Group of Seven
industrialized nations late next week. Finance Ministers and
central bankers from the United States, Japan, Britain, France,
Germany, Italy and Canada are scheduled to meet in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 100.83 yen, down
from 101.44 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell
to 1.7700 percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.7750 percent. Its
price rose 0.05 point to 101.12.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
